period. Based on the user input system will run a query to the tables and display the period information in search restuls grid.',NULL,'2011-06-06 09:36:57','2011-06-07 08:01:40',0),(24,'Manage Repeating Period: Advanced Search',19,'lbo','Lets the user execute advanced queries based on logical operators and wildcards.\r\nSearch can be executed using the following parameters\r\n    Name : Name of the Period, it is a text box\r\n    Period Type : Type of the period, It is choice list field with Daily, Weekly, Monthly, Semi-Monthly types.\r\n    What type of the Month? / How long is the period? choice list will be displayed based on the Period Type Selection \r\n    Description : Description of the period is text box\r\n    Also allows wildcards in Name and Description based search\r\n    These operators will give flexiblity to search on text box columns \r\n\r\n      These are fields with any character data type (CHAR, VARCHAR2) or fields that store documents.\r\n          * Starts With searches for records where the first characters match the given text string.\r\n          * Ends With searches for records where the last characters the given text string.\r\n          * Equals searches for records that match the text string exactly (ignoring case).\r\n          Replaces the \'Is\' operator in BLAF 3.x.\r\n          * Does Not Equal searches for records that do not match the text string exactly (ignoring case).\r\n          Replaces the \'Is Not\' operator in BLAF 3.x.\r\n          * Contains searches for records that contain the given text string.\r\n          Oracle Text and OSES Contains operator\r\n          SQL LIKE operator\r\n          * Does Not Contain searches for records that do not contain the given text string.\r\n          Not supported for SQL search.\r\n          Not recommended for Oracle Text and OSES driven search for performance reasons.\r\n          Use only if there is a strong use case approved by Apps UX and Performance.\r\n          * Is Blank searches for records that do not have a value (i.e. are null).\r\n          When Is Blank is chosen, the value field is hidden.\r\n          * Is Not Blank searches for records that have any value (i.e. are not null).\r\n          When Is Not Blank is chosen, the value field is hidden. ',NULL,'2011-06-06 09:38:15','2011-06-07 08:02:47',0),(25,'Manage Repeating Period: Search Grid Results',19,'lbo','Results of basic/advanced search\r\n\r\nGenerated basic/advanced search results will be displayed in this table, it contains Period Name, Period Type and Description of the Period.\r\n\r\nResults table also displays seed data.',NULL,'2011-06-06 09:38:43','2011-06-07 08:02:58',0),(26,'Manage Repeating Period: Actions - Create',19,'lbo','\'Create\' action or \'Create\' button from the Search Results grid are used to create new repeating periods. ',NULL,'2011-06-06 09:39:54','2011-06-07 08:03:18',0),(27,'Manage Repeating Period: Actions - Edit',19,'lbo','Only the name of a repeating period can be edited, the other fields will be grayed out in read only mode to protect the period. ',NULL,'2011-06-06 09:40:06','2011-06-07 08:03:26',0),(28,'Manage Repeating Period: Actions - Done',19,'lbo','Done button navigates the user to the main FSM page',NULL,'2011-06-06 09:40:55','2011-06-07 08:03:36',0),(29,'Create Period',19,'lbo','When using the Create action or Create button from the Search Results grid, user will be able to add a new Repeating Period in a new window.\r\n\r\nThis page is divided into two main sections, Define Period and Test Period. The Define Period section allows the user to create repeating period of choice, the choices are Monthly, Semi-monthly (every 15 days), Weekly and Daily. Each of these options provide relevant suboptions. The suboptions are to further define chosen time period type. For example, \"Weekly\" would provide option to pick if the repeating period length is 1 week, 2 weeks or n weeks, where n is chosen by the user.\r\n\r\nThe \"Test Period\" section allows for the user to preview the repeating period generated for the chosen Define Period selection.\r\n\r\nThe Define Period section also has little \"Usage\" section that displays read only text informing user of allowed applications of the period, ex: Timecard Periods, Timecard Rules.\r\n\r\nThe Define Period Section and Test Period Section also has Embedded help messages to understand the column usage.',NULL,'2011-06-06 09:41:52','2011-06-07 08:08:55',0),(30,'Create Period: Define Period',19,'lbo','This section allows user to define a repeating period and has the following columns.\r\n\r\nName : Name is a text column that user can choose to enter a customized name for the period. It allows upto 120 characters input. Ex: Monthly Time Period\r\n\r\nDescription: Description is also a text column for user to enter any text up to 1000 chars that describes the period definition. Ex: This is a monthly time period with period duration of one month\r\n\r\nPeriod Type: Period Type is a Choicelist, with following options. Daily, Weekly, Monthly and Semi-Monthly.\r\n\r\nBased on PeriodType choicelist selection below subsection will be displayed',NULL,'2011-06-06 09:42:12','2011-06-07 08:09:04',0),(31,'Create Period: Define Period - Daily Period Type',19,'lbo','Tracks Period in units of days\r\n\r\nWhen user selects \"Daily\", it further display the following options\r\n\r\n   1. One Day - Creates repeating period with period duration of exactly one day\r\n   2. More Than One Day - This selection pops up two more boxes, one to enter the duration of the period in units of days and other is for user to enter reference date. The reference date serves as reference point which helps calculate next and previous beginning dates in the repeating sequence.\r\n      Ex: Period type: Daily\r\n          How long is the period: More than One Day\r\n          How many Days : 5 - Period repeates every 5 days\r\n          Reference Date of the Period - Jan 1 2010. Sequence: ...Dec 22, 2010, Dec 27, 2010, Jan 1, 2011, Jan 6, 2011, Jan 11, 2011 ..',NULL,'2011-06-06 09:42:40','2011-06-07 08:09:28',0),(32,'Create Period: Define Period - Weekly Period Type',19,'lbo','Tracks Period in units of Weeks\r\n\r\nWhen user selects \"Weekly\", the following options are displayed\r\n\r\n   1. One Week - Period duration is exactly one week\r\n   2. Bi-weekly - Duration of the period is 14 days\r\n   3. More than Two Weeks - Provides the following options\r\n      Ex: Period type: Weekly\r\n          How many Weeks : 3\r\n          Reference Date of the Period - Jan 1 2010. Sequence is: ....Nov 20, 2009, Dec 11, 2009, Jan 1, 2010, Jan 22, 2010, Feb 12, 2010, Mar 5, 2010, ....\r\n\r\n      This table is an example of test period results ',NULL,'2011-06-06 09:43:07','2011-06-07 08:09:38',0),(33,'Create Period: Define Period - Monthly Period Type',19,'lbo','Tracks Period in units of Months\r\n\r\nWhen user selects \"Monthly\", the following options are displayed\r\n\r\n   1. Calendar Month - Period duration is exactly one calender month, asks for Reference Date\r\n   2. Quarter - Period duration is 3 months, asks for Reference Date.\r\n   3. Semi-Year - Period duration is 6 calender months, also asks for Reference Date\r\n   4. Year - Period duration is one calender year, asks for Reference Date.\r\n   5. Multiple Months - Custom period in units of months. Provides 2 columns for user to enter duration in months and Reference Date\r\n      Ex: Period type: Monthly\r\n          What type of month: Multiple Months\r\n          How many Months : 4\r\n          Reference Date of the Period - Jan 12 2010. Sequence of period start dates is: ....Sep 12, 2009, Jan 12, 2010, May 12, 2010, Sep 12, 2010, ..... Code handles leap year February',NULL,'2011-06-06 09:43:43','2011-06-07 08:09:50',0),(34,'Create Period: Define Period - SemiMonthly Period Type',19,'lbo','Tracks Period in units of 15 days\r\n\r\nWhen user makes this selection, it expects the user to fill the Reference Date.\r\nEx: Period type: Semi-Monthly\r\n    Reference Date of the Period - Jan 12 2010',NULL,'2011-06-06 09:44:13','2011-06-07 08:10:02',0),(35,'Create Period: Usage',19,'lbo','Usage: This section will help user to understand where all defined periods are used.\r\n\r\nEx: Timecard periods, Timecard Rules and Approval Periods\r\n\r\nUsage will get displayed after user defines the preriod.\r\nBy default, all fields will be selected and read only. Only in the following conditions will the \"Timecard Periods\" checkbox not be selected\r\n    Daily Period - any period greater than 31 days\r\n    Weekly Period - any period greater than 4 weeks\r\n    Monthly Period - any month type except \"Calendar Month\"\r\n\r\nThe reason for this limitation is for timecard intra-period navigation and for ease of use and application of rules.',NULL,'2011-06-06 09:44:39','2011-06-07 08:10:12',0),(36,'Create Period: Test Period',19,'lbo','This section will provide the user to see how the period gets generated with the defined information.\r\n\r\nUser can test the period by providing start date and end date and hitting on Generate Test Period button.\r\n\r\nIt contains a subsection of \'View Generated Period Results\' to display the test results in calendar view or tabular view based on the user selection.\r\n\r\nExample:\r\nGenerated results in table view\r\nStart Date 	End Date\r\nMonday 5th Jan 2008 	Sunday 11th Jan 2008\r\nMonday 12th Jan 2008 	Sunday 18th Jan 2008\r\nMonday 19th Jan 2008 	Sunday 25th Jan 2008\r\nGenerated results in calendar view\r\n\r\nThis section will include calendar view of the test results.\r\n\r\nCalendar View will show 3 months at a time, scroll to left or right to view more months. Default to display first 3 months from \"Test Time Period Start Date\"',NULL,'2011-06-06 09:45:09','2011-06-07 08:10:30',0),(37,'Create Period: Save and Close',19,'lbo','Save and Close action will insert rows into the Repeating Period tables and exits the Create screen ',NULL,'20