"39\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"TOC Heading\"/>\r\n </w:LatentStyles>\r\n</xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 10]>\r\n<style>\r\n /* Style Definitions */\r\n table.MsoNormalTable\r\n	{mso-style-name:\"Table Normal\";\r\n	mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0;\r\n	mso-tstyle-colband-size:0;\r\n	mso-style-noshow:yes;\r\n	mso-style-priority:99;\r\n	mso-style-qformat:yes;\r\n	mso-style-parent:\"\";\r\n	mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;\r\n	mso-para-margin:0in;\r\n	mso-para-margin-bottom:.0001pt;\r\n	mso-pagination:widow-orphan;\r\n	font-size:11.0pt;\r\n	font-family:\"Calibri\",\"sans-serif\";\r\n	mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;\r\n	mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;\r\n	mso-fareast-font-family:\"Times New Roman\";\r\n	mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast;\r\n	mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri;\r\n	mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;\r\n	mso-bidi-font-family:\"Times New Roman\";\r\n	mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-bidi;}\r\n</style>\r\n<![endif]-->\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-left: 0in;\"><span class=\"BodyTextChar\">All\r\nfields are grayed out except Period Name.<span style=\"\">&nbsp;\r\n</span>This is to protect the period definition, since it is immediately built\r\nout upon save.<span style=\"\">&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><b style=\"\">The user will not see the graying out of the fields unless they come\r\nback into the period definition in edit mode.</b></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-left: 0in;\"><span class=\"BodyTextChar\"><span style=\"\">&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Period instances are\r\nautomatically generated behind the scenes for use in all relevant\r\nfeatures.<span style=\"\">&nbsp; </span>To be determined in technical\r\ndesign the actual duration of period instances built out.<span style=\"\">&nbsp; </span>This may be for six months or more, before\r\nand after System Date.<span style=\"\">&nbsp; </span>The system will\r\nalways automatically generate the period instances needed for time entry, rules\r\nand approval processing.<span style=\"\">&nbsp; </span>The user never\r\nhas to manually build period calendars.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-left: 0in;\"><span class=\"BodyTextChar\"><span style=\"\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><br></p>Cancel - brings you back to the Manage Repeating Periods search/search result page','2011-05-31 20:54:21','2011-06-07 23:09:28',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1546,180,'Action Menu','Action Menu - Create New (w/Icon), Update (w/Icon), Duplicate (w/Icon), Details (w/Icon),&nbsp; Delete (w/Icon) <br><br>Create (New) Icon- to Questionaire<br><br>Update (Edit) Icon - to Task List - to Questionnaire (read-only mode)<br>(If not highlighting a line - then message to select layout to edit )<br><br> \r\n Duplicate - to Questionaire then on to task list and other pages <br>\r\n If not highlighting a line - then message to select layout to duplicate <br><br>Delete Icon - <br>\r\n If not highlighting a line - then message to select layout to duplicate <br class=\"atl-forced-newline\">\r\nIf not linked <br><br><font color=\"#ff0000\">View Details</font>&nbsp;&nbsp; (OPEN ISSUE - JF to resolve with Joel&nbsp; - not in Use case 1)<br><font color=\"#ff0000\">Icon / Action item to display additional information for the Layout Set selected.&nbsp; Information to include:</font>\r\n<ul><li><font color=\"#ff0000\">List of Layout Components used</font></li><li><font color=\"#ff0000\">Applications selected when adding attributes&nbsp;</font></li><li><font color=\"#ff0000\">Setup Option Profiles that use the Layout Set</font></li><li><font color=\"#ff0000\">Currently deployed</font></li><li><font color=\"#ff0000\">Different Page configurations (Modified CLA page, Manager Page differences, Override of rules attribute)</font></li></ul>\r\n <font color=\"#ff0000\">(Button) - Navigate to Layout Components<br></font><table class=\"confluenceTable\"><tbody><tr><td class=\"confluenceTd\"> <br></td>\r\n<td class=\"confluenceTd\"> <font color=\"#ff0000\">Maybe a good option \r\nwould be to provide a navigation from the Time Entry Matrix setup, when \r\nthe user is adding layout component to the matrix, we could offer to \r\ncreate a new component from the matrix setup, depending on privilege \r\nassigned to the users.</font> </td></tr></tbody></table><br>','2011-05-31 21:00:33','2011-06-10 21:55:11',1,'Must Have','','UI'),(1547,185,'Edit Repeating Period page','1.  Page Name: Edit Repeating Period: \"Period name\"\r\n<br><br>2.  The only editable field in an existing period isT is the period name. ','2011-05-31 21:03:31','2011-06-07 21:24:08',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1549,186,'Basic and Advanced Search','Page Action = Done - this will return the user to the Time and Labor Tasklist in the Functional Setup Manager\r\n<br><br>Basic Search fields:								\r\n<br>• Time Consumer Set Name							\r\n<br>• Description  - user defined description of the time consumer set\r\n\r\n - <br><br>Saved Searches Box\r\n - <br>Buttons for Search: Search/ Reset/ Save\r\n<br><br>Advanced Search Fields:	<br>							\r\n• Time Category Name – smart choicelist of all time categories, with a default of “All Time Entry”	\r\n\r\n<br>• Validate on Save - Yes/No choicelist<br>&nbsp;• Time Required – Yes/No choicelist						\r\n• <br><br>Approval Period- choice list of all repeating time periods\r\n\r\n<br><br>• Approval Transaction Type-  different AMX approval transaction types associated to the Timecard\r\n<br><br>Operator – this field is coupled with all of the advanced search fields, to allow more flexibility to search \r\n<br><br>The options for the operator values are:	<br>\r\n•	Greater than\r\n<br>•	Equals\r\n<br>•	Does Not Equal\r\n<br>•	Less Than\r\n<br>•	Greater Than\r\n<br>•	Between\r\n<br>•	Not Between\r\n<br>•	Is Blank\r\n<br>•	Is Not Blank<br>&nbsp;Also allow for wildcard search in each field.<br><br>&nbsp;- Saved Searches Box\r\n - <br>Buttons for Search: Search/ Reset/ Save/ Add Fields','2011-05-31 21:23:14','2011-06-07 23:21:34',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1550,167,'Rule when Attributes Seen / Updated differ from Ind and Mgr ','Rule to determine how / when the Worker can update an entry made by the Manager that has more attributes than the Workers Layout can update.\r\n\r\n','2011-05-31 21:42:50','2011-05-31 21:43:54',1,'Must Have','','Business Rule'),(1551,186,'Search Grid Results ','The 2 columns for the search results grid are :\r\n\r\n<br><br>Search Results: <br>Time Consumer Set\r\nName\r\n<br>Description\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>o  The search results should initially default to the last 10 time consumer sets created.  There will be seeded sets which will also be listed\r\n\r\n - Columns should be sortable\r\n\r\n','2011-05-31 21:46:05','2011-06-07 23:19:43',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1552,187,'Set Definition','The 2 fields for this section should be:\r\n<br>\r\nName<br>Description','2011-05-31 22:38:46','2011-06-07 23:01:39',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1553,187,'Select Time Consumers','The section title should be : Select Time Consumers\r\n<br><br>1.  Will have 2 checkboxes to select from : Payroll and Projects<br><br>&nbsp;2.  Instruction text information:  \"Select time consumers to create your set.\"','2011-05-31 22:38:56','2011-06-07 23:01:51',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1555,187,'Time Consumer: Payroll','Time Category Name = Any time category can be selected from the related smart choice list.   <br><br>Default  value  is “All Time Entry”.  <br><br>The time category selected denotes what attributes of time are to be sent to the time consumer.  For example, Payroll may not want time entries reported against Project values, so may enter a time category which excludes Projects related attributes.  This field needs explanation for the user to let them know that this Time Category value represents all timecard fields which the time consumer cares to see about retrieval of timecards via retrieval services.\r\n\r\n<br><br>Validate on Save = Yes/No Field with Default Value= Yes.  This field determines if the Payroll delivered validations will be executed upon save of the timecard.\r\n<br><br>Time Required = Yes/No field with Default Value=Yes.  This field determines if a timecard is always required by Payroll for every time period.  This field can help determine if a timecard is deemed “missing” for a given time period.\r\n<br><br>Approval Period = User can select from a smart choice list of repeating time periods which can be used as approval periods.  This approval period is the period in which time would be routed for approval once the period has been met.<br><br>&nbsp;Approval Transaction Type – Auto Approval by Source and AMX defined approval transactions will be possible choices.  To be finalized in technical design of Approvals LBA.\r\n<br><br>OTL to BEE Transfer Statuses *<br>&nbsp;• Timecard is:  Radio buttons with options of Saved or Submitted.  This field represents in which state a timecard can be transferred to Payroll’s interface table<br>.  \r\n• Approval Required By: Checkboxes for Payroll and Projects.  This field represents if the timecard must be approved by both Payroll and/or Projects before the timecard can be transferred to Payroll.<br><br>&nbsp;*Note:  We will validate with Core Payroll Team that this is still an appropriate label for the transfer of timecards to Payroll process.\r\n','2011-05-31 22:40:03','2011-06-07 23:03:18',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1556,187,'Time Consumer: Projects','Time Category Name = Any time category can be selected from the related smart choice list. <br>  Default  value  is “All Time Entry”. <br> The time category selected denotes what attributes of time are to be sent to the time consumer.  For example, Projects may not want time entries reported against Hours Type values, so may enter a time category which excludes Payroll related attributes.\r\n<br><br>Validate on Save = Yes/No Field with Default Value=No.<br>&nbsp;This field determines if the Projects delivered validations will be executed upon save of the timecard.\r\n\r\n<br><br>Time Required = Yes/No field with Default Value=Yes.  This field determines if a timecard is always required by Projects for every time period.  This field can help determine if a timecard is deemed “missing” for a given time period.<br><br>&nbsp;Approval Period = User can select from a smart choice list of repeating time periods which can be used as approval periods.  This approval period is the period in which time would be routed for approval once the period has been met.\r\n\r\n<br><br>Approval Transaction Type – Auto Approval by Source and AMX defined approval transactions will be possible choices.  To be finalized in technical design of Approvals LBA.\r\n\r\n<br><br>Transaction Import Transfer Statuses *\r\n<br>•  Timecard is:  Radio buttons with options of  Saved or Submitted.  This field represents in which state a timecard can be transferred to Projects’ interface table.<br>&nbsp;•  Approval Required By: Checkboxes for each time consumer selected in the Time Consumer Set.  For example,  Payroll and Projects.  This field represents if the timecard must be approved by other time consumers, before the timecard can be transferred to Projects.<br><br>&nbsp;*Note:  We will validate with Projects Team that this is still an appropriate label for the transfer of timecards to Projects .\r\n','2011-05-31 22:40:18','2011-06-07 23:04:23',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1557,132,'Search Grid Results','The columns for the search results need to be the following:<br><br>&nbsp;o	Name - User name for time period\r\n\r\n<br>o	Period Type - Daily, Weekly, Monthly, Semi-Monthly are the delivered types<br>&nbsp;o	Period Description– User entered description for the period<br><br>&nbsp;The search results should initially default to the last 10 repeating periods created.  There will be seeded repeating periods listed as well.\r\n','2011-05-31 23:19:06','2011-06-07 21:14:19',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1558,187,'Page Actions','Save - saves the page, offers a save confirmation, and remains on the current page.<br><br>Save and Close - saves the page and returns user to Manage Time Consumer Set page<br><br>Cancel - returns user back to Manage Time Consumer Set page<br>','2011-06-01 06:25:45','2011-06-07 23:06:17',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1559,187,'Default Values and Field Help','The following fields should have default values:\r\n <br><br>‘Time Required’ = “Yes” default value\r\n<br><br>‘Validate on Save’= “No” default value\r\n<br><br>‘Payroll’ and ‘Project Status’ = Approved<br><br><u>&nbsp;In Field Help Notes for the following fields\r\n</u><br><br>Time Category Name - Enter a time category of fields to be sent to this time consumer.\r\n\r\n<br><br>Validate on Save - Enables validations to run from the time consumer when a timecard is saved.\r\n<br><br>Time Required  -  Select this option if a timecard is required for every time period by this time consumer. Missing timecards can be tracked based on this selection.\'\r\n','2011-06-01 06:28:04','2011-06-07 23:01:04',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1560,188,'Allowed Edits','Page Name:  Edit Time Category: \"Category Name\"<br><br>&nbsp;1. Once in edit mode, the user cannot change the time consumers selected for the time consumer set, but can edit all other fields displayed for each time consumer. <br><br>2.  However, if the time consumer set is associated to an employee, it cannot be edited. A Time Consumer Set cannot be updated if in use.  (“In use” is defined as being assigned to an employee via Time and Labor Setup Options, or attached to a timecard.)\r\n  \r\n<br><br>3. If the user needs to have different time consumers in their set, they can create a new time consumer set.<br><br>&nbsp;4. There will be a seeded time consumer set including Payroll and Projects.\r\n','2011-06-01 06:29:19','2011-06-07 23:00:07',1,'Must Have','1','Business Rule'),(1561,189,'On Save of Time Consumer Set','If “Timecard Is” Saved is selected for Transfer Status, then the user must select “Validate on Save=Yes”. <br> There will be business logic to cross-validate this combination upon save of the time consumer set.<br><br>&nbsp;Time should be “stamped” as validated in the core timecard storage – “timestore” if “time not require validation” is selected in the Process Mode logic for the Load Process.<br><br>&nbsp;o  A Time Consumer cannot be deleted unless it is not in use.  (“In use” is defined as being assigned to an employee via Time and Labor Setup Options, or attached to a timecard.)\r\n\r\n<br><br>o  A Time Consumer Set cannot be updated unless it is not in use.  (“In use” is defined as being assigned to an employee via Time and Labor Setup Options, or attached to a timecard.)<br><br>&nbsp;ISSUE: During the TDD phase, it will be determined if the \"attached to a timecard\" check could be implemented (if too costly or not), but we surely need to consider it, as it will cause lot of problem if we have a timecard stamped with a \r\ntime consumer configuration set that does not exist anymore.\r\n\r\n','2011-06-01 06:31:44','2011-06-07 22:59:19',1,'Must Have','1','Business Rule'),(1562,126,'Search','Basic Search fields:\r\no	Time Category Name\r\no	Time Category Description\r\n\r\n- Saved Searches Box\r\n - Buttons for Search: Search/ Reset/ Save/ \r\n\r\n\r\nAdvanced Search Fields\r\no	Time Category Name\r\no	Time Category Description\r\no	Time Attribute field – any time attribute field which is specified in an existing time category\r\no	Usage\r\no	Time Attribute value\r\no	 Operator – this field is coupled with all of the advanced search fields, to allow more flexibility to search \r\nThe options for the operator values are:	\r\n•	Greater than\r\n•	Equals\r\n•	Does Not Equal\r\n•	Less Than\r\n•	Greater Than\r\n•	Between\r\n•	Not Between\r\n•	Is Blank\r\n•	Is Not Blank \r\n	Also allow for wildcard search in each field.\r\n\r\n- Saved Searches Box\r\n - Buttons for Search: Search/ Reset/ Save/ Add Fields\r\n','2011-06-01 06:41:14','2011-06-01 06:45:07',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1563,126,'Search Results Grid',NULL,'2011-06-01 06:41:25','2011-06-01 06:41:25',1,'Must Have',NULL,NULL),(1564,126,'Toolbar and Menubar Actions','Actions Menu\r\n\r\nCreate – create a new time category\r\nDelete – delete an existing time category, only if it is not currently used in another object such as rule or balance\r\nDuplicate – select an existing time category and duplicate it, changing the name and description.  All other values will copy over from the selected time category\r\nEdit  - select an existing time category for update\r\n\r\nToolbar Menu – following are the icons in the toolbar which represent the menu actions\r\n	Add\r\n	Delete\r\n	Duplicate\r\n	Edit	\r\n','2011-06-01 06:42:36','2011-06-01 06:46:41',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1565,190,'Accessibility Requirements','Although there are no visible column labels in the Condition pane, the following needs to be coded for accessibility requirements:\r\n\r\no  Field labels (for example, attribute, operator, and so on) are hidden but must be labeled. \r\n\r\no  Each row in the condition must be identified uniquely. \r\nExample:  Attribute: Row 1, Operator: Row 1 \r\n','2011-06-01 06:48:18','2011-06-01 06:48:59',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1566,190,'Summary Information','Section Name: Summary Information\r\n\r\no	Name: Time Category Name\r\no	Description: Time Category Description\r\n','2011-06-01 06:49:38','2011-06-01 06:50:45',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1567,190,'Condition Pane','Actions Menu \r\no	Add \r\no	Duplicate \r\n---------------- \r\no	Delete\r\n---------------- \r\no	Add Nest \r\no	Delete Nest \r\n\r\nActions Behavior\r\no	Add New Row (No Selection): A new row is inserted after the last row in the table. \r\no	Add New Row (Row Selected): A new row is added below the selected row. \r\no	Add New Row (Multiple Rows Selected): One new row is added below the last selected row. \r\no	Duplicate Row: The duplicate row is added below the selected row. \r\no	Duplicate Multiple Rows: The group of duplicated rows is added below the selected group. \r\no	Duplicate Noncontiguous Duplication: The group of duplicated rows is added below the selected row or group of rows.\r\nExample: If the user selects rows 2, 3, and 5, and then clicks the Duplicate icon, the duplicated rows appear below the 2 and 3 grouping and below row 5.  \r\no	Delete Row: Deletes the selected row from the table. All rows below it move up to fill the space. \r\no	Add Nest – to add a nested condtion with its own set of parentheses within an existing condition\r\no	Delete Nest – to select a nested condition and delete\r\n\r\nToolbar Icons \r\no	Add (   )   Add new row\r\no	Duplicate (   )   Duplicate selected row or rows\r\no	Delete (   )  Delete selected row or rows\r\n---------------- \r\no	Add Parentheses (   ): Nests and indents selected rows. \r\no	Delete Parentheses (   ): Deletes the nesting and indention of selected rows.\r\no	Up and Down Arrows – to allow the user to select a row and move it above or below another condition. \r\no	Import Time Category button – to allow the user to select a row and import a time category below that condition.  This allows the ability to bring into the current definition of a new time category, a pre-existing time category, i.e.  nest one time category within another.  Once an existing time category is imported into the current time category definition, it will be displayed in read-only format, along with its attribute fields and values.  This will protect the original definition of the nested time category. Insert Time Category action should be available at any level and part of collapsible section.\r\n\r\n\r\nFields displayed in the Condition Pane\r\n•	Row Selector: A check box and row highlighting is used to indicate selection for a given condition\r\n•	Parentheses:  Added before and after each condition grouping, different levels of parantheses based on nested conditions\r\n•	Time Attribute field: A smart choice list which contains a set of attributes defined within the Time and Labor data dictionary.  Examples of Time Attributes include Project ID, Hours Type, Task, Expenditure Type, Department, Customer.   Users cannot add new attributes to the choice list.   \r\n•	Condition:  A choice list of the following options for the conditions of the time attribute values to exist to trigger the time category:\r\no	Any Value\r\no	Empty Field (Null Value)\r\no	Value Set\r\no	Specific Value\r\n•	Time Attribute Value: A choice list of the values related to the selected time attribute field. \r\n•	Logical Operator: This combines two conditions to return a set of filtered results. \r\no	Values: AND or  OR \r\no	Set to AND by default. \r\no	This field should be hidden in the last row of the table \r\n\r\n•   Show/Hide Collapsible Sections – Each “first level” logic grouping identified with its set of  parentheses can be collapsed in a section, with a summary Comments field displayed, to make it easier to read the content of a time category which has multiple logic groupings.  The sub or indented logic will get included in the collapse or expansion of that section.  Each logic grouping should be collapsible to allow for a distinct summary of what each logic defines. The summary is provided by the Comments field.\r\n\r\n• Comments Field – should be 30 characters in length and part of collapsible section for logic grouping.  When the section is collapsed, this field is still open for display to the user.\r\n','2011-06-01 06:49:46','2011-06-01 06:56:42',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1568,190,'Page Actions','Validate:  The combination of conditions are checked to ensure the logic is grouped correctly\r\no  If errors are found, a message is displayed. \r\no  User can validate the condition at any time. \r\no  Validation is performed when the user clicks the Validate button or exits the page.\r\n Conditions should be verified to: \r\n Check that data has been entered into required fields. \r\n Check that a selection has been made in each of the Attribute, Operator, Value and Logical Operator fields. \r\n  Check that no invalid characters have been entered in the Value field. Invalid characters include: @, >, %, and so on. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSave: Saves the changes, updates the object information in the base table. \r\no  Condition are checked for errors. If errors are present a message is displayed. \r\no  The time category should not be saved with errors because then inaccurate time categories may be used\r\n\r\n\r\nSave and Close: Saves the changes and closes the window. \r\no  Conditions are checked for errors. If errors are present a message is displayed. \r\n \r\nCancel: Cancels the transaction, closes the page and returns user to the referencing page. \r\n','2011-06-01 06:49:54','2011-06-01 06:53:23',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1569,190,'View Resolved Time Category','View Resolved Time Category – (nice to have) this  last section will dynamically provide an“English” sentence which retrieves the selected Time Entry Attribute values and places them within the logic statement selected, with the use of “and” and “or” operator in between the value listing.  This sentence will get updated as the time entry attributes are associated to the appropriate logic columns.','2011-06-01 06:56:58','2011-06-01 06:57:37',1,'Nice to Have','2','UI'),(1570,191,'Edit Rule and Page','Page Name: Edit Time Category: \"Time Category Name\"\r\n\r\nEdit Rule:  All fields and behavior will be available for update in the Edit Time Category display.  ','2011-06-01 06:58:18','2011-06-01 06:59:27',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1571,197,'Basic and Advanced Search Section','A.   Basic/Advanced Search section of the Manage Worker Web Entry Profiles page:\r\n<br><br>Basic Search<br>&nbsp;•  Profile Name – name of the Setup Profile\r\n<br>•  Description – Setup Profile Description\r\n<br><br>- Saved Searches Box\r\n<br><br>Buttons for Basic Search	\r\n•	Search\r\n•	Reset\r\n•	Save\r\n<br><br>Advanced Search\r\n<br>•Profile Name – name of the Setup Profile\r\n<br>Description - Profile Description\r\n<br>•Setup Option Name – name of one of the Profile Value options contained in the Values section\r\n<br>•Setup Option Value – value of one of the Profile Value options contained in the Values section\r\n<br>•Precedence – precedence number of the Setup Profiles (there is a unique number precedence for each profile 	type)\r\n<br>•Group Association – choice list of HCM groups to which the setup profiles are assigned  (labeled as Group Name Assigned To in the prototy<br>pe)&nbsp; Saved Searches Box\r\n<br>\r\nAdditional Buttons for Advanced Search	\r\n•	Search\r\n•	Reset\r\n•	Save\r\n•	Add Fields\r\n','2011-06-01 07:12:58','2011-06-08 06:12:42',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1572,197,'Search Grid Results','Search Results Grid : Columns to be displayed:<br>&nbsp;•  Profile Name – name of the Setup Profile\r\n<br><br>•  Description – description for the Setup Profile<br><br>&nbsp;•  Precedence – overall precedence order this setup profile has <br><br>•  Group Usage – icon triggering a pop-up page displaying all groups to which this setup profile is attached, with a 	start and end date\r\n','2011-06-01 07:13:10','2011-06-08 06:12:57',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1574,199,'Basic and Advanced Search Section','A.   Basic/Advanced Search section of the Manage Worker Core Processing Setup Profiles page:\r\n<br>Basic Search\r\n<br>•  Profile Name – name of the Setup Profile<br>&nbsp;•  Description – Setup Profile Description\r\n\r\n  -<br>&nbsp;Saved Searches Box\r\n\r\n <br>Buttons for Basic Search	\r\n•	Search\r\n•	Reset\r\n•	Save\r\n\r\n<br><br>Advanced Search\r\n<br>•Profile Name – name of the Setup Profile\r\nDescription<br>&nbsp;- Profile Description\r\n<br>•Setup Option Name – name of one of the Profile Value options contained in the Values section<br>&nbsp;•Setup Option Value – value of one of the Profile Value options contained in the Values section\r\n<br>•Precedence – precedence number of the Setup Profiles (there is a unique number precedence for each profile 	type)\r\n<br>•Group Association – choice list of HCM groups to which the setup profiles are assigned  (labeled as Group Name Assigned To in the prototype)\r\n<br>\r\n\r\n  - Saved Searches Box\r\n\r\nAdditional Buttons for Advanced Search	\r\n•	Search\r\n•	Reset\r\n•	Save\r\n•	Add Fields\r\n','2011-06-01 07:17:11','2011-06-08 06:02:40',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1575,199,'Search Grid Results','Search Results Grid : Columns to be displayed:<br>&nbsp;•  Profile Name – name of the Setup Profile\r\n<br>•  Description – description for the Setup Profile\r\n<br>•  Precedence – overall precedence order this setup profile has \r\n<br>•  Group Usage – icon triggering a pop-up page displaying all groups to which this setup profile is attached, with a 	start and end date\r\n','2011-06-01 07:17:21','2011-06-08 06:01:46',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1577,201,'Basic and Advanced Search Section',NULL,'2011-06-01 07:18:40','2011-06-01 07:18:40',1,'Must Have',NULL,NULL),(1578,201,'Search Grid Results',NULL,'2011-06-01 07:18:49','2011-06-01 07:18:49',1,'Must Have',NULL,NULL),(1579,201,'Menubar and Toolbar Actions',NULL,'2011-06-01 07:19:00','2011-06-01 07:19:00',1,'Must Have',NULL,NULL),(1580,192,'Business Rules','o	Only one Time and Labor Setup Profile can be associated to an HCM Group at one time\r\n<br><br>o	A Setup Profile can be associated to more than one HCM Group\r\n<br><br>o	Setup Profiles cannot be deleted when assigned to a group(s) or people\r\n<br><br>o	Each Setup Profile (of a particular type) must have a unique precedence within the Enterprise\r\n<br><br>o	When saving a Setup Profile, there should be business logic to cross-validate the association of layout sets and public template sets to ensure they match.  If they don’t match, the system needs to issue an error messages that these 2 attributes do not match on the profile\r\n','2011-06-01 16:24:22','2011-06-08 05:10:07',1,'Must Have','1','Business Rule'),(1581,193,'Actions and Date Effectivity','The date effectivity is only for profile values, therefore the date effectivity will be implemented in the \"Set Profile Values\" train stop of each Setup Profile and only the \"Values\" section will have the date effectivity functionality enabled.<br><br>&nbsp;Following are the behaviors when an administrator creates, duplicates or updates a Setup Profile:\r\n\r\n<br><br>On Create, when user is creating a new profile option, he will navigate to the \" Set Profile Values \". In the values section the effective start date will be set to 01-01-1990, effective end date is blank.\r\n<br><br>On Duplicate, the logic will be the same as create but the setup profile values will be pre-populated with the value that you want to duplicate. We will duplicate the values from the setup profile the user wants to duplicate effective as \"Today\".  <br><br>We can also duplicate all of the record history of the setup profile values , the user can delete those additional effective dated records if he does not want to carry them over to the new profile.<br><br>&nbsp;On Update, when navigating to the \"Set Profile Values\" train stop, the values will be in read-only mode. The user will be able to select one of the following options:\r\no	 Correct :  The user will make a correction to Date Tracked row and all the values are now editable.\r\no	 Update:   In update mode, the effective start date popup window shows, user selects a date. He navigates back to the \"Set Profile Values\" and all the values are now editable.\r\no	 Delete Record:   The user deletes the current date tracked record. The rule will be to let the user delete records but one record must always be attached to the setup profile. \r\n','2011-06-01 16:25:33','2011-06-08 05:09:32',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1582,194,'Deriving Logic','There will be different setup profile types which will be resolved for the proper display and processing of timecards.<br><br>&nbsp;o	Worker Core Processing Setup Profile – will always need to be resolved for the proper display of timecard period and the application of rules, no matter which role is accessing the timecard\r\n<br><br>o	Worker Web Time Entry Setup Profile – will be resolved when the worker or manager accesses the timecard, for determining timecard access privileges, layout display and available public templates<br><br>.  \r\no	Group Time Entry Setup Profile – will be resolved for the user (timekeeper or manager) of the Group Time Entry feature for available layout sets, timecard access privileges and audit notification options.\r\n<br><br>For each of these setup profile types which need to be resolved, there is a process to derive the correct Setup option values  for the timecard period being accessed.\r\n\r\n<br><br>The profile option evalution on the opening of a timecard is as follows:\r\n<br><br>1.	Is there an individual profile assignment for the person? If so, use the Setup Profile from the individual assignment available in the Troubleshoot page of the Profile type. \r\n<br><br>2.	If no individual profile assignment, find the Groups the person belongs to for the range of dates we are interested in.<br><br>&nbsp;If the person does not belong to any groups, use the Default Setup Options.  There will be a seeded default setup profile which can be used as a backup to open a timecard for a person if no setup profile is yet assigned for them.<br><br>&nbsp;3.	Find the Setup Profiles that are linked to those Groups for the range of dates in question. <br><br>Where the person would be eligible for two or more Setup Profiles, use the precedence on the Setup Profile to decide which Setup Profile is to be used.  Higher numbers mean higher precedence. <br><br>Where the person is not eligible for any Setup Profiles (none of the Groups they belong to is assigned to a Setup Profile) then use the Default Setup Options. \r\n','2011-06-01 16:27:10','2011-06-08 05:07:16',1,'Must Have','1','Business Rule'),(1583,195,'Timecard Actions and Timecard Status','The control of security access to timecards will be defined in a Timecard Actions table embedded in the Worker Web Time Entry Setup Profile and the Group Web Time Entry Setup Profile.<br><br>&nbsp;It is a matrix which allows the setup administrator to determine what actions the user can take on the timecard and for what period of time.  In essence, these are access privileges.\r\n\r\n<br><br>The timecard actions which are displayed are the following:<br>&nbsp;o	Create\r\n<br>o	Delete<br>&nbsp;o	Edit\r\n<br>o	View Only\r\n\r\n<br><br>The create function simply offers the option of “enable” or not.  This means either the user can create or not create new timecards.  No timecard status is needed for this definition.<br><br>&nbsp;For the other timecard actions, (delete, edit, view only) ; there is a row for each timecard status, so the administrator can determine if the timecard user can take these actions on any or all of the following timecard statuses:\r\n<br><ul><li>&nbsp;\r\nSaved&nbsp;\r\n</li><li>&nbsp;Submitted\r\n</li><li>&nbsp;In Error<br></li><li>&nbsp;Rejected</li><li>&nbsp;	Approved</li><li>&nbsp;	Transferred</li><li>Pending Resolution</li></ul><br>&nbsp;In addition to allowing flexibility to define timecard actions per timecard status, the user also has the ability to define the access to timecards in the past or future.  <br><br>For each timecard status row, there are fields for “Number of Days Before” and “Number of Days After”.  These fields allow for the administrator to define the number of days before or after System Date that a timecard user can access a given timecard.<br><br>&nbsp;If the number of days falls in the middle of a timecard period, the user should be able to take the assigned actions for the whole timecard.<br><br>&nbsp;If Number of Days Before or Number of Days After fields are not populated with a number of days, then the user will have unlimited access to take selected actions on the current timecard.\r\n','2011-06-01 16:28:48','2011-06-08 05:04:48',1,'Must Have','1',''),(1584,196,'Restrict Prior Year Fields',' Customers may want to ensure that timecards from prior year is not updated, as there have been closing of financial books and year end payroll processing. <br><br>To support this requirement, additional flexibility for timecard actions would be to add the following two fields, to be associated for the worker, manager or timekeeper views of Timecard Actions:\r\n<br><br>\r\no	Restrict Prior Year Time Entry :  a Yes/No option to define if prior year access to timecards should be restricted\r\n<br><br>\r\no	Prior Year Ends In:   this choicelist would be listing all calendar months, as different customers have different definitions for their fiscal years.  Additionally, there should be an optional “date” field, if there is as specific date on which the fiscal year ends for the customer.\r\n\r\nIf a timecard should overlap two years, if the timecard begins in a prior year and the prior year is restricted, that timecard should be restricted from access.\r\n\r\n','2011-06-01 16:30:18','2011-06-08 04:58:44',1,'Should Have','2','Business Rule'),(1585,203,'3 Tabbed Display','There will be three types of setup profiles which a Time and Labor  administrator can associate to workers.<br><br>&nbsp;Each of these profile types will be displayed as tabs on the main page:\r\n<br><br>Page Name: Define Time and Labor Setup Profiles\r\n\r\n<br><br>Tab 1: Worker Core Processing Profiles\r\n<br>Tab 2: Worker Web Time Entry Profiles\r\n<br>Tab 3:  Group Web Time Entry Profiles<br><br>&nbsp;Page Action: Done Button<br>&nbsp;The Done button should bring the user back to where they were, in this case probably the Time and Labor tasklist in the Workforce Deployment offering in the Functional Setup Manager.\r\n<br><br>These three profile types will be part of a tasklist in FSM, with a taskgroup name of “Define Time and Labor Setup Profiles”.\r\nThese profiles will have different setup profile values,  but will be setup with the same steps of defining the setup profile values, defining the precedence of the profile,  assigning the profile to a group(s) , setting the profile precedence and reviewing the profile setup.<br><br>&nbsp;Worker Core Processing Profiles should be assigned to all workers who will have timecards, as these are the core processing rules for the timecard.<br><br>&nbsp;Worker Web Time Entry Profiles should be assigned to all workers, if either they or their managers will access their timecards. \r\n\r\n <br><br>Group Web Time Entry Profiles should be assigned to users who will be using the Group Time Entry feature for viewing, editing, deleting or creating timecards.  The majority of these users will be timekeepers.   The key access to Group Time Entry will be via Time Entry Groups.\r\n','2011-06-01 16:33:37','2011-06-07 23:54:28',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1586,197,'Troubleshoot Page','Page Name:  Worker Web Time Entry Setup  Profile:  Troubleshooting<br><br>&nbsp;Instructional text: You can troubleshoot the assignment of your profile in this page. You can assign profile directly to a person as an override to any group association. <br><br>First Section:\r\n\r\nSearch:  Worker<br>&nbsp;The top section of the page is a person search, with basic single search fields of person name, person number, location, person type, hire date and job code.<br><br>&nbsp;For the advanced search, there are operator fields and value fields.\r\n\r\nOperator – this field is coupled with all advanced search fields, to allow more flexibility to search.  After the operator, the value can then be entered or a wildcard search.\r\nThe options for the operator values are:	\r\n•	Greater than\r\n•	Equals\r\n•	Does Not Equal\r\n•	Less Than\r\n•	Greater Than\r\n•	Between\r\n•	Not Between\r\n•	Is Blank\r\n•	Is Not Blank \r\n\r\n<br><br>Second Section:\r\nGroup Membership and Associated Profiles\r\n<br>\r\nThe second section of the page lists  a table of the profiles (based on the tab type you are in) which the person is eligible for in a Setup Profiles/Groups table containing the columns:<br>&nbsp;• Precedence – Precedence Number of the Profile\r\n<br>• Profile Name – name of the Setup Profile\r\n<br>• Group List – Group names which are associated to this Setup Profile in alphabetical order\r\n\r\n<br><br>3rd Section:\r\n\r\nIndividual Assignment to Setup Profile\r\nInstructional text: You can assign a profile directly to the selected person, this assignment will override any other Profile association based on groups.\r\n<br>\r\nProfile Name ____   \r\n<br>Start Date  ______  \r\n<br>End Date    _______\r\n  <br>Save \r\n \r\n<br><br>4th Section\r\nSetup Option Values for : \"Worker Name\"\r\n\r\nList of Setup Profile Values<br>&nbsp;(displayed in read only mode from the highest precedence setup profile currently associated to this person)\r\n\r\nThis will be the setup option values from the Worker Web Time Entry Setup Profile\r\n \r\n\r\nPage Actions:  Save, Done, Cancel','2011-06-01 18:52:18','2011-06-08 06:11:33',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1588,204,'Edit Train Stops','All functionality for Create action is available to be changed in edit mode.\r\n\r\nPage Name for each tab should begin with \"Edit Worker Web Time Entry Profile: \"Profile Name\"','2011-06-02 08:07:33','2011-06-08 06:03:28',1,'Must Have','1','UI'),(1589,199,'Troubleshoot Page','Page Name:  Worker Web Time Entry Setup  Profile:  Troubleshooting<br><br>&nbsp;Instructional text: You can troubleshoot the assignment of your profile in this page. You can assign profile directly to a person as an override to any group association. <br><br>First Section:\r\n\r\nSearch:  Worker\r\n\r\nThe top section of the page is a person search, with basic single search fields of person name, person number, location, person type, hire date and job code.<br><br>&nbsp;For the advanced search, there are operator fields and value fields.<br><br>&nbsp;Operator – this field is coupled with all advanced search fi