:37:08'),(3150,'Feature',1203,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:08'),(3151,'Feature',1204,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:08'),(3152,'Feature',1205,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:08'),(3153,'Feature',1206,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:08'),(3154,'Feature',1207,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:08'),(3155,'Feature',1208,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:08'),(3156,'Feature',1209,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:08'),(3157,'Feature',1210,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:08'),(3158,'Feature',1211,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:08'),(3159,'Feature',1212,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:08'),(3160,'Feature',1213,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:08'),(3161,'Feature',1214,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:08'),(3162,'Feature',1215,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:08'),(3163,'Feature',1216,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:08'),(3164,'FunctionalWorkUnit',124,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:08'),(3165,'Feature',1217,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:08'),(3166,'Feature',984,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: No Name\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 984\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 108\ndescription: \"  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3167,'FunctionalWorkUnit',108,'destroy','1','--- \nname: \"Time and Labor Time Entry Group \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 108\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3168,'Feature',985,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Manage Time Category Page\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 985\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 109\ndescription: \"<p> Time Category search will allow for the access to time \\n                    categories as well as create, duplicate, view, edit or delete existing time categories<p>\\n                    <p>Must have features to support existing functionality:</p>\\n\\n     <p> Basic/Advanced Search Page for Time Categories</p>\\n\\\n  <p>Basic Search fields:</p>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>   Time Category Name</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    Time Category Description </li>\\n\\n\\\n  <p>Advanced Search Fields</p>\\n\\n\\\n  <li> Time Category Name</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li> Time Category Description</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li> Time Attribute field:  any time attribute field which is specified in an existing time category</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li> Usage</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li> Time Attribute value</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li> Operator: this field is coupled with all of the advanced search fields, to allow more flexibility to search</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <p>The options for the operator values are:</p>\\n    <li>Starts With: </li> searches for records where the first characters\\n       match the given text string.\\n     <li>Ends With: </li> searches for records where the last characters the\\n       given text string.\\n     <li>Equals: </li> searches for records that match the text string exactly\\n       (ignoring case).\\n       Replaces the \\xE2\\x80\\x9CIs\\xE2\\x80\\x9D operator in BLAF 3.x.\\n     <li>Does Not Equal: </li> searches for records that do not match the text\\n       string exactly (ignoring case).\\n       Replaces the \\xE2\\x80\\x9CIs Not\\xE2\\x80\\x9D operator in BLAF 3.x.\\n     <li>Contains: </li> searches for records that contain the given text string.\\n       Oracle Text and OSES Contains operator\\n       SQL LIKE operator\\n     <li>Does Not Contain: </li> searches for records that do not contain the\\n       given text string.\\n       Not supported for SQL search.\\n       Not recommended for Oracle Text and OSES driven search for\\n       performance reasons.\\n       Use only if there is a strong use case approved by Apps UX and\\n       Performance.\\n     <li>Is Blank: </li> searches for records that do not have a value (i.e.\\n       are null).\\n       When Is Blank is chosen, the value field is hidden.\\n     <li>Is Not Blank: </li> searches for records that have any value (i.e.\\n       are not null).\\n       When Is Not Blank is chosen, the value field is hidden.\\n\\\n  <br/><br/>\\n <p>Default Conditions for Text Fields:</p>\\n\\n     <li>Starts With: If search technology is SQL and widget is a Text\\n       Box or LOV. </li>\\n     <li>Contains: If Search Technology is Oracle Text or OSES and\\n       widget is a Text Box or LOV.</li>\\n     <li>Equals: If widget is a Choice List.</li>\\n\\n    Also allow for wildcard search in each field.\\n\\n\\\n  <p>Search Results Section:</p>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    Time Category Name- user defined name for time category</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    Usage: a hyperlinked list of Time Entry Rules, Time Calculation Rules or Time Audit Rules that contain this Time Category.  When clicking this hyperlink, a pop up page will provide details on the rules impacted.</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    Description: user defined description of the time category</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    The search results should initially default to the last 10 time categories created.  There will be seeded time categories which will also be listed</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    Actions Menu</li>\\n\\\n  <p>\\n\\\n  <li>  Create: create a new time category</li>\\n\\\n  <li>  Delete: delete an existing time category, only if it is not currently used in another object such as rule or balance</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>  Duplicate: select an existing time category and duplicate it, changing the name and description.  All other values will copy over from the selected time category</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>  Edit: select an existing time category for update. </li>\\n\\\n  </p>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    Toolbar Menu: following are the icons in the toolbar which represent the menu actions</li>\\n\\\n  <p>\\n\\\n  <li>  Add</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>  Delete</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>  Duplicate</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>  Edit   </li></p>   \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3169,'Feature',986,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Create Time Category Page\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 986\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 109\ndescription: \"<p> Time Categories can be simple listing of possible values entered in the timecard, or it can be a more complex combination of values that are used in a comparison.  These categories are used to trigger validations and rules on time entries, for summary timecard analytics, or for balances used in rules.   A time category itself can be a nested time category of other time categories.   In Fusion, the attributes available for compiling a time category will be time attribute fields or other time categories. <p>\\n                   <p>The time category definition requires the flexibility for a user to add as many conditions as they need to summarize time attributes.  It is also required to group these conditions into logical expressions, with comparisons between these expressions.  In order to offer this flexibility, we will use the Fusion Structured Condition Builder Guideline.  Reference to this Guideline: http://fusiongps.us.oracle.com/guidelines/content/guidelines/expressionbuilder/conditions/index.htm#StructuredCondition. Using this structured condition builder design approach will make it easier for users to uptake the feature, as they will have exposure to this design in other applications, such as AMX approval rules setup.<p>\\n                   <p>Create Time Category page</p>\\n\\n\\\n  <p>Create Time Category : Page Name</p>\\n\\n\\\n  <p>Tags: enable the web center icon to allow user to define tags on time categories</p>\\n\\n         <p>Summary Information:</p>\\n\\\n  <p>\\n   <li> Name: Time Category Name</li>\\n\\n <li>   Description: Time Category Description</li>\\n\\\n  </p>\\n    <p>     Time Category Condition Pane</p>\\n\\n    <p> Actions Menu</p>\\n    <p>\\n          <li> Add</li>\\n          <li> Duplicate</li>\\n            \\n          <li>Delete</li>\\n            \\n          <li>Add Nest</li>\\n          <li> Delete Nest </li>\\n\\\n  </p>\\n\\\n  <p>Actions Behavior</p>\\n\\\n  <p>\\n\\\n  <li>  Add New Row (No Selection): A new row is inserted after the last row in the table.</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    Add New Row (Row Selected): A new row is added below the selected row.</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li> Add New Row (Multiple Rows Selected): One new row is added below the last selected row.</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    Duplicate Row: The duplicate row is added below the selected row.</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li> Duplicate Multiple Rows: The group of duplicated rows is added below the selected group.</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    Duplicate Noncontiguous Duplication: The group of duplicated rows is added below the selected row or group of rows.\\n\\\n  Example: If the user selects rows 2, 3, and 5, and then clicks the Duplicate icon, the duplicated rows appear below the 2 and 3 grouping and below row 5. \\n\\\n  </li>\\n\\\n  <li>    Delete Row: Deletes the selected row from the table. All rows below it move up to fill the space.</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    Add Nest: to add a nested condtion with its own set of parentheses within an existing condition</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    Delete Nest: to select a nested condition and delete</li>\\n\\\n  </p>\\n    <p> Toolbar Icons</p>\\n    <p>\\n          <li> Add (  )   Add new row</li>\\n          <li> Duplicate (  )   Duplicate selected row or rows</li>\\n          <li> Delete (  )  Delete selected row or rows</li>\\n           \\n          <li> Add Parentheses (  ): Nests and indents selected rows.</li>\\n          <li> Delete Parentheses (  ): Deletes the nesting and indention of selected rows.</li>\\n          <li> Up and Down Arrows \\xE2\\x80\\x93 to allow the user to select a row and move it above or below another condition.</li>\\n          <li> Import Time Category button \\xE2\\x80\\x93 to allow the user to select a row and import a time category below that condition.  This allows the ability to bring into the current definition of a new time category, a pre-existing time category, i.e.  nest one time category within another.  Once an existing time category is imported into the current time category definition, it will be displayed in read-only format, along with its attribute fields and values.  This will protect the original definition of the nested time category. Insert Time Category action should be available at any level and part of collapsible section.\\n\\\n  </li>\\n\\\n  </p>\\n\\\n  <p>Fields displayed in the Condition Pane</p>\\n\\\n  <p>\\n    <li> Row Selector: A check box and row highlighting is used to indicate selection for a given condition</li>\\n    <li> Parentheses:  Added before and after each condition grouping, different levels of parantheses based on nested conditions</li>\\n    <li> Time Attribute field: A smart choice list which contains a set of attributes defined within the Time and Labor data dictionary.  Examples of Time Attributes include Project ID, Hours Type, Task, Expenditure Type, Department, Customer.   Users cannot add new attributes to the choice list.  </li>\\n    <li> Condition:  A choice list of the following options for the conditions of the time attribute values to exist to trigger the time category:</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <ol><li>    Any Value</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    Empty Field (Null Value)</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    Value Set</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    Specific Value</li>\\n\\\n  <ol>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>      Time Attribute Value: A choice list of the values related to the selected time attribute field.</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>         Logical Operator: This combines two conditions to return a set of filtered results.</li>\\n\\n        <ol><li> Values: AND or  OR</li>\\n          <li> Set to AND by default.</li>\\n          <li> This field should be hidden in the last row of the table </li>\\n\\\n  </ol>\\n \\n\\n\\\n  <p>Page Actions:</p>\\n\\n    <li> Validate:  The combination of conditions are checked to ensure the logic is grouped correctly</li>\\n          <ol><li> If errors are found, a message is displayed.</li>\\n          <li> User can validate the condition at any time.</li>\\n          <li> Validation is performed when the user clicks the Validate button or exits the page. Conditions should be verified to: </li>\\n\\\n  </ol>\\n\\\n  <li>  Check that data has been entered into required fields.</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>  Check that a selection has been made in each of the Attribute, Operator, Value and Logical Operator fields.</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>   Check that no invalid characters have been entered in the Value field. Invalid characters include: @, >, %, and so on.</li>\\n\\n    <li> Save: Saves the changes, updates the object information in the base table.</li>\\n          <ol><li> Condition is checked for errors. If errors are present a message is displayed.</li>\\n          <li> The time category should not be saved with errors because then inaccurate time categories may be used</li><ol>\\n    <li> Save and Close: Saves the changes and closes the window.</li>\\n          <li> Condition is checked for errors. If errors are present a message is displayed.  </li></ol>\\n    <li> Cancel: Cancels the transaction, closes the page and returns user to the referencing page.</li>\\n\\n \\n\\\n  <p>\\n\\\n  <li>Additional Features of the Condition Pane</li>\\n\\n         <ol><li>Show/Hide Collapsible Sections: Each logic grouping identified with its set of  parentheses can be collapsed in a section, with a summary Comments field displayed, to make it easier to read the content of a time category which has multiple logic groupings.  Each logic grouping should be collapsible to allow for a distinct summary of what each logic defines. The summary is provided by the Comments field.</li>\\n\\n         <li>Comments Field: should be 30 characters in length and part of collapsible section for logic grouping.  When the section is collapsed, this field is still open for display to the user.</li>\\n\\n \\n\\n        <li>View Resolved Time Category: (nice to have) this  last section will dynamically provide an\\xE2\\x80\\x9CEnglish\\xE2\\x80\\x9D sentence which retrieves the selected Time Entry Attribute values and places them within the logic statement selected, with the use of \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cand\\xE2\\x80\\x9D and \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cor\\xE2\\x80\\x9D operator in between the value listing.  This sentence will get updated as the time entry attributes are associated to the appropriate logic columns.\\n\\\n  </li></ol>\\n </p>\\n\\n\\\n  <p>Accessibility Requirements</p>\\n\\\n  <p>\\n\\\n  Although there are no visible column labels in the Condition pane, the following needs to be coded for accessibility requirements:\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    Field labels (for example, attribute, operator, and so on) are hidden but must be labeled.</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <li>    Each row in the condition must be identified uniquely.\\n\\\n  Example:  Attribute: Row 1, Operator: Row 1</li>\\n\\\n  </p>\\n \\n\\\n  <p>\\n\\\n  <li>Time Category examples</li>\\n\\n\\\n  <ol><li> Unscheduled Hours</li>\\n\\n\\\n  Day = Saturday or Day=Sunday\\n\\n\\\n  And\\n\\n\\\n  Hours Type = Regular or Jury or Holiday or Overtime or Doubletime\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  <li>  Special Pay</li>\\n\\n\\\n  (Day=Saturday or Sunday\\n\\n\\\n  And\\n\\n\\\n  Hours Type= Compensation Earned, Call In Pay, Double Overtime)\\n\\n\\\n  OR\\n\\n\\\n  Hours Type= Compensation Earned, Call In Pay, Double Overtime\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  <li>  Project Development Cost</li>\\n\\n\\\n  Project ID is Design or Development or Testing\\n\\n\\\n  And\\n\\n\\\n  Task=Any Value\\n\\n\\\n  And Expenditure Types is Straight Time or Overtime\\n\\n\\\n  And\\n\\n\\\n  Cost Code is 123, or 456, or 789\\n\\\n  </p>\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  <li>Edit Time Category: all fields and behavior will be available for update in the Edit Time Category display.  </li>\\n    \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3170,'FunctionalWorkUnit',109,'destroy','1','--- \nname: Time and Labor Time Categories\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 109\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3171,'Feature',987,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"General Worklist: Timecard Summary Approval Display\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 987\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"A user needs the ability to view a listing of all timecards that require approval in one view.  This summary view should allow for a single timecard to be approved or multiple timecards to be approved (rejected) at one time. The user actions on the timecards would include approving, rejecting, reassigning or requesting more information.\\n\\n\\\n  The approver needs to be able to enter comments for each timecard being approved or rejected, so the approval comments will route to the originator of the timecard.\\n\\n\\\n  One display of the timecards requiring approval will be in the federated version of the Worlist table which will appear in the Welcome tab of the Fusion Home page This component displays all open workflow tasks (approvals and other requests for action) and notifications (FYI tasks) for the current user.\\n\\n\\\n  Worklist tasks are displayed using the table as shown below. Selecting an item in the table launches the corresponding task details page in its own browser window without the Fusion chrome. Both single-select and multi-select actions are supported by this table.\\n\\n\\\n  Table columns displayed:\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Title\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Status\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     From\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Assigned Date\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Actions menu:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Custom action\\n\\n\\\n  o     Claim\\n\\n\\\n  o     Resume\\n\\n\\\n  o     Renew\\n\\n\\\n  o     Submit\\n\\n\\\n  o     Dismiss\\n\\n\\\n  o     -----\\n\\n\\\n  o     Request Information...\\n\\n\\\n  o     Delegate...\\n\\n\\\n  o     Reassign...\\n\\n\\\n  o     Push Back...\\n\\n\\\n  o     Escalate...\\n\\n\\\n  o     -----\\n\\n\\\n  o     Release\\n\\n\\\n  o     Suspend\\n\\n\\\n  o     -----\\n\\n\\\n  o     Create To Do Task... \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3172,'Feature',988,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"General Worklist: Timecard Detail Approval Display\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 988\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: |-\n  Ability to drill down into the detail of a timecard, to see all time requiring approval, and be able to approve from the detail view.  The user actions on the timecard would include approving, rejecting, reassigning or requesting more information.\n  \n  The Timecard Details section should be a display similar to what is viewed on the Timecard Review page, which would include in a read only display, the time entry details, processed results, and other sections as configured in the Time Entry Page Composer.\n  \n  Additionally, there should be a link to the actual timecard from the detail display page, in case the approver needs to navigate to the actual timecard for more information.\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3173,'Feature',989,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Custom Worklist: Timecard Summary Approval Display\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 989\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"To provide the timecard approver with a filtered list of just timecards requiring approval, along with other data which assist in making informed approver decisions, there will be a custom worklist view of Timecards Requiring Approval.  This worklist display will be available in the landing page of the Timecards Workarea for managers or timekeepers who are granted the duty role of timecard approval. \\n\\n\\\n  This summary view should allow for a single timecard to be approved or multiple timecards to be approved at one time. The user actions on the timecards would include approving, rejecting, reassigning or requesting more information.\\n\\n\\\n  Additionally, there should be information specific for the timecard approver to make a better decision to approve or reject the timecard.  The custom worklist should include the following columns:\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Person Name\\n\\n\\\n  o     Role\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Period\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Status\\n\\n\\\n  o     Total Hours\\n\\n\\\n  o     Premium Hours\\n\\n\\\n  o     Non Worked Hours\\n\\n\\\n  o     Submission Date\\n\\n\\\n  The table should include Search and Advanced Search options in the toolbar to assist in finding certain timecards requiring approval.  These search items were also available in Mass Timecard Approval feature in EBS OTL R12\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xA7     Basic Search:   Person, Timecard Period,  Status\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xA7     Advanced Search: \\n\\\n  - Timecard Fields: Detail Comment,  Timecard comment, Timecard Period, Timecard Status, Timecard Submission Date, Totals Hours  , also any other timecard fields which have been defined in the time entry page composer by the user , should be available from Add Field choice list \\n\\\n  - Comparative Operator: Equals To, Greater Than, Greater Than or Equals To, Less Than, Less Than or Equals To, Like, Not Equal To, Not Like \\n\\\n  - Value: Open Field  \\n\\\n  - Logical Operator:   And, Or\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3174,'Feature',990,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Custom Worklist: Configurable Columns in Timecard Summary Approval\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 990\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"In addition to the columns added for the custom view of timecard approvals,  we should also provide extra columns that could be added by the user when defining a view.  These additional columns allows a user to add summary fields that are specific to their business, to aide in the process of approving timecards.  There should be an \\xE2\\x80\\x9CAdd Field\\xE2\\x80\\x9D component, which allows the user to select from summarization fields which are defined in Time Entry Editor for the Time Summary table displayed in the Timecard.  These additional fields will be dependent on what the customer selects as their timecard summarizations to track in the Time Summary section of the Layout Set.  They could be such things as Project and Task, or Billable/Non-Billable or Worked/Non-Worked Hours.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3175,'Feature',991,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Custom Worklist:  Timecard Detail Approval Page\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 991\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: |-\n  a.     Would need the ability to drill down into the detail of a timecard, to see all time requiring approval, and be able to approve from the detail view.  The user actions on the timecard would include approve, reject, delegate, transfer or request more information.\n  \n  b.     Would need the ability to view the timecard detail, as displayed in the Timecard Review page, without any pop-ups or drill in pages.  There will be a configuration for the setup of the timecard detail approval notification page in the Time Entry Page Composer.\n  \n  c.     Would need to view a tablular and graphical approval history of which approvers have taken action and which approvers have yet to take action\n  \n  d.     Would need a hyperlink to the viewable timecard page, in case the approver needed more detail within the timecard. Once viewed, the user needs to be able to navigate back to the approval notification.\n  \n  e.     Would need a section for Comments, for the approver to make comments if the timecard has been approved or rejected.\n  \n  f.     Would be nice to have a section for Audit Log, to see the users who have interacted with the timecard and what action they took.  (Fields to include:  user name, action taken, date and timestamp, role)\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3176,'Feature',992,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worklist: Timecard Detail Approval Page \\xE2\\x80\\x93 Display Change and Late Audit Entries\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 992\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: For users, with time audit rules associated to them, they will have additional entries to make on a Time Audit page, in which they need to enter reasons and comments for changes to time entries.  The Timecard Detail Approval Display should include the Change and Late Audit sections in the Timecard Details section .   Ideally, the change and late audit sections we display on the  Time Audit Review page will be used on the Timecard Detail Approval page. Alternatively, if there is not enough space to display these sections, the user should be taken to the full viewable timecard page by hyperlink to see all relevant sections.\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3177,'Feature',993,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worklist: Approval Actions \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 993\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"Support the following  AMX Approval Actions for both the Approval Notification Detail page as well as the Custom Timecard Approval Summary Workllist page.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Approve \\xE2\\x80\\x93 Approve the timecard, providing any comments in the approval notification if needed.  Should be a page level action button on the approval notification page and Custom Timecard Approval Summary Worklist page.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Reject \\xE2\\x80\\x93 Reject the timecard and place comments in the approval notification explaining what has been rejected.  Should be a page level action button on the approval notification page and Custom Timecard Approval Summary Worklist page.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Request More Information \\xE2\\x80\\x93 email notification sent to worker, email and no action needed on the  timecard,.  This allows the approver  to ask a question to the requester or anyone in the approval list before making a decision..  This option should be part of an Actions menu dropdown in the approval notification page.  It can be a toolbar button on the Custom Timecard Approval Summary Worklist page.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Reassign... \\xE2\\x80\\x93 there are two options from this action in its dialog:\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xA7     Delegate - Forwards task to another user, without change in ownership.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xA7     Transfer - Forwards and changes ownership to another user.\\n\\n\\\n  The option of Reassign with the two sub-options of Delegate and Transfer should be part of an Actions menu dropdown in the approval notification page.  It can be a toolbar button on the Custom Timecard Approval Summary Worklist page.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3178,'Feature',994,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worklist: Require User to Open Timecard before Approval\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 994\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"A business requirement may be that an approver must open a timecard to review it before approving it.  In order to enforce this condition, there would need to be the prevention of approving or rejecting a timecard from the summary approval worklist page in either the General Worklist or Custom Worklist view.   The user would need to do to the Detail Approval page to take the approval action necessary.  Currently there is a Enhancement Request registered with AMX to provide for this requirement:\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  AMX Enhancement Request:  REQUIRE TO OPEN THE TIMECARD BEFORE BEING ABLE TO ACT ON IT \\xE2\\x80\\x93 configuration needed in AMX, parameter set so when user clicks on Approve or Reject action, cannot take action unless open notification.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3179,'Feature',995,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worklist: Approval Comments\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 995\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: |-\n  An approver should be able to enter comments against a timecard with the approval or rejection of a timecard.  If the approver is making multiple approvals or rejections from the summary worklist page, there should be a pop-up to allow the approver to make comments against each timecard prior to taking the action. \n  \n   \n  \n  One option would be to have the comment field in the worklist table, the second option would be to have a dialog box that allows comments to be entered for the different timecards selected.\n  \n   \n  \n  Currently there is an enhancement request open with AMX to allow for the entry of comments against multiple timecards for a multiple approval or rejection of timecards:\n  \n  BEING ABLE TO ENTER COMMENTS AGAINST A TIMECARD PRIOR APPROVE/REJECT: (MUST HAVE) \n  Mass Comment Entry before applying the action (approve, reject, whatever)\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3180,'Feature',996,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Display Approval Results on Timecard\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 996\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"The results of the approval or rejection of a timecard needs to be consolidated for display in the timecard.  There may be multiple approvers who may have approved or rejected different blocks of time within the timecard.  Since the timecard is one entity viewed by the user, it needs to easily display which time entries have been approved or rejected, by which approver and any comments related to the actions. \\n\\n\\\n  a.   The user will see the Timecard Status on the Timecard:\\n\\n\\\n  Rejected: If there is at least one time entry which is rejected, the whole timecard status will be rejected\\n\\n\\\n  Approved:  If all time entries for that timecard is approved, the whole timecard is approved\\n\\n\\\n  Submitted:  The timecard will remain in this state pending approver or if the user needs to respond to an email request for information from one of the timecard approvers.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  b.   There will be an Approver Comments pop-up dialog box which will display the following information to the timecard user:\\n\\n\\\n  Approver Name  Role  Approver Comments\\n\\n\\\n  If any approver has rejected part or all of the timecard, his comments should specify what was rejected and what needs to be resolved.  The Approval Comments will pop-up in a dialog when the user enters the timecard if there are any comments to display.  If the user closes the pop-up dialog box by clicking on \\xE2\\x80\\x9COK\\xE2\\x80\\x9D button, then he needs to be able to access a \\xE2\\x80\\x9CView Approver Comments\\xE2\\x80\\x9D toolbar button to view the comments again.  The approval comments are associated with the current version of the timecard being reviewed.  If the timecard is modified and resubmitted, new approval comments will be associated to the \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cnewer\\xE2\\x80\\x9D version of the timecard.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3181,'Feature',997,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Override Approver  (AMX)\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 997\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"The timecard will no longer display an \\xE2\\x80\\x9Coverride approver\\xE2\\x80\\x9D field for the user to enter a name. The main reason for the override approver field displayed on the timecard was if the approver was on vacation. The other example is that a worker has a change in Projects reported, and thus a change in Project Manager who would approve his timecard.  In this example, the timecard approval rule can be setup to be based on Project ID, to derive the correct Project Manager for approval routing.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Instead, the AMX action of \\xE2\\x80\\x9CDelegate\\xE2\\x80\\x9D can be used by the approver who will not be available, to delegate the approval to another. \\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  A second approach recommended by AMX was to have the customer define an \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cowner\\xE2\\x80\\x9D for the timecard approval transactions, so they could intercede if the approval transaction was \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cstuck\\xE2\\x80\\x9D in the approval chain\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  It is still be determined if the above approach is workable for the temporary change of approvers needed.  The attributes of the \\xE2\\x80\\x9COverride Approver\\xE2\\x80\\x9D field on the timecard was the following:\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     Provide the ability for a user to enter a name for an override approver in the routing of the timecard.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     The override approver will take the place of any other approvers originally designated in the approval routing for that timecard. \\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     This override approver will only be defined for that particular timecard.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     Provide the ability to define a default override approver, to allow the user to easily find the name of an override approver that he has selected on prior occasions.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3182,'Feature',998,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Approval Routing: Allow for Parallel or Serial Approvers for a Timecard (AMX)\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 998\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"Provide the ability to route a timecard for approval in multiple methods:\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     Serial (sequential) routing which will allow a timecard to be routed to one approver, upon approval from the prior approver\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     Parallel routing which allows the timecard to be routed to multiple approvers simultaneously:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Sections of the Timecard can be routed in parallel to one or more approvers within one application like Payroll.  This covers Entry Level Approvals functionality which existed in EBS OTL R12.  We will be able to send a row of timecard data to each approver for which it is relevant for them.  The sections of the timecard matrix which are relevant will display in the Timecard Details section.\\n\\n\\\n  o     The whole Timecard can be routed in parallel to one or more approvers in different applications like HR, Payroll and Projects\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  (Note:  We will not continue the requirement for a sequential application dependency that all approvers from one application will not receive the timecard for approval until the timecard has been acted upon by another application.)\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3183,'Feature',999,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Approval Routing: Package Time for Approvers (AMX)\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 999\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"The following are the requirements for packaging portions of a timecard to be routed to different approvers:\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     Allow for the user to define certain fields of the timecard to be routed to different approvers based on defined approval rules\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     The segmentation or fragmentation of the timecard allow for the approver to only see fields that are critical to them for approval, and also secures other fields that they should not see from the approval display\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     The segmentation of the timecard fields can be done by application via the use of time categories.  These time categories can summarize time entries by time attributes. \\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     (Moved to Out of Scope region )Timecards can be sent for approval with a priority order to various applications\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3184,'Feature',1000,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Approval Routing: Flexibility of Defining the Approvers (AMX)\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 1000\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"hese are the current default approval mechanisms which the Time and Labor Approval Styles offers, which should be offered in Approval Groups in AMX:\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     HR Supervisor \\xE2\\x80\\x93 ability to specify the worker\\xE2\\x80\\x99s HR Supervisor\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     Specific Person \\xE2\\x80\\x93 ability to define a specific person\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     Project Manager \\xE2\\x80\\x93 ability to define the worker\\xE2\\x80\\x99s project manager based on the project that the employee reported time against\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     Auto Approve \\xE2\\x80\\x93 Allowance for auto approval of the timecard\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     Entry Level Approver \\xE2\\x80\\x93 different approvers within an application(s) who see portions of the timecard requiring approval.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  This flexibility of defining such criteria should be covered by Dynamic Approval Groups setup in AMX.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Note:  Fast formula will no longer be supported for defining approvers, as AMX does not support Fast Formula, but uses their own rule logic.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3185,'Feature',1001,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Approval Routing: Deleted Timecards  (AMX)\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 1001\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: For timecards that have been submitted which have triggered the approval routings, the approval flow needs to be interrupted and the approvers need to be notified that the timecard has been deleted.\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3186,'Feature',1002,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Approval Routing:  Changes to a Timecard (AMX)\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 1002\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"If an approved timecard requires changes, the status of the timecard needs to be reset to a submitted status.  The timecard needs to be routed again for approvals.  The approval routing may be different for a resubmission, as opposed to the original submission, based on the approval rule setup. \\n\\n\\\n  If the approval period is greater than a single timecard period, than all the timecards which make up the approval period will be re-routed for approval based on time entry changes.\\n\\n\\\n  If a timecard has been submitted and has entered an approval routing, the routing process needs to be cancelled, so the updated timecard can re-enter the approval routing.\\n\\n\\\n  Processed Result Changes Only - If the timecard has not had changes to the raw entered time, but for some reason the time calculation rules need to recalculate, which causes changes to the processed results, the timecard should be retriggered for approval.  The reason for this is to give the approver a \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cheads up\\xE2\\x80\\x9D that the processed time has changed, in case it would impact his approval decision.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:28'),(3187,'Feature',1003,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Approval Routing:  Change of Approvers within Timecard Period (AMX)\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 1003\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: The determination of which timecard entries should be sent to which approvers should be determined by the approval rule associated to the approval transaction type.  The approval rule can be defined to either send impacted time entries to the correct approver for each time period section, or to send all time to the valid approver for beginning of timecard or valid approver at end of timecard period.\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3188,'Feature',1004,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Business Events of Timecard (Timecard Actions)\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 1004\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"The current trigger points for approval include the following actions: manual action or bulk upload of timecards being submitted triggering approval.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     Submission of timecard\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     Re-submission of timecard\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     Deletion of timecard\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  There should be the ability for users to assign different approval routings for different events.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Determination of the approval period is required to determine if approval is needed:\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     A timecard approval period must be complete.  There may be different approval periods for each application to which the timecard is routed. (i.e. Payroll, Projects, etc) These approval periods are not necessarily analogous to the timecard time periods.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC3\\xBC     Data Entered:  certain data is entered in the timecard which would trigger approvals.  This data would be analyzed as part of time categories.  Prior to Fusion, this data would be recognized as fields in mappings related to retrieving applications like Payroll or Projects.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3189,'Feature',1005,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Use of HCM Transaction Model (Time and Labor)\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 1005\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"If the timecard approval transaction is incorporated into the HCM Transaction Model, outputs of the transaction model which can be included in the timecard approval transaction include:\\n\\n\\\n  A.  Review Page which would include:\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     A single column table showing new data for Create operations\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     A two or three column table showing data changed for Update operations\\n\\n\\\n  B.  Transaction Storage which would include:\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Storing business data as XML (the default operation)\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Sets up Conflict Management data\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Allows customer to over-ride the default functions of the Transaction Store (e.g. setting up Status Column handling)\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Provides callbacks at appropriate points to allow consumer to amend the business data\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Allows consumer to store their own values in flexfield structures (for custom conflict checking)\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Allows the business data to be reactivated, for example to edit during approval.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Raises an event to call Approvals Integration\\n\\n\\\n  C.  Use of Approvals Integration which would include:\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Notifications to approvers requesting approval.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Allowing the Approvals routing to be configured\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Provides asynchronous call-back to the Transaction Store to process approval result\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3190,'Feature',1006,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: No Locks on Timecards in Approval (Time and Labor)\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 1006\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"There are instances when an approver may be opening a timecard notification requiring approval, and at the same time  a timecard user is updating the same timecard.  The approval notification would have a display of the timecard version related to that approval.  Ideally, we could provide an informational message to the approver if someone else submitted a new version simultaneously. \\n\\n\\\n  When the new version of the timecard is resubmitted, the current approval notification should be cancelled and a new approval notification should be generated for the approvers.  Additionally, it would be a good user experience for the approver if he is accessing the timecard during the approval process and the timecard is in the midst of being updated, to show a message to the approver that the timecard is being edited currently.  However, this may not change the approver\\xE2\\x80\\x99s actions, as the current approval transaction is currently open and active.\\n\\n\\\n  We would not want to lock the timecard from updates during the approval process, as there is no sense of how long the timecard approval process would last for the last version of the timecard.  Locking the timecard when a user has the security access to update the timecard is very frustrating and confusing to the timecard user.\\n\\n\\\n  Open issue:  We will have to see how AMX is dealing with this conflict when a timecard user is accessing an approval transaction (email or worklist notification) and the approval transaction is being cancelled because a new approval transaction is being generated.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3191,'Feature',1007,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Requiring Your Approval Notification (Manager)\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 1007\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"Following  are the key features of the \\xE2\\x80\\x9Ctimecard requiring your approval\\xE2\\x80\\x9D notification which will be routed to a timecard approver and can be accessed from the general worklist table or custom worklist table in the Timecards Workarea:\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Details Section - Human task fields are placed in the first column.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xA7     Assignee: Recipient\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xA7     From: Requestor\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xA7     Assigned Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xA7     Expiration Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xA7     Due Date: appears only when not null.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xA7     Outcome: appears only when not null.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xA7     Task Number: Primary object identifier. Needed for trouble-shooting between user and admin.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Approval Actions \\xE2\\x80\\x93 Approve, Reject, Request More Information, Reassign (Transfer or Delegate)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Details- summary display of the timecard, including raw and processed time\\n\\n\\\n  o     Link to View Timecard Details \\xE2\\x80\\x93 hyperlink to take user to the timecard view page, which is configured in the Time Entry Page Composer\\n\\n\\\n  o     Link to Edit Timecard \\xE2\\x80\\x93 hyperlink to the timecard to allow the approver to edit the timecard, if they have edit access\\n\\n\\\n  o     Comments \\xE2\\x80\\x93 ability for approver to add comments regarding approval or rejection of the timecard\\n\\n\\\n  o     Audit Log \\xE2\\x80\\x93 display only region to show different users who have taken action on the timecard\\n\\n\\\n  o     Tabular Action History- Displays the action history from beginning to end in tabular form. This includes past as well as future actions. It allows for editing the list of participants, full and abreviated history, and task snapshot.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Graphical Action History- a This component displays the action list and process flow as applicable in the system in an easy-to-scan graphical format. This graph is generated by the SOA-BPEL/HT team.\\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Once the approver takes an action on the notification, it will be cleared from his worklist queue.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3192,'Feature',1008,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Has Been Approved Notification (Worker)\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 1008\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"This is an informational notification which can be routed to the worker, or original submitter of the timecard that the timecard was approved.  The notifications provides the list of approvers who approved the timecard and has 2 action buttons to \\xE2\\x80\\x9CAcknowledge\\xE2\\x80\\x9D or \\xE2\\x80\\x9CCancel\\xE2\\x80\\x9D the notification.  If the user selects the acknowledge button, the notification will be cleared from their worklist.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  The key sections of this notification are:\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Details Section - Human task fields are placed in the first column.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Assignee: Recipient\\n\\n\\\n  o     From: Requestor\\n\\n\\\n  o     Assigned Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Expiration Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Due Date: appears only when not null.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Outcome: appears only when not null.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Task Number: Primary object identifier. Needed for trouble-shooting between user and admin.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Timecard Details- summary display of the timecard, including raw and processed time\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Link to Edit Timecard \\xE2\\x80\\x93 hyperlink to the timecard if needed\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Approver List \\xE2\\x80\\x93table listing the approvers and their action\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Comments \\xE2\\x80\\x93comments regarding approval or rejection of the timecard\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Audit Log \\xE2\\x80\\x93 display only region to show different users who have taken action on the timecard\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Tabular Action History- Displays the action history from beginning to end in tabular form. This includes past as well as future actions. It allows for editing the list of participants, full and abreviated history, and task snapshot.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Graphical Action History- This component displays the action list and process flow as applicable in the system in an easy-to-scan graphical format. This graph is generated by the SOA-BPEL/HT team. \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3193,'Feature',1009,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Has Been Rejected Notification (Worker)\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 1009\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"This is an informational notification which can be routed to the worker, or original submitter of the timecard that the timecard was rejected.  The notifications provides the list of approvers who rejected  or approved the timecard and has 2 action buttons to \\xE2\\x80\\x9CAcknowledge\\xE2\\x80\\x9D or \\xE2\\x80\\x9CCancel\\xE2\\x80\\x9D the notification.  If the user selects the acknowledge button, the notification will be cleared from their worklist.  Cancelling the notification will not remove the notification from the worklist, but just close the notification.  The comments section should indicate why the timecard was rejected. \\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  The key sections of this notification are:\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Details Section - Human task fields are placed in the first column.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Assignee: Recipient\\n\\n\\\n  o     From: Requestor\\n\\n\\\n  o     Assigned Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Expiration Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Due Date: appears only when not null.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Outcome: appears only when not null.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Task Number: Primary object identifier. Needed for trouble-shooting between user and admin.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Timecard Details- summary display of the timecard, including raw and processed time\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Link to Edit Timecard \\xE2\\x80\\x93 hyperlink to the timecard to allow the worker to edit the timecard, to resolve the reasons for rejection based on the notification\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Approver List \\xE2\\x80\\x93table listing the approvers and their action\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Comments \\xE2\\x80\\x93comments regarding approval or rejection of the timecard\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Audit Log \\xE2\\x80\\x93 display only region to show different users who have taken action on the timecard\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Tabular Action History- Displays the action history from beginning to end in tabular form. This includes past as well as future actions. It allows for editing the list of participants, full and abreviated history, and task snapshot.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Graphical Action History- This component displays the action list and process flow as applicable in the system in an easy-to-scan graphical format. This graph is generated by the SOA-BPEL/HT team.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3194,'Feature',1010,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Requires More Information Notification (Timecard Submitter or Approver)\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 1010\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"The worker or initiator of the timecard will receive this notification and  need to respond to the approver with updated comments and submit the notification back to the approver for update.  The key action buttons on this notification are Submit and Cancel.  Once the notification is submitted, it will be cleared from the user\\xE2\\x80\\x99s worklist queue.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  The key sections of this notification are:\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Details Section - Human task fields are placed in the first column.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Assignee: Recipient\\n\\n\\\n  o     From: Requestor\\n\\n\\\n  o     Assigned Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Expiration Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Due Date: appears only when not null.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Outcome: appears only when not null.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Task Number: Primary object identifier. Needed for trouble-shooting between user and admin.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Timecard Details- summary display of the timecard, including raw and processed time\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Approver List \\xE2\\x80\\x93table listing the approvers and their action\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Comments \\xE2\\x80\\x93comments section in which the user can add more comments to respond to the questions\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Audit Log \\xE2\\x80\\x93 display only region to show different users who have taken action on the timecard\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Tabular Action History- Displays the action history from beginning to end in tabular form. This includes past as well as future actions. It allows for editing the list of participants, full and abreviated history, and task snapshot.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Graphical Action History- This component displays the action list and process flow as applicable in the system in an easy-to-scan graphical format. This graph is generated by the SOA-BPEL/HT team\\n\\n\\\n  See Open Issues on Notification requirements\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3195,'Feature',1011,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Has Been Reassigned for Approval Notification (Worker)\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 1011\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"This informational notification is sent to the worker or originator of the timecard to alert them that one of the approvers in the approver list has been changed and approval is reassigned to a new \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cnamed\\xE2\\x80\\x9D approver.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  The page actions for this notification is \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cacknowledge\\xE2\\x80\\x9D and \\xE2\\x80\\x9Ccancel\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.  If the user clicks on \\xE2\\x80\\x9CAcknowledge\\xE2\\x80\\x9D, the notification is cleared from their worklist queue.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  The key sections of this notification are:\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Details Section - Human task fields are placed in the first column.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Assignee: Recipient\\n\\n\\\n  o     From: Requestor\\n\\n\\\n  o     Assigned Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Expiration Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Due Date: appears only when not null.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Outcome: appears only when not null.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Task Number: Primary object identifier. Needed for trouble-shooting between user and admin.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Timecard Details- summary display of the timecard, including raw and processed time\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Approver List \\xE2\\x80\\x93table listing the approvers and their action\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Comments \\xE2\\x80\\x93comments section in which the user can add more comments to respond to the questions\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Audit Log \\xE2\\x80\\x93 display only region to show different users who have taken action on the timecard\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Tabular Action History- Displays the action history from beginning to end in tabular form. This includes past as well as future actions. It allows for editing the list of participants, full and abreviated history, and task snapshot.\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Graphical Action History- This component displays the action list and process flow as applicable in the system in an easy-to-scan graphical format. This graph is generated by the SOA-BPEL/HT team\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3196,'Feature',1012,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Approval Periods (Time and Labor)\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\npriority: \nid: 1012\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"To continue the flexibility customers currently have, it is important to be able to distinguish timecard periods from approval periods. For example, a timecard period may have aduration of biweekly, but an approval period defined for payroll might be weekly.  The ability for different time consumers to define different approval periods for the timecards to be retrieved allows for the time to be transferred on a timely basis to the time consumer.  Approval periods will be setup in the time consumer set UI, associated to each time consumer who will be retrieving the worker\\xE2\\x80\\x99s timecard data.\\n\\n\\\n  Approval periods can span across timecards.  For example, an approval period for Payroll might be weekly, which could start on one timecard and complete on the next timecard.  In this example, when the 2nd timecard has reached the approval period upon submit, the time from the prior timecard needs to be consolidated with the time from the 2nd timecard and routed for approval.  In this example, it is important to note that the submission of the first timecard would not trigger approval, it was upon the submitting of the 2nd timecard that it needed to be determined if the overlapping approval period was met.\\n\\n\\\n  Some examples of when timecard periods and approval periods are not aligned:\\n\\n\\\n  In some cases customers want to have a short Timecard Period and a long Approval Period. This is because the customer wants to force users to submit time on a frequent basis yet not burden their approvers with frequent approvals.  \\n\\\n  For example: Daily Timecard Period and Weekly Approval Period   \\n\\n\\\n  In some cases customers (eg Santos) want to have a short approval period and a longer timecard period. This is because the customer wants to move the time that\\xE2\\x80\\x99s been entered through to the time consumer as quickly as possible. For example, a weekly timecard period and a daily approval period. Users submit there timecard whenever they enter time and this time is then sent to the approver and can be transferred to the time consumer without waiting till the end of the week.\\n\\n\\\n  In the case where there is more than one time consumer for a given worker\'s time, it may be that 2 or more of the Time Consumers have their own, \'natural\' approval period. For example Projects might have a Weekly Expenditure Period and Payroll a Bi-monthly payroll period. In this case, at least one of the approval periods must differ from the Timecard Period.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3197,'Feature',1013,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Approval Rules (AMX)\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1013\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"In order to correctly route the timecard data to approvers, there are evaluations of the timecard that need to be done which would continue the same functionality as Approval Styles and Approval Rules in EBS Time and Labor R12.  Firstly, it needs to be determined if approval is needed on timecard submission, based on the approval period defined for the timecard.  Then if approval is required, it needs to be determined, what type of approval needs to be done, such as auto-approval or routing to one or more approvers.    The approval rules defined in AMX will determine what timecard data is collected for approval and to whom it is routed for approval, and how the routings will occur.\\n\\n\\\n  The approvers may or not be in the same application (i.e. Payroll, Projects).  Once the type of approval is determined, it needs to be determined what timecard data needs to be packaged and transferred to the approvers, based on rule criteria, which can include the summing of data using time categories.  Time categories allow for the summing up of time against different time entry fields present on the timecard.  These time categories can sum up data that is specific to an application, like Payroll or Projects, or it can simply sum up a specific group of time entries, such as overtime or bonuses which require approval.\\n\\n\\\n  The approval rules made available in AMX need to provide the following flexibility:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Need the ability to define approval rules by role , to allow time to be approved by role (project manager(derived by Project ID) , payroll manager, timekeeper, manager).\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Need the ability to define approval rules based on data values in the timecard ( assignment status (based on Core HR status) , summarization, timecard status, project manager, overtime, hours exceeding \\xE2\\x80\\x9CX\\xE2\\x80\\x9D hours, Project ID exists, Hours Type of \\xE2\\x80\\x9COvertime, Special Compensation\\xE2\\x80\\x9D. Time Categories will allow ways of summarizing values, to look for \\xE2\\x80\\x9CAll Values\\xE2\\x80\\x9D or \\xE2\\x80\\x9COnly specific values\\xE2\\x80\\x9D to allow for \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cfragmented approval\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Need the ability to define approval rules to support \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cfragmented approval\\xE2\\x80\\x9D  - to filter only certain rows of timecard data to the correct approver.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Need the ability to define approval rules to bypass normal approval flow and allow auto-approval \\xE2\\x80\\x93 (based on conditions like, time entered by manager, timekeeper, project manager, payroll manager)\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Note:  Please refer to the Appendix on Seeded Approval Rules, based on approval rules that were delivered in EBS OTL R12.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3198,'Feature',1014,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Approval Rules:  Conditions  (AMX)\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1014\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"When creating approval rules for timecard approvals, every organization has different needs for when time needs approval.  Approval conditions can be based on who the employee is, how an employee is associated to some entity, what type of time is reported or if certain limits are met.  It is important that a user can combine any attributes which are associated to a worker in HCM as well as time attributes, which can be defined and combined with time categories.  Time categories can also be used in \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cexceed limits\\xE2\\x80\\x9D rules.  The following fields are examples of core HR, Payroll, Projects and Time and Labor fields which should be available as attributes for timecard approval rules:\\n\\n\\\n  Core HR\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Job\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Position\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Legislative Data Group\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Legal Entity\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Organization\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Assignment Status\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Shift\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Work Schedule\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Person Type\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Company\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Cost Center\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Department\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Grade\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Location\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Collective Agreement\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     Person\\n\\n\\\n  \\xC2\\xB7     HCM Group\\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Payroll\\n\\n\\\n  Payroll Element\\n\\n\\\n  Payroll Period\\n\\n\\\n  Balance\\n\\n\\\n  Payroll Cost Allocation\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Projects\\n\\n\\\n  Project\\n\\n\\\n  Task\\n\\n\\\n  Project Status\\n\\n\\\n  Labor Rate\\n\\n\\\n  Expenditure Type\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Time and Labor\\n\\n\\\n  Time Category\\n\\n\\\n  Setup Option Profile\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3199,'Feature',1015,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Approval Transaction Type: Approval Rule Association to Workers\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1015\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"In order to provide flexibility among different populations of workers, it is critical that a user can group their approval rules into a logical set and associate them to different groups of workers.  Some workers may only require auto approval of time, whereas other groups of workers may require different types of time to be approved.  Being able to associate different levels of timecard approval requirements to different workers provides more efficiency for overall approval processing.\\n\\n\\\n  To accomplish this goal, different Approval Transaction Types will be defined in AMX, with groupings of Approval Rules.  These Approval Transaction Types will be associated to the time consumer in the Time Consumer Set UI.  The worker will be associated to the Approval Transaction Type based on the Time Consumer Set assigned to his Time and Labor Worker Processing Setup Profile.  The options for the Approval Transaction Type choicelist will either be \\xE2\\x80\\x9CAuto-Approval\\xE2\\x80\\x9D, which will bypass the AMX flow, or one of the seeded Approval Transaction Types in AMX.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3200,'Feature',1016,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Auto Approval of Loaded Time and Labor)\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1016\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"Time can be loaded into Time and Labor from an API from any time collection system.  There should be a mechanism in which the user can configure imported time to be \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cstamped\\xE2\\x80\\x9D with an approved status.  In this manner, the time should not be routed through any approval process, it should just be approved and ready to be transferred to another application. \\n\\n\\\n  However, any time which is loaded into Time and Labor will be processed through application validations (validations of the time consumers which will retrieve the time).   If any time that is validated is in error, then it cannot be stamped as approved.  The timecard errors will need to be resolved before they can be \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cstamped\\xE2\\x80\\x9D as approved.  The Approval Transaction Type option of \\xE2\\x80\\x9CAuto-Approve\\xE2\\x80\\x9D defined in Section 2.3.29 can be utilized for this scenario, when the errors are cleared and the timecards are resubmitted.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3201,'Feature',1017,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Forced Approval  (AMX)\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1017\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"For timecards which are not slated for auto approval, but need to be routed to approvers, there are times that the timecards may need to be forced through approvals.  There may be a timing issue in which the timecards need to get processed to payroll immediately, or there may be a breakdown in the approval routing in which approvers are not available.  There needs to be a process in which a user can easily determine the timecards which are pending approval and be able to approve them.  The ability to do this approval may require special \\xE2\\x80\\x9Coverride approval\\xE2\\x80\\x9D security.\\n\\n\\\n  Example of the terminated worker scenario:\\n\\n\\\n  In the event that a worker is terminated (voluntarily or involuntarily), there needs to be a way to move the timecard through the approval process to get the accurate recorded time to payroll for payment.  At issue is that the approval period may not be met even if the timecard is submitted, so would not automatically route to the AMX routing rules.\\n\\n\\\n  A worker submits a timecard which only contains 2 days of a weekly Payroll approval period. The worker is terminated and therefore will not be submitting the next timecard which would \'fill up\' the Time Approval Transaction. There are two days which need to be paid but the timecard submission would not complete the approval period to trigger AMX approvals.\\n\\n\\\n  There is an enhancement request for AMX to provide and API for Forced Approval, which is not available as of yet - Enhancement 7495226.  To utilize this API we would need to specify parameters of when to call this API and for which worker\\xE2\\x80\\x99s timecards.  As this API is not currently available, the main design solution for Fusion v2 is the following:\\n\\n\\\n  In Fusion v2, in order to expedite timecards being pushed to a time consumer, we will not force the approval but we will leave the approval process as it is, but we will force the timecards for immediate transfer. Using the Group Time Entry user interface, the administrator can select workers and their related timecards which need to be immediately transferred.  We are calling this process \\xE2\\x80\\x9CForced Transfer\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.  Going forward with this solution, that will permit the timecard to carry on its normal approval route and hence allows the approver to reject the timecards if wrong/missing entries were made. If the timecard gets rejected, after getting transfered in a time consumer application, after the timecard gets corrected and approved, in the next transfer to the time consumer adjustement will be made.\\n\\n\\\n  An alternate solution for terminated workers is that we can subscribe to event triggers such as terminations of employees, which would trigger the adjustment of approval periods to end on the employee\\xE2\\x80\\x99s termination date, to expedite the approval of the required timecards.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3202,'Feature',1018,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Approval of Blank Timecards (AMX)\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1018\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"For businesses which always require timecards to be generated and approved for all time periods for their employees, it is important that even a blank timecard can be approved.  A blank timecard means that no time entries have been made for the employee for the time period.  It is critical that a blank timecard can still be routed through the approval process, whether it is for \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cauto approval\\xE2\\x80\\x9D or for specific approval routing.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3203,'Feature',1019,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Approval Statuses (Time and Labor)\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1019\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 110\ndescription: \"As stated in the Report Time FDD, there are derived statuses which will be displayed in the Timecard Status field for the timecard related to approvals:\\n\\n\\\n  Approved: When all time entries have been approved within that timecard\\n\\n\\\n  Rejected:  When at least one time entry has been rejected in the timecard\\n\\n\\\n  Submitted:  When the timecard has been submitted without errors to be approved\\n\\n\\\n  Open Design Issue:  There is the use case in which the timecard has been submitted but is not routed for approval because the approval period is greater than the timecard period.  In this instance, the timecard will be waiting for the next timecard to be submitted to see if the approval period has been met for it also to be routed for approval.  As a result, this timecard is in a \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cholding pattern\\xE2\\x80\\x9D until the approval period is met.  A possible additional status for this condition can be \\xE2\\x80\\x9CPending Approval\\xE2\\x80\\x9D, to indicate that the timecard has been completed but is not yet ready for the approval flow.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3204,'FunctionalWorkUnit',110,'destroy','1','--- \nname: \"Time and Labor Technology Uptake: Uptake of AMX Approvals Functionality\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 110\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3205,'Feature',1020,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: No Name\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1020\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 111\ndescription: \" \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3206,'FunctionalWorkUnit',111,'destroy','1','--- \nname: \"Time and Labor Setup Changes: Time Interaction Rules and Rule Sets\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 111\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3207,'Feature',1021,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: No Name\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1021\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 112\ndescription: \"  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3208,'FunctionalWorkUnit',112,'destroy','1','--- \nname: \"Time and Labor Timecard Template \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 112\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3209,'Feature',1022,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Basic Search page for Time Consumer Set\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1022\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 113\ndescription: \"\\n        <p>User can search Time Consumer Sets using this feature </p>\\n        <p>Basic search is performed using \'Consumer Set Name\' or \'Description\' search fields of the Consumer Sets.  Based on the user input system will run a query to the tables and \\n        display the information in search restuls grid.</p> \\n        \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3210,'Feature',1023,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Advanced Search page for Time Consumer Sets\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1023\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 113\ndescription: \"\\n                    <p>Lets the user execute advanced queries based on logical operators and wildcards.</p>                     \\n                    <dt>Search can be executed using the following parameters</dt>\\n                    <dd>Time Consumer Name : Name of the Consumer Set, Choice list of consumers</dd>\\n                    <dd>Time Category Name : smart choicelist of all time categories, with a default of \\\"All Time Entry\\\".</dd>\\n                    <dd>Validation on Save : Yes/No Choicelist <dd>\\n                    <dd>Time Required : Yes/No Choicelist <dd>\\n                    <dd>Approval Period : Choice list of all repeating time periods</dd>  \\n                   \\n        \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3211,'Feature',1024,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Search Grid Results for Time Consumer Sets\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1024\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 113\ndescription: \"\\n                  <p>Results grid displays repeating consumer set details </p>\\n                  <p>Create, Edit, Delete and Duplicate buttons and Actions are included in the grid</p>\\n                  <p>Columns of the Search Results Grid are Name, Description of the Consumer Sets.</p>  \\n                  <p>The search results will initially defaults 10 last Consumer Sets created.  It also inculdes seed data.</p>\\n                  \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3212,'Feature',1025,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Create Time Consumer Set\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1025\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 113\ndescription: \"\\n                  \'Create\' action or \'Create\' button from the Search Results grid are used to create new time consumer set. \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3213,'Feature',1026,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Edit Time Consumer Set\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1026\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 113\ndescription: \"\\n                  Can edit Time consumer set deatils.\\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3214,'Feature',1027,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Delete Time Consumer Set\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1027\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 113\ndescription: \"\\n                  Can delete Time consumer set if it is not in use(\\\"In use\\\" is defined as being assigned to an employee via Time and Labor Setup Options,\\n                  or attached to a timecard).\\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3215,'Feature',1028,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Duplicate Time Consumer Set\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1028\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 113\ndescription: \"\\n                  Can duplicate Time consumer set deatils if it is not in use(\\\"In use\\\" is defined as being assigned to an employee via Time and Labor Setup Options,\\n                  or attached to a timecard).\\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3216,'Feature',1029,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Default values for Time Consumer Set\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1029\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 113\ndescription: \"\\n                   <p>\'Time Required\' = \'Yes\' default value</p>\\n                   <p>\'Validate on Save\'= \'No\' default value </p>\\n                   <p>\'Payroll\' and \'Project Status\' = Approved </>\\n                    \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3217,'FunctionalWorkUnit',113,'destroy','1','--- \nname: \"Time and Labor Setup Changes: Time Consumers\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 113\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3218,'Feature',1030,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: No Name\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1030\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 114\ndescription: \"  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:29'),(3219,'FunctionalWorkUnit',114,'destroy','1','--- \nname: \"Time and Labor Setup Profile \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 114\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3220,'Feature',1031,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Basic Search page for Repeating Time Periods\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1031\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 115\ndescription: \"\\n        <p>User can search Repeating Periods using this feature </p>\\n        <p>Basic search is performed using \'Name\' or \'Period Type\' search fields of the period.  Based on the user input system will run a query to the tables and display the period \\n        information in search restuls grid.</p> \\n        \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3221,'Feature',1032,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Advanced Search page for Repeating Time Periods\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1032\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 115\ndescription: \"\\n                    <p>Lets the user execute advanced queries based on logical operators and wildcards.</p>                     \\n                    <dt>Search can be executed using the following parameters</dt>\\n                    <dd>Name : Name of the Period, it is a text box</dd>\\n                    <dd>Period Type : Type of the period, It is List of Values field with Daily, Weekly, Monthly, Semi-Monthly types.</dd>\\n                    <dd>Description : Description of the period is text box</dd>\\n                    <dd>Start Date : Start date of the period it is a date column</dd>\\n                    <dd>Duration in Days : Period length in days is number field.</dd>                    \\n                    Also allows wildcards in Name and Description based search</ol>\\n                   \\n        \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3222,'Feature',1033,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Search Grid Results\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1033\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 115\ndescription: \"\\n                  <p>Results grid displays repeating period details </p>\\n                  <p>Create/Update buttons and Actions are included in the grid</p>\\n                  <p>Columns of the Search Results Grid are Name, poeriod Type and Description of the Peirod.</p>  \\n                  <p>The search results will initially defaults 10 last repeating periods created.  It also inculdes seed data.</p>\\n                  \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3223,'Feature',1034,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Create Repeating Time Period \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1034\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 115\ndescription: \"\\n                  \'Create\' action or \'Create\' button from the Search Results grid are used to create new repeating periods. \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3224,'Feature',1035,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Edit Repeating Time Period \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1035\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 115\ndescription: \"\\n                  Only the name of the repeating period can be edited, other fields are read only fields.\\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3225,'Feature',1036,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Key logic for Repeating Period \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1036\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 115\ndescription: \"\\n                   User cannot delete existing Repeating Period.\\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3226,'Feature',1037,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Translation \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1037\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 115\ndescription: \"\\n                   Period Name and Period Description fields are translatable.\\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3227,'Feature',1038,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Lunar Month Option \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1038\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 115\ndescription: \"\\n                  To support Lunar month option as payroll, we are giving an option to create 4 weeks period but not real Lunar month(29 day, 12 hours and 44 minutes) \\n                  Real Lunar Month capability -- Feature Release.\\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3228,'Feature',1039,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Cutoff Date \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1039\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 115\ndescription: \"\\n                  <dt>Description:</dt>\\n                  <dd>John raised the possibility of allowing the customer to define a cutoff date for each recurring period. Whilst we do not know the eventual use of a \\n                  repeating period when its defined a cutoff date that was simply used for reporting purposes might not be an issue.<dd> \\n                  <dd>02-DEC-2009 MarkV: Please remind John/Sue about this and ask them if they have come to a conclusion. Also, I would like to know what this cutoff date would be used \\n                  for in OTL. BTW, this functionality is also present in the Payroll Period, again bringing our Period LBA closer to the Payroll Period module, making the need to \\n                  merge them into one HCM application even more useful.</dd> \\n                 <dt> 12/7/09 Sue - Timecard Submission Date/Time Purposes</dt>    \\n                  <dd>   List Date Time the timecard is due on the timecard  </dd>                          \\n                  <dd>   Monitor late timecards which have not yet been submitted compared to due date  </dd>                           \\n                  <dd>   Send notification reminders before due date/time to the employee            </dd>                \\n                  <dd>  Time should be an optional field, some just have submission dates, some use date and time   </dd> \\n                                  \\n                  <dt>5.  A competitive feature UI Suggestions:</dt>          \\n                  <dd>Borrow from Payroll\'s payroll definition with offsets to define cutoff date (# of days on/before/after time period start or end date), \\n                  with ability to override the date.</dd>\\n                  <dd>Determine if we can import payroll definition with regards to period duration, period instances and period cut off date.</dd>                             \\n                  <p>Reference:Payroll Definition FDD from Payroll Next Step to Resolve: John to talk to Sue and propose the details of how a cutoff \\n                  date would be defined for all the period types and propose UI.</p>\\n                  <p>2/11/10 - Action to Sue to write up the reasons for cutoff date and where it would be placed and how the customers would use it and then followup with meeting to discuss with all.</p>                        \\n                  Timecard Submission Due Date.doc   - sent to all interested parties on 2/27/2010 - Sue \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3229,'Feature',1040,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Offset \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1040\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 115\ndescription: \"\\n                     <dt>Description:</dt>\\n                     <dd>Enterprise had the concept of  off set in their repeating period definition, do we need this concept in fusion?  (Sue)\\n                        Offset in Daily Time Period in Enterprise: used for Rolling Periods.  Rolling periods can have overlapping period instances if the offset is negative or there can be \\n                        jumps in period instances if the offset is positive. \\\"Enter the number of offset days. Offset days are used to derive the start date of the next period instance with \\n                        respect to the end date of previous instance. Offsets can be positive or negative. The default for offset days is 1. </dd>\\n                        <dd>If the offset is a negative number, the system counts backwards from the end of the earlier period instance by the number of offset days to determine the start of the next period instance. Any two \\n                        consecutive period instances will overlap if the offset is negative. The absolute value of offset days cannot be equal to or greater than the period length. \\n                        In other words, when the offset days number is negative, the next period cannot start on or before the current period. \\\"\\n                        Rolling periods are for rules processing only, not for time reporting.</dd>\\n                     <dd>Suggestion:  we could offer different  period types: rule period (which allow for offsets) versus time reporting and approval periods whch do not allow offsets. \\n                        Or we can invoke business logic when assigning reporting periods or approval periods, that they cannot assign periods with offsets.</dd>\\n                     <dd>Mitul: 07 Dec, 2009 - Are we going to support only the definition of rolling period given in Issue 16 below? \\n                        How are we going to incorporate support for Rolling Period and Off Set in our UI? We need to remember Overlapping Period also when we talk about Off Set. \\n                        All these three goes hand in hand.</dd>\\n                     <dt>Next Step to Resolve:</dt>\\n                     <dd>Talk to John/Sue 02-DEC-2009 MarkV: Please remind John and Sue. Also, please find out what this does in E and note that on this LBA somewhere </dd>\\n                     <dd>2/11/10 - Do not think it is a priority for v2, will schedule a meeting to discuss this with team, along with item 16, and 17. - Sue)</dd>\\n                     <dd>2/26/2010 - Met on 2/25/2010 with Joel, Mark, Kavitha, Andy, John, Faz on rolling periods and offsets today - We cannot determine requirements for overlapping time periods or period instances which skip days.  I have emailed Anton Graaf today to ask him if there are localzation requirements in rules or elsewhere which require the concept of overlapping periods or periods with skips of days.  \\n                     Most likely this will be scoped out for Fusion v2 unless there are compelling use cases. - Sue</dd>\\n                     <dt>Resolution:</dt>\\n                     <dd>3/10/2010 - have not heard from Anton Graaf at all, as of now no requirement in hand to use offset for period definition for Fusion v2- Sue</dd>\\n                  \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3230,'Feature',1041,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"9-80 \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1041\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 115\ndescription: \"\\n                  <p>9-80 implementation will have an impact on the repeating period adding \'time\' to time period definition, dependent on our 9/80 scheduling/time entry \\n                  requirements 02-DEC-2009.  MarkV: This will actually be handled differently now and does not require these \'time aware periods\' anymore so we can close this. </p>\\n                  <dt>Next Step to Resolve:</dt>  \\n                  <dd>Cover in the 9-80 FDD 2/11/10 - Joel checking with Mark on why we don\'t need time for 9/80 requirements on the time period? - Sue </dd>                      \\n                  <dt>Resolution: </dt>\\n                  <dd>We do not need time aware periods anymore. Faz: At this point 9/80 is not in the V2 scope. but development should have design consideration for that                          \\n                    Sue - are we doing anything for this right now?</dd>\\n                               \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3231,'Feature',1042,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Overlapping Period \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1042\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 115\ndescription: \"\\n                    <dt>Description:</dt>\\n                    <dd> From your previous e-mail, I understand that we will have overlapping period if the offset is negative (and The maximum number of negative offset days \\n                    cannot exceed the period length minus two) and gap into the period when the offset is positive. It becomes interesting when an rolling period is defined \\n                    with an offset First you have to confirm if we will be using offset in Fusion V1.1</dd>                          \\n                    <dd>After the use of the repeating periods with offset, I would like to understand if a timecard or approval period could be set on a period with offset, \\n                    or it is exclusively for rules. Are we generating such period? </dd>                            \\n                    <dd>16-OCT-2008: Andy: I am curious about this offset idea. You are basically trying to set up some kind of structure to the repeating periods. \\n                    I am wondering why, if this is needed, why other things arent, say a 5 day period followed by a 4 day period etc. If we are going to get into this \\n                    kind of complex period definition I think we should just come up with something that allows for any kind of repetition .. . \\n                    danger is that it starts to be a calendar.  </dd>                        \\n                  <dt>Next Step to Resolve: </dt>                           \\n                    <dd>Sue/John/Andy/Mark - Sue:  This issue is linked to Issue 9, once we resolve issue 9, this is resolved as well.  \\n                    An overlapping period does not exist without an offset principle. Overlapping periods would only be for rules and not for time entry or approvals. -                              \\n                    Rolling periods and complex periods are period types supported in Enterprise TL currently.  - 2/26/2010 </dd>                                                \\n                  <dt>Resolution:</dt> \\n                  <dd>3/10/2010 - have not heard from Anton Graaf at all, as of now no requirement in hand to use offset for period definition for Fusion v2- Sue\\\" </dd>\\n                  \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3232,'Feature',1043,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Dependency on PER_TIME_PERIOD_TYPES  \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1043\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 115\ndescription: \"\\n                  <dt>Description:</dt> \\n                  <dd>We need to think about the solution we are providing. In the long run it would seem to make sense to centralize time period definitions and generation in HCM or apps and not \\n                    in specific products (payroll / OTL).</dd>\\n                    <dd>Since payroll is in the same pillar we could continue to have this dependency on period type or simply hard code the period types into the evaluation \\n                    code for performance reasons (we have NEVER had a request for a new period and since these come from payroll I imagine they have never seen such a request either) 02-DEC-2009 \\n                    MarkV: More indications of the similarities between this and Payroll Periods ...  </dd>                         \\n                  <dt>Next Step to Resolve:</dt>\\n                  <dd>Talk to Joel about it </dd>                                            \\n                  <dt>Resolution:  </dt>\\n                  <dd>We will not have any dependencies on per_time_period_types. </dd>\\n                  \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3233,'Feature',1044,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Persistence of Time Periods \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1044\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 115\ndescription: \"\\n                  <dt>Description:</dt>\\n                  <dd>Do we need to move to a payroll-style period model where we store time periods instead of generating them as needed </dd>                                          \\n                  <dt>Next step to Resolve: </dt>\\n                     <dd>Andy: Need to collect period requirements. Where are periods needed and is storage of periods essential? </dd>                      \\n                  <dt>Resolution: </dt>\\n                  <dd>16-OCT-08:We will generate periods and store them. This makes it easier when using payroll balances. It will probably also be helpful as periods become more \\n                  complex</dd>\\n                  <dd>post 1.1 .. offsets .. time component and custom periods where the dates are simply listed out by the customer. </dd>\\n                    \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3234,'Feature',1045,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Do we need repeating periods at all  \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1045\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 115\ndescription: \"\\n                  <dt>Description:</dt>                  \\n                      <dd>Can we use something like the ZMM schedule instead of owning our own periods or try to get the payroll / OTL models merged.</dd>                       \\n                      <dd>16-OCT-08: Feedback from Sue ... you could think of periods as calendars / schedules. Problem is that you could NOT use ZMM as it stands </dd>                            \\n                      <dd>01-DEC-2009 (MarkV): I think we can definitely dismiss the idea of using ZMM, however, I would like us to expand on the idea of using other \\n                      Application\'s periods implementations.</dd>\\n                     <dd> What would be really cool is if in our Period LBA we can point to other applications\' periods. For example, we should be able to define a period as a \\n                     \'Payroll Period\'. </dd>                             \\n                      <dd>All the information of this period is held in payroll, we just reference it in our Period LBA and provide services/APIs to retrieve the periods as needed.</dd>                              \\n                      <dd>Even nicer would be if we can define an \'(Primary) Assignment Payroll Period\' which in essence would link to the Assignment\'s Payroll Period rather than a \\n                      fixed Payroll Period.  </dd>                            \\n                      <dd>We could then use this throughout the product and base e.g. a Timecard Period on the \'Assignment Payroll Period\' which would mean that the Timecard Period \\n                      differs per person because different assignments have different Payroll Periods assigned to them. This way we can define our own periods \\n                      (if we would still need to do this because most of the periods we define exist in Payroll already) and reference any other period in HCM (or even outside). \\n                      Can you please investigate this? </dd>                        \\n                      <dd>Mitul: 03 Dec, 2009 - Payroll Period- Prototype , Live , FDD AdfHcmPayPublicModel.jar contains the related public objects. Finding more information on \\n                      \'Assignment Payroll Period\'. </dd>                        \\n                      <dd>Mitul: 07 Dec, 2009 - Time Defintion - Prototype , Live </dd>                            \\n                      <dd>Mitul: 09 Dec, 2009 - Additional features Payroll Time Definitions provides: Defintion Type : Time Span Takes user input to know whether the periods \\n                      should be generated for past or future and the amount of units to generate ( 7 Days, 2 Weeks, 1 Month, 10 Years ). Allows negative and positive \\n                      adjustments in days to the periods.  </dd>                           \\n                      <dd>Defintion Type : Static Period Takes user input for number of years to be generated. Features Payroll Time Definitions doesn\'t provide: I could not \\n                      see any support for Lunar Calendar.  For us, we always ask for a Reference date, while for them it is always centered to the current date \\n                      (except when the definition type is User Defined Date) We provide more flexibility to allow more user control on how periods get generated. \\n                      For e.g. when type is Multiple Months we allow them to select Start Month and Day. While we can fetch Payroll Time Definition to generate our periods, \\n                      we may not want it to be completely replaced by Payroll Time Definition. Additionally, we can fetch cut-off date/offsets from Payroll Period Definition.</dd>\\n                  <dt>Next step to Resolve: </dt>\\n                     <dd>\\n                      Ask Joel to investigate - though probably difficult to get interest in this from v1  teams at the moment 16-OCT-08: Plan is to bring this up in the Leadership Circle.\\n                      Definitely suggest central entity for HCM. For apps? May talk about periods as schedules / calendars. </dd>                      \\n                  <dt>Resolution: </dt>\\n                  <dd> For V2 we will go with our solution. </dd>\\n                                     \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3235,'FunctionalWorkUnit',115,'destroy','1','--- \nname: \"Time and Labor Setup Changes: Repeating Periods\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 115\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3236,'Feature',1046,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: ConfigComposer_AdminIndivWorkerMgr\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1046\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 116\ndescription: \"\\n               <p>\\n               The Configuration Composer must allow the setup of all entry pages from one consistent set of setup pages.  The Composer will allow:\\n               <ul>\\n               <li>Both admin and individual timecards should be configurable from the Composer pages.\\n               <li>The configuration Composer provides the configurability that was available in R12 (configurability for Admin and individual timecards).\\n               <li>The setup of the Admin page(s) and the individual pages are all defined from the same guided process.\\n               <li>The Configurable Admin Entry pages (batch time entry pages) should continue to look like the current R12\\n               \\xE2\\x80\\x98spreadsheet\\xE2\\x80\\x99 entry page look, where many workers are shown on one page.\\n               </ul>\\n               </p>\\n               \\n               \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3237,'Feature',1047,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: UseDeliveredorConfiguredAttributes\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1047\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 116\ndescription: \"\\n\\\n  <p>The Composer should have the ability to use OTL delivered application attributes, or to define company defined attributes that can be added to the layout pages.  To that end, the Composer must allow:\\n\\\n  <ul>\\n\\\n  <li>The ability to add attributes to the defined layout, including element input values associated to elements.  Ideally the input values displayed is based on the element selected (dependent on the element).\\n\\\n  <li>The components available on the timecard should also include the Projects DFF Component, where the values are added as one \\xE2\\x80\\x98item\\xE2\\x80\\x99 defined by projects.  The exact component look and functionality is still open but is an item OTL will work with Projects to close.  The Projects Standard Cost Collection DFF defines the attributes that may be transferred from OTL to Projects.  OTL Should develop, with Projects Team a process to import the Projects Attributes as Timecard Fields.\\n\\\n  <li>Ability to define new attributes using value sets that are defined as independent, table defined, free text (not validated) and dependent (Dependent on other fields already entered on the timecard).\\n\\\n  <li>Attributes on the time entry matrix may be defined as editable (displayed and editable), viewable (displayed but not editable), or hidden (not viewable or editable), where hidden values are deposited based on some other value selected.  Attributes that are hidden may be deposited based on viewable entries that were entered.  An example is the current Expenditure type / SLF values, where the expenditure type is selected, but the SLF (System Linkage Function) value is also deposited.\\n\\\n  <li>The Composer allows the ability to define the attributes on the time entry pages as either Choice Lists or LOV\\xE2\\x80\\x99s or Choice LOV\\xE2\\x80\\x99s.\\n\\\n  <li>The Composer should have the ability to define value sets that allow for \\xE2\\x80\\x98type ahead\\xE2\\x80\\x99 functionality so that one letter or more can limit selection lists (SHOULD HAVE \\xE2\\x80\\x93 V2 based on ATG component functionality).\\n\\\n  <li>The Composer should have the ability to define selection lists for input values that change based on the element selected in a prior field (e.g., LOV dependencies and setting of contexts).\\n\\\n  <li>The attributes that can be added in the Composers guided process should also include alternate name Timecard Fields defined in Timecard Field Form.Alternate Name Components will be defined and added through the Timecard Field Task, and defined as multiple attribute Timecard Fields.Alternate Name components will be defined for each layout / layout set, and not defined in the Setup Options for a Worker (change from EBS V12).\\n\\\n  <li>The Composer allow the values (attributes and other components) added to the layouts should provide for \\xE2\\x80\\x98properties\\xE2\\x80\\x99 which define characteristics of the component, which can be updated easily during time of configuration.Properties define the component functionality, such as editable, value set, etc.\\n\\\n  <li>The value sets used in the entry matrix may be selected and dependencies defined resulting in value sets \\xE2\\x80\\x98copied\\xE2\\x80\\x99 (customer to copy (or duplicate) based on best practice instructions, so as to not impact other layouts.\\n\\\n  <li>The Configuration Process will deliver a Timecard Field Setup task, that configures time attributes for use in the Configuration Composer\\n\\\n  <li>Time Attributes (timecard Fields) will be delivered for the Work location of State and City / State / County / Zip (as one field for the user to select), stored as separate values and passed to Payroll as an input value.\\n\\\n  <li>OTL will deliver a Rule Override Attribute that will work with the Rule Engine to override rule execution.  Post V2,  another attribute may be introduced to override individual rules NOTE :  All Rules for the Timecard will be overrides by use of the attribute.\\n\\\n  <li>The Composer will allow for the entry of Detail comments (associated to an individual entry) to be:\\n   <ul>\\n    <li>Part of the Detail Page (V2)\\n    <li>A Separate Component, placed on the Timecard to capture only detail level comments (V2)\\n    <li>A \\xE2\\x80\\x98GLIF\\xE2\\x80\\x99 placed in the day cell, where the glif is activated to open a \\xE2\\x80\\x98pop up\\xE2\\x80\\x99 window where the comments and detail entries may be entered, and specific to that field.\\n   </ul>\\n\\\n  <li>Allow for the configuration of extra information on the timecard for the Accrual Balances.  The balances should configurable as:\\n    <ul>\\n    <li>Show all Data from a \\xE2\\x80\\x98More\\xE2\\x80\\x99 link from the timecard (in the Show Accrual Balances section).  The data would be shown in a Popup window.\\n    <li>Show up to 2 balances, with description as to which balances\\n\\\n  <li>The Composer should allow for the placement of an Add Row Icon at the end of a row, to add a new row on the individual timecard, and to add a new row for the person row on the admin, group entry page.\\n\\\n  </ul>\\n\\\n  </p>\\n\\n\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3238,'Feature',1048,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Define/use assignment depositing / setting attributes in the time entry process\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1048\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 116\ndescription: \"\\n               <p>The timecard should allow for the entry of an assignment depositing value that results in other attributes and validation being dependent on the initial assignment selected.  Therefore a delivered component should be available that delivers the depositing of the assignment ID, while showing a meaningful value.\\n\\\n  Time entry configuration for multiple assignment support must include:\\n\\\n  <ul>\\n\\\n  <li>The ability to define the Person, Assignment value on the timecard (either individual or admin entry pages), where the value displayed is easily configured as some value on the assignment record, while the value deposited to the time store is the full assignment, agreement, employment value.\\n\\\n  <li>OTL must deliver an Assignment component that defaults the primary assignment value.  The time entry user may select a different assignment value which then applies to the entries on that \\xE2\\x80\\x98line\\xE2\\x80\\x99  The component should be definable as to what assignment value is displayed for selection.  The component should also allow for the option to be \\xE2\\x80\\x98hidden\\xE2\\x80\\x99, still depositing the default value, used by other components to determine the person\\xE2\\x80\\x99s assignment.  If the component is \\xE2\\x80\\x98hidden\\xE2\\x80\\x99 then the Primary Assignment should be defaulted as the value used.\\n\\\n  <li>The Composer have the ability to add Cost Key Flex values (one or more) \\xE2\\x80\\x93 The flex values are dependent on the assignment information.  Therefore, the Cost Key flex values and assignment values dependency should be easily defined (based on the Person Model FDD).  The Key flex ID should continue to be stored, but the value displayed is based on the assignment entered in a prior field.\\n\\\n  </ul>\\n\\\n  </p>\\n\\n\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3239,'Feature',1049,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Configure Layouts within the Time and Labor Application\\xE2\\x80\\x99s guided process\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1049\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 116\ndescription: \"\\n\\\n  <p>The Composer process in Fusion V2 is seen as providing the following functionality:\\n\\\n  <ul>\\n\\\n  <li>Guided layout set creation should walk the admin through creation, where selection of attributes and selection lists (value sets) that do not exist at time of layout creation should be allowed to be created as part of the setup process without exiting the layout set process (side processes- create in line).  NOTE \\xE2\\x80\\x93 The setup of Timecard Fields (layout specific entry attributes will be a separate task, accessed from the Time Entry Page Composer Manage Layout Sets Task)\\n\\\n  <li>The Composer process allows the setup of layouts accomplished within the application, using delivered ADF pages, where the OTL Setup administrator is guided through the process to define all layouts in a \\xE2\\x80\\x98set\\xE2\\x80\\x99.\\n\\\n  <li>The guided layout creation process to create layouts should allow for searches of layout sets, as well as the parts contained within the layout sets.  For example, search for sets what start with the letter \\xE2\\x80\\x98P\\xE2\\x80\\x99, or search for layouts that contain XYZ value set.\\n\\\n  <li>The creation of layouts should be Effective Dated?\\n\\\n  <li>Guided layout set creation should walk the admin through creation, where selection of attributes and selection lists (value sets) that do not exist at time of layout creation should be allowed to be created as part of the setup process without exiting the layout set process (side processes- create in line).\\n\\\n  <li>The guided process for creating  layouts walks the setup admin through the various sections on the pages, where the different regions may be defined\\n\\\n  <li>The guided setup process should work for the different layout flows, where cla pages are introduced, and configured, as well as whether admin\\xE2\\x80\\x99s see review and or confirmation pages.\\n\\\n  <li>The Guided process for configuring pages should look to \\xE2\\x80\\x98inherit\\xE2\\x80\\x99 values form the entry page for other pages in the entry process (fields become view only) for easier setup.\\n\\\n  <li>The Guided Process should allow for the creation of both Private and Public Templates, based on the time entry page, along with the Detail and Day level comments.\\n\\\n  </ul>\\n\\\n  </p>\\n\\n               \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3240,'Feature',1050,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Configuration Composer defines all regions (parts) of the entry pages\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1050\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 116\ndescription: \"\\n\\\n  <p>The Composer will allow the admin to define all regions.  Exact rules, regions and flow will be addressed in the full FDD sections.  The functionality will include:\\n\\\n  <ul>\\n\\\n  <li>The defining of the Confirmation messages and dialogues should be configurable, based on UX guidelines and whether they display as a banner, message or dialogue requiring a response.\\n\\\n  <li>The setup of the layout may use messages and personalization technology, as well as flex field technology.  The user should not be impacted by the different technology, but rather complete the configuration of a layout set in one process flow.  Stated another way:  the Admin when setting up the layout should not be required to setup certain parts in other pages, processes because they may use different Oracle technology, but rather the setup of the layouts should be from one guided process.\\n\\\n  <li>The layouts should allow for the defining of the following (complete list to follow in complete FDD):\\n    <ul>\\n     <li>Header information \\xE2\\x80\\x93 containing , but not limited to: person info \\xE2\\x80\\x93 that shows many fields, which can be limited (V2), as well as instructional text.\\n     <li><p>Person Information should follow HR guidelines on what the person info has available, as well as allowing the addition of the Timecard Status, and other OTL specific values (Based on Report Time FDD)</p>\\n     <li><p>  Middle region \\xE2\\x80\\x93 containing, but not limited to: Main Period navigation as month selection or calendar, then tabs for time periods around the main selection (selected month / date), template selection functionality, accrual balance displayed, approver overrides, comments at the timecard level.  In addition to new period navigation, the current period list should also be available for companies wanting to continue with the R12 functionality.</p>\\n     <li>Actions for save, submit, change views (layouts) TCR Processing (admin) details, import export of layouts, \\n\\\n  \\tsearch within timecard, freeze sections for scrolling\\n     <li>Review confirmation \\xE2\\x80\\x93 entry summary tables (recap tables)\\n     <li>Labels in both Header and Middle sections \\xE2\\x80\\x93 that are translatable\\n     <li><p>Entry matrix \\xE2\\x80\\x93 containing, but not limited to: attributes (both delivered and company defined), definable totals for rows and columns, labels; over columns (translatable) and for other values defining entries, start / stop, whole hours or both as enterable fields.  The list of attributes should also include the Projects entry component (still to be completely resolved).</p>\\n     <li> Additional details for each cell that is configurable, along with detail level comments.\\n     <li>CLA summary information components for previous and new values.  Based on OTL Delivered Page definition\\n     <li>Definable reason lov / choice lists for cla entry.\\n     <li><p>Defining what is shown on the csv and template pages, so that the other pages inherit the same or less than the entry page.  NOTE \\xE2\\x80\\x93 The import / export of timecard data is based on Fusion ADFdi technology and is addressed in the Report Time FDD.</p>\\n\\\n  <li><p>Period navigation (middle region) allows for defining the tab functionality, where the tab is enabled or not, the periods on the tab (start of period or end) is defined, as well as whether the periods in a month, or on either side of the current active period, such as the period navigation to other months or timecard periods.</p>\\n\\\n  <li>Period navigation that may be selected on the layout should allow for tabs (possibly as a Post V2 option), or the option to not use tabs (current period only).  If no tabs are used, then the period navigation should use the current R12 period navigation.\\n\\\n  <li>Intra Period Navigation as an option to minimize Horizontal Scroll, where the component is placed on the Time Entry Page, based on a Week, and if the timecard Period is a week, then the component displays but has no effect on timecard navigation.\\n\\\n  <li>Period Navigation using a Calendar Widget, either in the Contextual panel (Should Have), and in the Local Panel.  The Selection of a Date will either:\\n\\\n  \\t<ul>\\n\\\n  \\t<li>Navigate to that Day\\n\\\n  \\t<li>Navigate to the Start of the timecard period containing that Date\\n\\\n  \\t<li>Navigate to the Start of the Week that Contains that Date\\n\\\n  <li>Certain components in each section may be defined as required which will be defined as setup business rules.\\n\\\n  <li>Messages and Instructional text will be configurable and translatable, added or modified during the configuration Composer process.  Translated and instructional text is the customer\\xE2\\x80\\x99s responsibility, as currently the case in R12.\\n\\\n  <li>The entry matrix configuration will allow for the reordering, and re-labeling of columns based on company requirements.\\n\\\n  <li>Provide Analytics that display various info to the user, based on the Analytics FDD.\\n\\\n  <li>Provide a Status column for the Admin, based on the person / timecard information.\\n\\\n  </ul>\\n\\\n  </p>\\n\\n\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3241,'Feature',1051,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Configuration Editor Functionality specific to Admin Entry Configurations \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1051\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 116\ndescription: \"\\n\\\n  <p>The Composer must allow the following functionality when defining the admin layout:\\n\\\n  <ul>\\n\\\n  <li><p>Admin entry pages should allow for the deferment of processing, and to force processing of TCR rules \\xE2\\x80\\x93 (Should be addressed in Admin Entry FDD as a possible preference, or as a Configuration Composer option for specific layouts (manager or Timekeeper roles).A Button on the layout is the only possible UI concern).</p>\\n\\\n  <li><p>Admin entry layouts and individual entry layouts should be available in an assigned set, which can be assigned to the admin (Manager, or Specialist (Timekeeper)) for selection as to what layout to use for entry.  Data security may be the guiding process on what is assigned.  Assigning the various layouts to the Admin should be addressed in the Admin Entry FDD \\xE2\\x80\\x93 just added as a note here.</p>\\n\\\n  <li><p>Admin layouts should allow for more attributes than shown to the individual user that may be used for some type of overrides of TCR processing rules.  This is a Must Have for admin batch entry page \\xE2\\x80\\x93 SHOULD Have for Admin Individual  entry page (individual entry page being one that is different than self service sees, and is selected from the list of possible layouts available (assigned ) to the admin)</p>\\n\\\n  <li><p>Admin \\xE2\\x80\\x93 Managers should have the ability to select what entry page is used for a worker or group of workers, either individual pages, where an added person selection component displays the worker selected and has previous / next navigation around the component, or batch pages where the workers all show on one page.  NOTE \\xE2\\x80\\x93 This item is referenced here for the component that should be available when defining the admin batch entry page.</p>\\n\\\n  <li><p>Admin entry may require the use of alternate preference values for editing of entered timecards Preference values would be a value other than what is associated to the individual worker, and what would be assigned to the admin \\xE2\\x80\\x98role\\xE2\\x80\\x99. (SHOULD HAVE V2 \\xE2\\x80\\x93 noted here, but to be addressed in the in the Admin or assign setups FDDs)</p>\\n\\\n  <li>Admin display of review and confirmation pages should be a configurable option defined at time of setup.\\n\\\n  <li>Admin Mass edits should inherit the attributes from the admin batch entry page.\\n\\\n  <li>SHOULD HAVE \\xE2\\x80\\x93 the enabling of the mass edit functionality should be configurable.\\n\\\n  </ul>\\n\\\n  </p>\\n\\n\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3242,'Feature',1052,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: PreviewPage\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1052\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 116\ndescription: \"\\n\\\n  <p>The guided process should allow for the following:\\n\\\n  <ul>\\n\\\n  <li><p>The guided process, as well as the preview of components on the timecard should show all Timecard Fields defined, even if some components (or functionality enabling the components)  may be \\xE2\\x80\\x98turned off\\xE2\\x80\\x99 based on other preference values (override approver or templates for example).  NOTE \\xE2\\x80\\x93 Issue may be the scoping of the Preview page.  Exact delivery of a test, or viewable page is still to be determined.</p>\\n\\\n  <li><p>The guided setup process should allow for the preview of the layout.  The preview may be either as a page is \\xE2\\x80\\x98completed\\xE2\\x80\\x99 or at the end of the process (after each page is defined is desirable).  Value sets values will not be validated during the preview.  NOTE \\xE2\\x80\\x93 Issue may be the scoping of the Preview page.  Exact delivery of a test, or viewable page is still to be determined.</p>\\n\\\n  </ul>\\n\\\n  </p>\\n\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3243,'Feature',1053,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Extract Layout Functionality\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1053\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 116\ndescription: \"\\n\\\n  <p>The configured layouts should be able to:\\n\\\n  <ul>\\n\\\n  <li><p>Be extracted that shows the layout definitions (for all layouts in the \\xE2\\x80\\x98set\\xE2\\x80\\x99) so that problem resolution is available to development when encountering issues.</p>\\n\\\n  </ul>\\n\\\n  </p>\\n\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3244,'Feature',1054,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Admin Group Results Page\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1054\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 116\ndescription: \"\\n\\\n  <p>The Admin, after selecting a group should have the option to see a results page, where they can sort on various columns, or filter what is shown, similar to spreadsheet functionality.  The group result table with the members as \\xE2\\x80\\x98results\\xE2\\x80\\x99 should also be configurable, with a predefined group of columns, displayed in the company\\xE2\\x80\\x99s desired order.  The page should:\\n\\\n  <ul>\\n\\\n  <li>Admin entry will continue to be based on the time entry for groups, with a configurable group results page.\\n\\\n  <li>The Results page should have defined columns that will be displayed, sort able and filterable.\\n\\\n  <li>The sort, select and filter actions on the results page will carry over to the batch or individual entry pages.\\n\\\n  <li>The navigation from the group results page to the entry page should allow the selection of individual or batch entry page as the enterable page.\\n\\\n  <li>SHOULD HAVE \\xE2\\x80\\x93 The Configuration of the results page in the configuration Composer.  The page may have to be delivered and static for Fusion V2 \\xE2\\x80\\x93 though delivering a configurable page is highly desirable.\\n\\\n  </ul>\\n\\\n  </p>\\n\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3245,'Feature',1055,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Configuring the Review and Confirmation Pages\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1055\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 116\ndescription: \"\\n\\\n  <p>The configuration Composer allows the admin to what displays on the review and confirmation pages, and under what circumstances the pages display.  The configuration Composer will allow:\\n\\\n  <ul>\\n\\\n  <li><p>Defining the Review and Confirmation pages with summarized recaps (totals) entered by the user.  For example, defining time categories and displaying the time categories on the review and or the confirmation pages.</p>\\n\\\n  <li><p>Defining the Time Entry Page to have a Time Summary Section, allowing for specific summarization based on a specific attribute type, abstract attributes (work time, non work time) or a combination of attributes  to be displayed in a summarization section, along with in graphical analytic components.</p>\\n\\\n  <li>Define when the Review and Confirmation pages display, and whether they display for the admin in individual entry mode.\\n\\\n  <li>The review and confirmation pages should allow for the display of the same items entered on the time entry page, in read only mode.\\n\\\n  </ul>\\n\\\n  </p>\\n \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3246,'Feature',1056,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Enabling TCR results and Functionality\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1056\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 116\ndescription: \"\\n\\\n  <p>For Fusion V2 the Composer will provide:\\n\\\n  <ul>\\n\\\n  <li>TCR processed results should be an option to add to the review and / or the confirmation page.\\n\\\n  <li><p>The TCR processed results displayed should allow for different displayed values, than those available to the user as enterable values.  For example, the user sees alternate name set containing Regular and Training, while the TCR results region alternate name set shows regular, shift1, overtime and training.</p>\\n\\\n  </ul>\\n\\\n  </p>\\n \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3247,'Feature',1057,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Assigning Layouts to Workers\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1057\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 116\ndescription: \"\\n\\\n  <p>The Final configuration set, configured and named through the guided setup process should be assigned as one set to the OTL user.  The set, if defining a group of individual entry pages should be assigned as a setup option, while the admin layouts should be assigned to administrators in the set of selectable views.\\n\\\n  Admin use of layouts must allow the admin to have different views available, selectable from some selection list, where the layout used is based on the group of workers the admin is entering time for\\n\\\n  </p>\\n \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3248,'Feature',1058,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Ability to define Alternate Names\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1058\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 116\ndescription: \"\\n         <p>The attributes that can be added in the Composers guided process should also include alternate name Timecard Fields defined in Timecard Field Form.  Alternate Name Components will be defined and added through the Timecard Field Task, and defined as multiple attribute Timecard Fields.  Alternate Name components will be defined for each layout / layout set, and not defined in the Setup Options for a Worker (change from EBS V12)\\n         <ul>\\n         <p>Alternate Name (also referred to as \\\"Multiple Attributes\\\") functionality is defined as follows:</p>\\n         <li><p>An Alternate Name Timecard Field may also be referred to as a Multiple Attribute Timecard Field</p>\\n         <li><p>The Alternate Name Timecard Field (ANTF) is defined with an attribute structure consisting of one or more time attributes.</p>\\n         <li><p>The ANTF allows for the time attributes to be either required or not when defining the ANTF values</p>\\n         <li><p>The ANTF allows for a value set (or not) to be associated to each time attribute defined in the structure to be used during setup validation. </p>\\n         <li><p>The ANTF allows for the admin to define ANTF values with a user display value, the time attributes defined in the structure and either enabled or not enabled based on a date range.</p>\\n         <li><p>The ANTF allows for dependent values, the same as a single attribute time attribute field</p>\\n         <li><p>The ANTF allows for duplication of the timecard field.</p>\\n         <li><p>The ANTF allows for the addition of new attributes, as long as existing values do not have the updated attributes, and they are not marked as required.</p>\\n         <li><p>The ANTF does not allow for changes to attribute values when the ANTF timecard field has been used in timecards.</p>\\n         <li><p>The ANTF definition results in a Value Set that may have a modified \\xE2\\x80\\x98where clause\\xE2\\x80\\x99 to restrict the values displayed to different users.</p>\\n         <li><p>The ANTF may be delivered by different applications or a combination of applications, either manually or using a delivered process.</p>\\n         <li><p>The ANTF may be created by the customer, either using the create or Duplicate functionality.</p>\\n         <li><p>The ANTF may be created by the customer, either using the create or Duplicate functionality.</p>\\n         <li><p>The ANTF may be created by the customer, either using the create or Duplicate functionality.</p>\\n                  \\n         \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3249,'FunctionalWorkUnit',116,'destroy','1','--- \nname: Time and Labor Timecard Layout Editor\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 116\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:30'),(3250,'Feature',1059,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Manager Timecard Search page-Manage Timecards\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1059\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> This is the manager\'s timecard search page converted to use \\n        the Oracle Applications Fusion middleware.  This replaces the View Recent \\n        Timecards in EBS Time and Labor R12. This is the search page to access \\n        timecards of  the manager\'s direct reports, with a default display of \\n        status on their most recent timecards.</pre>\\n        \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3251,'Feature',1060,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Manager Timecard Search page-Manage Timecards: Gantt Display\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1060\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> \\n        Allows for an alternate view of the timecard search results in a Gantt\\n chart display.   The user can toggle between the table and Gantt\\n chart view.  This Gantt chart display would allow the user to scroll\\n through time to find timecards for any period of time for which he\\n has access.  There would be additional detail about each timecard\\n as the user clicks on the timecard cell.  There would also be a color\\n coded legend to define what timecard status each timecard block represents. \\n\\\n  The search fields that a user enters in the Search section of the\\n page should reflect the same results on the table or Gantt chart\\n view.  However, the Gantt view can show extended view over a greater\\n period of time, whereas the table view will need a From and To Date\\n defined to narrow the results.\\n\\\n  There will also be the ability to overlay icons on the color blocks\\n to show additional information like \\\"late timecards\\\".\\n\\\n  In the weekly view of the gantt chart, the start and end date of the\\n period can be displayed on the color block for the user to easily\\n see which timecard period the color block pertains to.  There will\\n also be a hover over on each timecard color block with information\\n on the timecard period, the submission date, number of total hours,\\n and approvers.  If the user clicks on a color block once, they will\\n be navigated directly to the selected timecard.</p>  \\n\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3252,'Feature',1061,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Manager Timecard Search page: Manage Timecards- Basic search\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1061\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> Basic search is performed using \'From date\', \'to date\', \'Timecard\\n        Status\' and \'Person Name\'.  Based on the user input system will run\\n a query\\n        to the tables and display the timecards in the gantt chart.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3253,'Feature',1062,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Manager Timecard Search page: Manage Timecards- Advanced search\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1062\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"\\n                    <p>\\tAllows the user the ability to string multiple lines of search attributes together with \\\"and\\\" and \\\"or\\\" statements, using the following search fields and operators, with the ability to configure additional search fields based on added time entry fields.  </p>                     \\n                    <dt>Search can be executed using the following parameters</dt>\\n                    <dd>Detail Comment : Comment of a timecard</dd>\\n                    <dd>Reported Hours: hours reported againts a timecard</dd>\\n                    <dd>Timecard Period: timecard\'s start and end dates</dd>\\n                    <dd>Project: Project information</dd>\\n                    <dd>Timecard Submission Date: submission date</dd>                    \\n\\\n  \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<dd>Timecard Due Date (new for Fusion): timecards validity date.</dd>                    \\n\\\n  \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<dd>Task: Task information of the project selected</dd>\\n\\\n  \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<dd>Timecard Comment: Comment against a timecard.</dd>\\n\\\n  \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\n\\\n  \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<dt>Operators for search</dt>\\n\\\n  \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<dd>Less than</dd>\\n\\\n  \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<dd>Less Than or Equal to</dd>\\n\\\n  \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<dd>Not Equal To</dd>\\n\\\n  \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<dd>Equal To</dd>\\n\\\n  \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<dd>Greater Than</dd>\\n\\\n  \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<dd>Greater Than or Equal To</dd>\\n\\\n  \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<dd>Like</dd>\\n\\\n  \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<dd>Not Like</dd>\\n\\n                    \\n                   \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3254,'Feature',1063,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Manager Timecard Search page: Manage Timecards- Create Timecard\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1063\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Create Timecard action - transfers user to a new timecard  \\n        (also a button on toolbar)</pre>\\n        \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3255,'Feature',1064,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Manager Timecard Search page-Create Timecard Action\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1064\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> Manager must select a worker (choice list of available direct\\n reports in the table)  and then select a date from a calendar widget,\\n to create for the correct timecard period, then be taken to the Create\\n Timecard page for that worker.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3256,'Feature',1065,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Manager Timecard Search page: Sort fields\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1065\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> \\n        Display the most recent timecards on top of the grid.  Ensure the\\n columns are sortable on the grid\\n        </pre>\\n        \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3257,'Feature',1066,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Manager Timecard Search page: Saved searches\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1066\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> \\n        a user will have the ability to save his basic and/or advanced searches\\n for future use.\\n        </pre>\\n        \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3258,'Feature',1067,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Manager Timecard Search page: Approval Data Flow\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1067\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> \\n      Have a column related to the Approval Data Flow of the timecard, with\\n further drill down detail as to where the timecard is in the approval\\n chain\\n        </pre>\\n        \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3259,'Feature',1068,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Manager Timecard Search page: Transfer to field\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1068\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> \\n      ability to see to which time consumers the timecard has been transferred,\\n as a column in the Search Results - Transferred to Payroll, Project\\n Portfolio Management, both, etc.  This is enhancement in 12.1.1.\\n Release to be brought into Fusion.  \\n      </pre>\\n        \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3260,'Feature',1069,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Manager Timecard Search page: Gantt legends\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1069\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \" \\n      <ol>\\n      <dt>The following are the timecard status colors which will be offered for display:<dt>\\n        <dd>\\tDraft</dd>\\n        <dd>\\tIn Error</dd>\\n        <dd>\\tSubmitted</dd>\\n        <dd>\\tApproved</dd>\\n        <dd>\\tRejected</dd>\\n        <dd>\\tTransferred</dd>\\n        <p>Nice to have:  Not Started Box: to indicate timecards which have not \\n        yet been created</p>\\n\\n      \\n        \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3261,'Feature',1070,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Use of Employment Header\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\npriority: \nid: 1070\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> The following are fields which are delivered by default by Core\\n HR:\\n\\n\\\n  Shown By default\\n\\n\\\n  o     Display Name\\n\\n\\\n  o     Person Number\\n\\n\\\n  o     Assignment Number\\n\\n\\\n  o     Job\\n\\n\\\n  o     Position\\n\\n\\\n  o     Department\\n\\n\\\n  o     Location\\n\\n\\\n  o     Manager\\n\\n\\\n  Hidden Fields\\n\\n\\\n  1.     WorkPhoneNumber\\n\\n\\\n  2.     Home Phone Number\\n\\n\\\n  3.     MobilePhoneNumber\\n\\n\\\n  4.     HomeAddress\\n\\n\\\n  5.     NationalIdentifier\\n\\n\\\n  6.     LegalEmployer\\n\\n\\\n  7.     Country\\n\\n\\\n  8.     WorkRelationshipStatus\\n\\n\\\n  9.     WorkEmailAddress\\n\\n\\\n  10.     PersonalEmailAddress\\n\\n\\\n  11.     BirthDate\\n\\n\\\n  12.     MailingAddress\\n\\n\\\n  13.     EnterpriseStartDate\\n\\n\\\n  14.     StartDate\\n\\n\\\n  15.     LegalEmployerSeniorityDate\\n\\n\\\n  16.     WorkingAtHome\\n\\n\\\n  17.     WorkingHours\\n\\n\\\n  18.     StartTime\\n\\n\\\n  19.     EndTime\\n\\n\\\n  20.     AssignmentCategory\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Worker\'s Picture - Although the header is delivered with the default\\n to have the section open for a worker\'s picture to be imported, Time\\n and Labor can hide the picture on the page.  If a picture is to be\\n displayed, it is maintained in two places:  1.  Manage Personal Information\\n - the HR Specialist can upload the picture. 2.  My Portrait - the\\n Worker can upload the picture themselves.  \\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Primary Assignment - The display of the timecard page will be derived\\n from the layout set and timecard period associated to a worker on\\n his Worker Web Time Entry Setup Profile.  This Profile will be assigned\\n to a worker via Group, based on the common component Group functionality.\\n  The connection between the Worker Web Time Entry Setup Profile and\\n group eligibility will be based on the worker\'s primary assignment.\\n  Since the eligibility is based on primary assignment only, the Assignment\\n label should denote in the header that this is the \\\"primary assignment\\\"\\n header information.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  In this way, the person accessing the timecard will understand from\\n which assignment the employment header is based, and also not to\\n expect display of additional employment header information from other\\n assignments.  The entry of time (entries in the timecard matrix)\\n does support multiple assignments and allows the user to report time\\n against any assignment.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Contextual Data - Time and Labor Data fields: display additional fields\\n which are relevant to the timecard for the worker, below the existing\\n employment header fields.\\n\\n\\\n  1.     Timecard period name\\n\\n\\\n  2.     Layout Set\\n\\n\\\n  Reference:  HCM Person Header TUD - http://files.oraclecorp.com/content/AllPu\\n\\\n  blic/SharedFolders/Fusion%20Deliverables-Public/HCM/Core%20HR/TUD/HCM_PER_Pe\\n\\\n  rsonHeader_TUD.doc<pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3262,'Feature',1071,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Status\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1071\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Shows the status of the Timecard. Saved and Submitted are the\\n timestore statuses, but there are additional derived statuses which\\n can be used for providing additional data to the user:\\n\\n\\\n  \\tNew -  Upon entering into a newly created timecard, the status would\\n be displayed\\n\\\n  \\tDraft - Upon save of the timecard, the status would be displayed.\\n\\\n  \\tSubmitted- Upon submitting of the timecard, the status would be submitted\\n\\\n  \\tPending Resolution - new status to denote administrator intervention\\n is needed to resolve errors before timecard can be routed for approval\\n\\\n  \\tApproved - Upon approval of all time entries in the timecard, the\\n status would be approved\\n\\\n  \\tRejected - Upon rejection of 1 time entry, the status would be rejected\\n\\\n  \\tIn Error - Upon 1 hard error in timecard, the status would be in error.\\n  This would occur if there is an offline batch processing of time\\n rules in Group Time Entry or import processing.  Otherwise, for all\\n application validations and time rules, the timecard errors need\\n to be resolved before saving or submitting the timecard.\\n\\\n  \\tTransferred -  Upon successful response reply from the integrating\\n application, the timecard is considered transferred.  The two integrating\\n applications to transfer timecards to include: Payroll, Projects  \\n\\n\\\n  Open Design Issue 1:  To be determined in Time Entry LBA, if will\\n implement the \\\"Transfer To\\\" column information which was implemented\\n in EBS OTL R12.1.2. which states if the timecard has been transferred\\n to \\\"Projects, Payroll, None\\\".  This would separate the Transfer information\\n out of the Timecard Status field into its own Transfer To field. \\n\\n\\\n  Open Design Issue 2:  To be determined if we will add another timecard\\n status of \\\"Pending Resolution\\\" which denote timecards which have\\n errors needing resolution by an administrator or timekeeper before\\n they can be routed for approval.  This is incorporated into the Validations\\n of Processed Time design section.\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3263,'Feature',1072,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"HR Person Contextual Action \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1072\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Uptake the use of the HR Person Contextual Action for any display\\n of the worker\'s name, especially in the Person Header section of\\n the timecard.  Upon clicking on the orange icon to the left of the\\n person\'s name, a pop up dialog box will offer additional information\\n about Leslie for further communication.  Upon clicking the Close\\n button, the dialog box will close.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3264,'Feature',1073,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Message Display\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1073\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Messaging to User - Allow for ability to configure and display\\n messages to the timecard user.   This may be done via the output\\n of Time Interaction Rules.\\n \\n\\\n  a. Tip of the Day - a message type that is offered by some users,\\n which can have different messages displayed to the timecard user\\n on dynamic basis.\\n\\\n  b. Message Section - a section of the timecard needs to be offered\\n to display messages to the timecard user, below the employment header\\n section.  No more than 3 messages can be displayed in the message\\n display area.  Global messages pertaining to the entire timecard\\n should be displayed in this area, if there is no time entry context.\\n\\\n  c. Time Interaction Rules - these types of rules would allow the user\\n to define any conditions to trigger the output of messages to the\\n timecard user and could be assigned to any groups of workers via\\n Worker Core Processing Time and Labor Setup Profile.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3265,'Feature',1074,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Timecard Page Actions \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1074\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>a.  Next button - takes user to the Timecard Review page, from\\n the Timecard Entry page\\n\\\n  b.  Save button - offers Save and Save and Close options\\n\\\n  c.  Cancel - cancels user out of timecard and returns them to prior\\n navigation\\n\\\n  d.  Submit button - enabled on the Timecard Review page, it  will\\n allow the user to submit the timecard.  Validations and rules will\\n be applied upon submission of the timecard.  If there are any resulting\\n errors, the user will be kept on the Timecard Entry page, will have\\n highlighted errors and will need to resolve the errors before successfully\\n resubmitting the timecard.  Once the timecard is successfully submitted,\\n the user will get a confirmation pop-up that the timecard has been\\n successfully submitted and will have an option to print (a read-only\\n review page of the timecard) or click OK.\\n\\\n  e.  Send Timecard for Resolution button (new) - If the user cannot\\n successfully resolve the errors, he should be able to select an action\\n \\\"Send Timecard for Resolution\\\" and this will save the timecard data\\n and route the timecard to an administrator for error resolution.\\n  Upon resolving the errors, the timecard can be resubmitted.  \\n\\\n  \\t\\n\\\n  Open Design Issue:  Save button, whether the label can be \\\"Save as\\n Draft\\\". UX to determine\\n\\\n  Open Design Issue:  Additional button for \\\"Send Timecard for Resolution\\\"\\n to transfer the timecard to an administrator or timekeeper for resolution\\n of errors which the worker cannot resolve (i.e. setup object changes)\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3266,'Feature',1075,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Default Timecard Templates\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1075\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide ability to auto populate timecard with dynamic, private\\n or public timecard templates which are assigned to the worker.  The\\n dynamic templates in scope for Fusion v2 (Work Schedule,  Last Timecard\\n  and Project Resource Management template).  The assignment of templates\\n  will occur in the Worker Web Time Entry Setup Profile (formerly\\n Preferences).\\n\\\n  The worker will be able to change their default template on their\\n Timecard Options in the Timecards Workarea landing page.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3267,'Feature',1076,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Additional Information Sections\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1076\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide more real estate in the timecard page so the user can\\n focus on the timecard matrix for time entry.  As a result, there\\n will be additional pieces of information that a user may want to\\n reference, but not view at all times. These sections should be \\\"information\\n on demand\\\", available to the user when needed.  Such sections include:\\n\\\n  a.\\tTimecard Comments - comments for the overall timecard\\n\\\n  b.\\tAccrual Balances - listing balances for all leave plans the worker\\n is associated to\\n\\\n  c.\\tApproval Comments - comments from each timecard approver. This\\n section should only be displayed if data exists.  If the timecard\\n has not been routed for approval as of yet, the Approval Comments\\n section or dialog box should not be displayed.\\n\\\n  Note : These sections can be either displayed as Pop Up Information\\n Sections or Expandable Sections based on the settings in Time Entry\\n Page Composer.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3268,'Feature',1077,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Accrual Balance Configurable Display\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1077\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Allow for configuration by customer to determine what is displayed\\n in the View Accrual Balance section.  This content display will be\\n determined in conjunction with the Absence Management team. \\n\\\n  The location of the accrual balance display on the timecard will be\\n part of the timecard layout set configuration.  Two of the configuration\\n options for placement of the information is as a section in the contextual\\n area of the timecard entry page, and also in the local area of the\\n page above the timecard matrix.  We will offer an expanded section\\n showing View Accrual Balances with two pre-selected balances displayed,\\n with a \\\"More\\\"  link for the user to click on to view all available\\n balances to be displayed in the timecard.  The \\\"More\\\" link will trigger\\n a pop-up page showing the additional balances if any exist.  If there\\n are no additional balances, no \\\"More\\\" link will be displayed.\\n Some of the configurable items discussed with customers include:\\n\\\n  o\\tDisplay As of Date in Accrual Balance pop up page or expandable section\\n\\\n  o\\tDisplay balances in Units, to allow for balances in hours or days \\n\\\n  o\\tDisplay link to view Accrual Balances, does not resolve balance\\n when open the Timecard page \\n\\\n  o\\t Allow ability to select which balances are displayed in the Timecard\\n\\\n  o\\tAllow for display of beginning balance as of time period, along\\n with any additional unprocessed leave entries in the period, along\\n with ending balance, to give the user the full picture of what leave\\n time remains.  Unprocessed hours would include recorded leave time\\n which is not yet approved or processed in payroll.  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3269,'Feature',1078,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Populated By\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1078\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>This field will be displayed above the timecard matrix to alert\\n the user if a default template has pre-populated a new timecard.\\n  The field will be populated with a read-only text of the Template\\n name.  If the default template could not be used to populate the\\n timecard because the layout set or timecard period of the current\\n timecard do not match the template, next to the template name, there\\n should be an icon, with a hover over explaining the default template\\n does not match the current layout set and timecard period.  There\\n should also be a global message displayed to the user in the Message\\n section of the timecard to alert the user that the default template\\n ccould not be used and to select an alternate default Template on\\n Timecard Options of their Workarea.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3270,'Feature',1079,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Period Message\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1079\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide indication or message to timecard user they are in a\\n prior or future time period.  This needs to be offered in the central\\n messaging section in the Timecard header.  This is a reminder to\\n the user in case they are updating the wrong timecard period.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3271,'Feature',1080,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Submission Due Date\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1080\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Allow for the association of a timecard submission due date and\\n time  to a timecard, so users can be made aware of when they need\\n to submit their timecards.  These due dates can be attached to the\\n repeating period definitions which are associated to the worker in\\n their Setup Options Profile.  \\n\\\n  This Due Date can be used to display in the timecard header.  It can\\n also be used for reminder notifications to workers or timekeepers,\\n and can be used for analytics to determine who are repeatedly late\\n in submitting timecards.  Some users just use timecard due dates,\\n some also associate a time to that date, to ensure that the payroll\\n processing department can plan on when to begin their payroll processes.\\n  If a time is defined along with the date, a time zone may need to\\n be supplied, unless the time is assumed to be the local time or the\\n time zone is derived from the user regional Preferences.\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3272,'Feature',1081,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Mid period display of  Changed Employment Information\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1081\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> Provide ability to see different person information for mid\\n timecard period changes.   This would cover changes that can occur\\n as a result of workers changing paygroups, departments jobs or positions\\n which can occur during a time period .  The user wants to see the\\n old and new data for this change.  \\n\\\n  As we are only displaying employment header data from Primary Assignment\\n in Fusion v2, this would only be applicable for changes to the primary\\n assignment during the timecard period.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3273,'Feature',1082,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Review Page\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1082\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide a table display view of one week at a time.  The days\\n will be displayed vertically on the left hand column and all attributes\\n will be displayed to the right of the days.  Daily detail and comments\\n will be separate columns in the grid.  All data from pop-up pages\\n on attributes and details will be concatenated in an Attributes and\\n Details column.\\n\\\n  If there is more than one week in the review, there should be the\\n ability to collapse each week display, so the vertical scroll of\\n the page is lessened and the user an focus on the detail of one week\\n at a time.\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3274,'Feature',1083,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Change and Late Audit Timecard Flow\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1083\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide ability to enter change and late audit reasons in the\\n defined Audit Entry page for a Change and Late Audit Layout Set,\\n as well as incorporate all of the change and late audit reasons and\\n comments, and show changed time in the Audit Review page.  The flow\\n would be Timecard Entry page, the Audit Entry page, the Timecard\\n Review page, with ability to submit the timecard.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3275,'Feature',1084,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Configurable Sections for Timecard Entry, Review and Confirmation Pages \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1084\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Refer to Time Entry Page Composer FDD for full details.  Some\\n of the requested configurations include:\\n\\\n  a.\\tAbility to collapse by default some sections\\n\\\n  b.\\tAbility to retain order of rows entered by line number in Time\\n Detail section \\n\\\n  c.\\tRule Results - ability to show the hours type against the correct\\n rows \\n\\\n  d.\\tRule Results - ability to have flexibility to show any hour types \\n\\\n  e.\\tTime Summary - would like to see this section on top of the page\\n for Confirmation page\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3276,'Feature',1085,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Printable Timecard\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1085\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> Provide ability to print timecard upon timecard submission.\\n  Customers would prefer to see the time detail in the matrix as you\\n have it normal time entry page, as opposed to vertical columns. \\n All drill down detail sections need to be flattened so they all appear\\n on the printable page.  (Note: UX design in progress, similar to\\n Timecard Review page)\\n\\\n  The printable version of the timecard can be initiated from two places:\\n  1. from the confirmation pop-up displayed upon submission of the\\n timecard 2.  from the Viewable version of the timecard available\\n at any time.\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3277,'Feature',1086,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Configurable fields in timecard\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1086\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide ability to display appropriate fields in timecard matrix\\n based on delivered layout.  The use of delivered layouts will depend\\n on the configurability offered in the Layout Editor FDD for Timecard.\\n  ( See Appendix A for existing delivered layouts from R12.)  The\\n ability to configure the display of each section of the timecard\\n online is new for Fusion.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3278,'Feature',1087,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Attribute Storage and Pre-population of values\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1087\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>We will have the ability to offer entry in the timecard to perform\\n any of the following functions:\\n\\\n  o\\tcontain a single attribute with a related value set, which contains\\n a where clause to filter the displayed values as needed\\n\\\n  o\\tcan link a single attribute to another single attribute on a layout\\n set (these linked attributes can be displayed or hidden on the timecard).\\n  As these attributes are linked, the entry of one attribute value\\n can default the value of the 2nd or related attribute\\n\\\n  o\\tcontain an attribute which is displayed on the timecard, which can\\n store but not display values for related attributes \\n\\\n  o\\tcan have an attribute automatically populated with a default value,\\n upon entry into the timecard based on the person\'s information\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3279,'Feature',1088,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Override Default Regional Preferences\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1088\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>As per setup in the Timecard Layout Sets, allow for users to\\n be able to enter time in different formats  and decimal precisions\\n for dates, time, numbers, timezone and currencies.  The default regional\\n preferences are delivered by ApplCore from the main Preferences menu\\n link.  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3280,'Feature',1089,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Smart choice lists\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1089\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>All time attributes which previously used LOVs must have values\\n displayed with smart choice lists, including all descriptive flexfields.\\n  This is a Fusion requirement for UI.  These smart choice lists will\\n list values such as Most Recently Used values before showing a search\\n link to search for more entries.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3281,'Feature',1090,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Display hours and clock times\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1090\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Must Have Justification :  Support Existing EBS OTL R12 functionality\\n of clock and hours display\\n\\\n  Provide ability to support a mixture of reporting hours and start/stop\\n times with the correct related totals for the day.  For each entry\\n there should either be a set of times or hours displayed.  Format\\n of time should support military or civilian display.\\n\\\n  If the set of times (Start and Stop Time) is entered, then we need\\n to allow that entry of time,  can be used as a Stop Time for a Start\\n Time as well as be used as a Start time for the next set of Start\\n and Stop Times.  For example: \\n\\\n  8:00 am\\t\\tStart\\n\\\n  10:00 am\\tStop\\n\\\n  10:00 am\\tStart\\n\\\n  12:00 pm\\tStop\\n\\\n  In this example, 10:00am is used as a Stop time for one set of times,\\n and a Start time for the next set of times reported..\\n\\\n  If the user does enter Start and Stop Time for a time entry, they\\n should not be entering hours for that same entry.  The entry of hours\\n or times are mutually exclusive.  As a result, if times are entered\\n we could gray out the hours field for that entry to ensure the user\\n does not enter both.  The same is true for entering hours, we could\\n gray out the Start and Stop Times field for that entry.  If this\\n is not feasible, then we need to ensure we have time entry rules\\n to generate an error message when a user enters both times and hours\\n for the same time entry.\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:31'),(3282,'Feature',1091,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Actions - Add\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1091\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide ability to add  one or more rows in timecard matrix for\\n time entry.  The rows may need to be inserted between existing rows\\n or would be new rows for additional entry.   The row needs to be\\n added where the user expects, either in between existing rows or\\n as the last row.   \\n\\\n  In prior versions of Enterprise Time and Labor and EBS Time and Labor,\\n new rows were added at the end of existing rows.  Rows could also\\n be inserted between existing rows.  Additionally, users could tab\\n to a + (plus) sign on existing row to add a new row below it.  This\\n action worked well for users who are used to tabbing through their\\n timecard fields for quick entry of time.\\n\\\n  The Fusion table design pattern is to add a new row at the top of\\n a table using the add action button.  To allow flexibility for users,\\n we need to offer configuration which allows \\\"add row\\\" to add to the\\n bottom of the table, or to the top of the table.  Adding a row to\\n the bottom of the table is important for clock time users to see\\n the clock times displayed in ascending order.  It is also a general\\n expectation of timecard users to add rows to the bottom of their\\n timecard.  Additionally, we need to allow for an add row icon at\\n the row level, for users to tab to the field and click enter to add\\n a new row below.  This is important for those reporting many rows\\n in a single timecard or timekeepers entering many entries per worker\\n or workers.   The need for this flexibility arose from strong customer\\n feedback,  registered in the HCM_Time&Labor_Usability_Feedback_Report_FINAL.\\n\\\n  doc\\n (3/26/2010)\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3283,'Feature',1092,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Actions - Delete\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1092\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide ability to select a row in the timecard matrix and select\\n the action of deleting a line to delete highlighted row.  User should\\n be able to delete one or more rows at once, based on rows selected.\\n  Once the user selects the action to delete, a warning message will\\n be issued to the user.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3284,'Feature',1093,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Actions - Clear Hours\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1093\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>This new timecard action was tested with customers and accepted\\n in the HCM_Time&Labor_Usability_Feedback_Report_FINAL.doc.  This\\n allows the user to select any or all rows in the timecard and clear\\n out the hours.  The usefulness of this action is the user can retain\\n attributes from prior timecards and just change the hours.  \\n\\\n  For the user who wants to clear one row, he should select the row\\n and use the timecard menu action of \\\"Clear Hours\\\", or use the toolbar\\n icon.  If the user wants to clear all hours for the timecard,  he\\n should be able to select all rows of the timecard and use the Clear\\n Hours action.  A message should pop-up to the user to alert them\\n to the fact that all hour entries will be reset to zero.  Please\\n refer to the Select All Fusion Guideline for selecting all rows whether\\n visible or not:\\n\\\n  http://stux.us.oracle.com/blaf/guidelines4/tblInteraction.html#selectAll\\n\\\n  From the Guideline:  When both row and column selection are implemented,\\n clicking the intersection of the row and column headers selects all\\n rows in the table\'s entire data set, regardless of whether they are\\n in view or not. However, there may be a design limitation if the\\n number of rows in the timecard exceed 300 rows: Note: In order to\\n turn on the Select All functionality, the SQL statement must include\\n an OrderBy and the table must have less than 300 rows.\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3285,'Feature',1094,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Actions - Duplicate\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1094\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>To allow the user to select a line to copy.  The user selects\\n the line to duplicate, and selects the action of duplicate.  A line\\n will be inserted below the selected line, with the same attributes\\n and hours and a new line number.  Would also like to be able to highlight\\n multiple rows and select duplicate to be able to copy down multiple\\n rows.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3286,'Feature',1095,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Actions - Save As Template\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1095\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Existing Timecard Action in EBS R12.  Allow user to save time\\n entries as a private template which can be applied in future.  User\\n just has to save a name against the private template.  If the user\\n is utilizing a semi-monthly or monthly timecard and saves that timecard\\n as a private template, only the attributes will be saved for use,\\n as the hours cannot be applied correctly from one period to the next.\\n  A business message will be displayed to the user, upon clicking\\n OK,  that \\\"Only atrributes will be saved for this template based\\n on timecard period length\\\".</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3287,'Feature',1096,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Actions - Apply Template\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1096\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Existing Timecard Action in EBS R12.  Allows user to select a\\n private, public or dynamic timecard template and apply to the timecard.\\n  The public templates are created by a Time and Labor administrator\\n and are assigned to workers via a Setup Options Profile.  Private\\n templates are created by the worker for his exclusive use.  This\\n action will be a menu-action, as well as a button on the toolbar\\n which will trigger a pop-up display.  The reason to offer as a button\\n is it is a regularly used function on the timecard.\\n\\n\\\n  The Apply Template pop-up will have the following actions for the\\n user to take:\\n\\\n  1.\\tSelect a template (private, public or dynamic)\\n\\\n  2.\\tSelect Apply Only Attributes - When selecting a template which\\n contains time attributes and hours, this option allows the user to\\n just apply the attributes displayed on the template, and not apply\\n the hours.\\n\\n\\\n  3.\\tSelect Append , Replace or Cancel as actions\\t\\n\\\n  o\\tAppend  (Add to Entries):  When a user selects this option for applying\\n the template, the content of the template will be added to existing\\n data which is in the timecard matrix.  The new data from the template\\n should be added below the existing data, as per behavior in EBS R12.\\n\\\n  o\\tReplace: When a user selects this option for applying the template,\\n they are replacing all existing data in the timecard matrix and adding\\n the data from the selected template.\\n\\\n  o\\tCancel: Cancel out of the pop-up and close the pop-up\\n\\n\\\n  The private and public templates displayed for use will be derived\\n from the layout set and timecard period assigned to the employee.\\n  If the timecard period associated to the worker does not match private\\n or public templates, they will not be made available in the template\\n selection.   Dynamic templates are not dependent on timecard periods.  \\n\\\n  The timecard user can also navigate to Manage Templates page and create\\n a new private template from scratch.  Dynamic timecard templates\\n which come delivered with the product are:\\n\\\n  1 Work Schedule - This template generates time and labor entries from\\n the worker\'s\\n\\\n  Schedule.  The schedule will now be derived from the person schedule\\n assignment in Core HR, so we need to ensure holidays as well as scheduled\\n work and off days are properly displayed in the timecard.\\n\\\n  2  Last Period Timecard - This template uses the previous time entry\\n data. You\\n\\\n  typically use this template when an employee is working on the same\\n projects week after week, eliminating the need for repetitive entry\\n of project and task numbers.\\n\\\n  3 Project Assignments - This template generates time and labor entries\\n from the\\n\\\n  project, type, and hours information held in Oracle Project Resource\\n Management for the worker\'s assignments. \\n\\\n  \\tIn addition to the ability to choose from private, public or dynamic\\n timecard templates, there are other actions a \\tuser can take.  \\n\\\n  ??\\tSet As Default:  User can select one of the timecard templates as\\n the default template.  This action allows the user to have that template\\n automatically prepopulate the timecard for every future timecard\\n created, unless the default is changed or no longer selected.  The\\n selection of the default template will be an action on the worker\\n Timecards Workarea landing page, in a Timecard Options portlet. \\n See Analytics FDD for Workarea functionality.\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3288,'Feature',1097,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: View Menu Options - Freeze, Sort, Detach\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1097\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Enable the following view menu actions for the timecard matrix- \\n\\n\\\n  Freeze - Allow the user the ability to freeze columns within the timecard\\n matrix and for that display to persist from session to session. \\n There would be a menu action and toolbar action to allow the user\\n to enable the freezing of columns.  The user will highlight the column\\n he wants to freeze on, and selects the Freeze action from the toolbar\\n or menu action.  All columns to the right of that frozen column can\\n be scrolled across horizontally, while the columns to the left  of\\n the frozen column will remain static.  This is the same concept if\\n you used \\\"Window, Freeze Panes\\\" action in an excel spreadsheet.\\n\\\n  For this timecard example below, the user could freeze the Hours Type\\n column, so that all the days to the right of the Hours Type column\\n could be scrolled to the left, while the user could still see the\\n Project, Task, Expenditure Type and Hours Type he entered on that\\n row.  This functionality would allow the user to keep the context\\n of what he is entering for each day.\\n\\n\\\n  Sort - Allow user to sort the columns in the timecard matrix in ascending\\n or descending manner.  Each column heading would have a sort indicator\\n to note that the column can be sorted in an ascending or descending\\n manner.  Example of sort display can be seen in the display of the\\n column \\\"Contract Number\\\" below, in which when the column is highlighted,\\n a black arrow pointing down is displayed, and 2 white arrows are\\n shown to the right of the column header to allow the user to sort\\n ascending (up arrow) or descending order (Down arrow).  Note: Not\\n all fields will be sortable in the timecard, the ability to sort\\n the field will be configured in the layout component and  layout\\n set in the Time Entry Page Composer.\\n\\n\\\n  Detach - this viewing function supports the ADF table component to\\n allow a user to click on a Detach action from the Timecard Matrix\\n toolbar.  This will maximize the table display to enhance the viewing\\n of the timecard columns.  This action is available from the View\\n drop down menu as well as the toolbar.  This table action is formerly\\n known as Maximize.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3289,'Feature',1098,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Line Numbers\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1098\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Display line numbers in the timecard matrix which would assist\\n in identifying lines for error messages, as well as easy reference\\n to a line in question for review or troubleshooting.  If a user inserts\\n a new row in between existing rows, then the new row and subsequent\\n rows would need to be renumbered accordingly. </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3290,'Feature',1099,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Inline Error Messages\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1099\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Allow for easy inline error messages for invalid time, with indications\\n on the reported cells.  The inline error messaging should allow for\\n the highlighting of any field in the timecard matrix, including a\\n particular entry of hours or Start and Stop times.\\n\\\n  Offer a \\\"Show Messages\\\" button as a way to get the \\\"error message\\n list\\\" dialog . Also, the user will have the dialog box open when\\n they access the timecard entry page if there are existing errors.\\n  Will also have the dialog expanded when selecting the  Next button,\\n if error messages still exist.\\n\\\n  If the user clicks on the message link and is taken to the line in\\n error, he should always be able to access the error message listing\\n dialog, to view all messages again.\\n\\\n  Message Summary: Including columns for Line Number, Description, Message\\n Type and Source of Error  along with the Error Message Listing. The\\n contents of the Error Message listing should include the following:\\n\\\n  o\\tline number of the error message, displayed in the timecard matrix\\n\\\n  o\\tmessage type (error, warning, informational, other)\\n\\\n  o\\tsource of the error message (application),\\n\\\n  o\\tdate of the error if applicable.  \\n\\\n  o\\trecommended action for the error condition, if applicable\\n\\\n  o\\tcounter of number of error/warning/information messages\\n\\\n  o\\tability to navigate to each message from the dialog box\\n\\\n  o\\tAs the user views each message per line, he should be able to select\\n that message and be transferred to the relevant line in the timecard\\n matrix.  This pertains to line level messages only.  If global level\\n messages are displayed, no line navigation would be available.  The\\n navigation to the applicable line in the timecard matrix could occur\\n by either highlighting that row in the error message display or have\\n the message hyperlinked.  If the message is hyperlinked, once the\\n user clicks on the link, the cursor should move to that line in the\\n timecard matrix.\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3291,'Feature',1100,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Daily Details  Icon and Pop Up Page\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1100\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide ability to drill down into daily details for the Timecard\\n to enter additional fields required by retrieving applications (DFFs).\\n  The display will be on a daily basis, to allow the user to have\\n different entries for each day listed on the timecard matrix row.\\n  This can be done with a Daily Details icon at the end of each row.\\n   Only the days which contain hours or time entries should be displayed\\n on the Daily Details pop-up for display.  That will make it easier\\n for the user to only enter detail for the days which are required. \\n\\\n  In the Daily Details, we will also have a Comments field for each\\n day for daily comments as well.  Initial prototypes tested at customer\\n feedback sessions in January 2010 had separate icons for Daily Comments\\n and Daily Details, to easily differentiate the two areas of entry.\\n  To consolidate columns, the two areas are being combined into the\\n Daily Details icon.\\n\\\n  Additionally, there should be a hover over the icon for the user to\\n see the attributes which are contained inside the pop-up page for\\n entry as an easy reference.  \\n\\\n  Finally, so the user or approver knows if there is data contained\\n in this pop-up page, there should be different modes of the icon,\\n one to display when the pop-up page has no data entered, and another\\n to display when the pop-up page does contain data.\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3292,'Feature',1101,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Additional Attributes Icon and Pop Up Page\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1101\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Allow for configurable option to display one  pop-up page in\\n the matrix to display dependent fields of a previously entered time\\n attribute or additional optional attributes which the user did not\\n want placed on the main timecard matrix.  This information is at\\n a row level, pertaining to all hours entered on that row.  Examples\\n of dependent fields are input types for Elements or \\\"estimate to\\n complete\\\" for a Project ID.\\n\\\n  Additionally, there should be a hover over the icon for the user to\\n see the attributes which are contained inside the pop-up page for\\n entry as an easy reference.  \\n\\\n  Finally, so the user or approver knows if there is data contained\\n in this pop-up page, there should be different modes of the icon,\\n one to display when the pop-up page has no data entered, and another\\n to display when the pop-up page does contain data.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3293,'Feature',1102,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Work Location Attribute\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1102\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>For Payroll use, we will offer a Work Location layout component,\\n which will offer a smart choice listing of concatenated values: city,\\n state, county and zip code.  The reason for the concatenated values\\n is for easy entry, so that the user does not need to enter 4 separate\\n fields.  Additionally, we should see if we can add \\\"smart filtering\\\"\\n in which not all work location combinations have to be shown to each\\n employee, if there is a way to filter that list per person.  \\n\\n\\\n  These values will be stored separately as City, State, County and\\n Zip Code in Time and Labor.  When they are transferred to Fusion\\n Payroll, they will be transferred into the appropriate fields: Area1,\\n Area2, Area3 and Area4. \\n\\n\\\n  This combination of values  is specifically for use by the US Localization\\n for Payroll.  Other localizations will use this functionality as\\n well, with ability to use different input values based on the localization,\\n but always utilizing Area1 - Area4 fields.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3294,'Feature',1103,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Report Absences\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1103\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>If not integrating with Absence Management, should be able to\\n report an absence by using Hours Types of Absence values and enter\\n a number of hours against that absence in the Timecard Matrix.  If\\n integrating with Fusion Absence Maangement, the absence display,\\n entry, validation,  approval  and retrieval of absences will be determined\\n further in Time & Labor and Absence Integration FDD.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3295,'Feature',1104,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Default Timecard Period Display\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1104\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Must Have Justification :  Support EBS OTL R12.1 Enhancement\\n\\\n  A user will be brought into a worker timecard via the timecard period\\n predefined for the user.  Based on Time and Labor Setup Profile Options,\\n the worker, manager and timekeeper can have different default time\\n periods associated to them.  \\n\\\n  EBS OTL R12.1 Enhancement Options: \\n\\\n  o\\tPeriod On or After System Date- Sets the open timecard period from\\n current date for a new timecard\\n\\\n  o\\tEarlier Period Prior to System Date-Sets the earliest not entered\\n timecard period prior to system date for a new timecard\\n\\\n  o\\tClosest Period Prior to System date-Sets the closest not entered\\n timecard period prior to system date for a new timecard\\n\\\n  Example of each of these options:\\n\\\n  Assuming the system date is 15-Mar-2008\\n\\\n  o\\tPeriod on or after System Date: Current timecard for March 17-March\\n 23 would be opened as Timecard for March 15 is already entered.\\n\\\n  o\\tClosest Period Prior to System Date:  Would backtrack from system\\n date and open the timecard period which is not yet entered, like\\n Feb 11 to Feb 17.\\n\\\n  o\\tEarliest Period Prior to System Date: Would start from the first\\n timecard period and open the timecard period which is not entered.\\n In this case assuming all timecards for year 2007 have been entered\\n excepting the last period, it would default to Dev 31 to Jan 06 period.\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3296,'Feature',1105,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Project Portfolio Management-Related choice lists\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1105\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Allow for the display of 10-15 values in the choice list, before\\n needing to use the Search functionality at the bottom of the choice\\n list.  Ensure values displayed are active,  which are not end-dated\\n (Project and Task fields as example).   The values for the choice\\n lists should be seeded with value sets from Project Portfolio Management,\\n to ensure the values are applicable for the workers, based on security\\n and other Project Portfolio Management criteria such as:\\n\\\n  a.\\tResource\'s association with the project (assignment or team member,\\n etc.) \\n\\\n  b.\\tStatus of the project\\n\\\n  c.\\tDefined transaction controls (if not too big of  performance hit\\n - Transaction controls are whether or not you can charge to certain\\n projects and tasks. Not everyone uses transaction controls. example:\\n What can I charge to this expense.)</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3297,'Feature',1106,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Uptake of Project Portfolio Management Descriptive Flexfield\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1106\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>(aka Standarized Cost Collection - whereby the configuration\\n in PPM will drive the PPM fields that will be \\\"turned on\\\" on the\\n timecard.)\\n\\\n  there will be a Descriptive Flexfield from Oracle Project Portfolio\\n Management which will contain various Projects segments which can\\n be displayed or used on the timecard.  The selection of the segments\\n by the customer will generate timecard layout components which will\\n be available for timecard usage.  See Time Entry Page Composer FDD\\n for more information on the generation of timecard layout components\\n from the Project Portfolio Management DFF setup.    See Appendix\\n F:  Projects Descriptive Flexfield Segments for all of the possible\\n flexfield segments that can be made available for entry in the timecard\\n matrix.\\t\\n\\\n  \\tNOTE:  For the first Fusion version for Time and Labor, timecard entry\\n will be limited to assignments in the same Project Portfolio Management\\n Business Unit as the primary assignment.   If time needs to be entered\\n for a secondary assignment that is not in the same BU as the primary\\n assignment, the time will need to be entered directly into Project\\n Portfolio Management via pre-approved batches or Excel Integration.\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3298,'Feature',1107,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Project and Task Code and Description Display\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1107\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Allow for the configuration of displaying the Project Code and\\n Description as concatenated together in the choice list display,\\n  and the same for the Task Code and Description from Project Portfolio\\n Management.  This is part of the OTL R12.1 Enhancements -OTL UI Enhancements\\n (HRMS-OTL-35)\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3299,'Feature',1108,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Task Reference Data\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1108\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide additional reference information for the user on the\\n reported task, such as the following information in a hover over\\n on the task field.  If cannot display as a hover-over, then display\\n in contextual section of page when user clicks on the task value.\\n  This is a request from the Project Portfolio Management team, and\\n is dependent on the views provided by Project Portfolio Management.\\n\\\n  o\\tTask Number\\n\\\n  o\\tTask Name\\n\\\n  o\\tTask End Date\\n\\\n  o\\tTask Manager with contact information (contact information is provided\\n via the Person Contextual Icon which offers email and chat information)    \\n\\\n  o\\tEstimated Finish Date \\n\\\n  o\\tActual Start Date \\n\\\n  o\\tPlanned Finish Date\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3300,'Feature',1109,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Uptake of Project Portfolio Management Contextual Icon\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1109\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>In order to display more information to a worker about the reported\\n project, the contextual icon related to the Project Number or Name\\n should be adopted for the display of the Project.  The contextual\\n action will launch a pop up page which will display more information\\n about the project, including the Project Manager, estimated and actual\\n dates.  The Project will need to be selected from the Smart Choice\\n list before the contextual action can be enabled for display. \\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3301,'Feature',1110,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Project Portfolio Management Transaction Controls\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1110\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Allow for immediate validation of Project Portfolio Management\\n fields against delivered Project Transaction Controls.  If controls\\n are based on the combination of a Project and Task entry,  then the\\n validation will be available after entering the Task.  If Project\\n Portfolio Management performs transactions controls during submit,\\n or performance is an issue, then the validation would happen when\\n Project Portfolio Management validation service is available. \\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3302,'Feature',1111,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Project Combination Favorites\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1111\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> Allow for display of projects used in last 5 timecards (like\\n Favorites).  Offer  combinations of Project, Task and Expenditure\\n Type values which are recently entered together, which can be selected\\n from for quick entry in the timecard.  This could be a section of\\n \\\"preferred data combinations\\\" listed in the Contextual section of\\n the page.\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3303,'Feature',1112,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Project Portfolio Management Progress Fields for Time Reporting\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1112\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>  In addition to the use of the Project Portfolio Management\\n Descriptive Flexfield for time entry, there are additional fields\\n which Project Portfolio Management would like to be available for\\n timecard entry, such as the following Progress fields which are related\\n to a combination of reported Project and Task.  The uptake of these\\n fields are listed in priority order below:\\n\\\n  High Priority:     \\n\\\n  Estimated Time to Complete (remaining work) \\n\\\n  Progress notes (per Task) - use the Common Notes component delivered\\n by CRM to record Progress Notes per Task\\n\\n\\\n  Medium Priority:            \\t\\n\\\n  Estimated finish date\\n\\\n  Physical Percent % complete\\n\\n\\\n  Low Priority\\n\\\n  Progress status\\n\\n\\\n  These fields may be more relevant for manager entry than worker or\\n timekeeper entry, so may need to be marked as \\\"manager\\\" only timecard\\n layout components.\\n \\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3304,'Feature',1113,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Contextual Timecard Assistance\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1113\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide contextual help to the user for timecard entry: include\\n explanation of difference of saving versus submitting a timecard;\\n timecard submission due dates (if functionality exists); how to update\\n a timecard with errors; how to use the filter to find time entries\\n in error. \\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3305,'Feature',1114,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Configurable Row and Column Totals\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1114\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Allow the user the ability to configure what hours are added\\n to the row and column totals in the timecard.   Example:  a user\\n wants to see work hours as the totals, without counting the meal\\n hours they are reporting.  The totals would overstate hours because\\n it includes more hours types than is wanted.  One option is to allow\\n for configurable total sections which have different labels per \\\"total\\n type\\\" and allow for time categories to build those totals behind\\n the scenes.\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3306,'Feature',1115,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Allow for Suppressing Time Entries by Role\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1115\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>By using an  \\\"administrator-only entry\\\" flag in Group Time Entry,\\n the user can denote which entries are made by the timekeeper or manager.\\n  This will allow filtering of time entries based on who made the\\n entries, if not all entries should be displayed in the timecard to\\n the worker.   These entries would also need to be excluded from timecard\\n totals for the worker as well.\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3307,'Feature',1116,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Totals Auto-Update\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1116\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Allow for timecard totals to be updated (row and column totals)\\n as users tab out of hours or time entry fields.  (Note:  this could\\n be a performance concern, to be evaluated during construct) \\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3308,'Feature',1117,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Total Scheduled Hours for Timecard Period\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1117\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> Display total scheduled hours per day below the Total Timecard\\n Hours, for a quick comparison of reported to scheduled hours. \\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3309,'Feature',1118,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Holiday Display on Timecard\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1118\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> Alert  the timecard user which days in the timecard period are\\n holidays, so time is reported appropriately.  The following are three\\n options which were discussed with customers, with the first option\\n being preferred.\\n\\\n  a.\\tOption 1:  Show holidays for the week in the column headings of\\n the time matrix (by color or text or icon)  with a hover over with\\n the holiday description.\\n\\\n  b.\\tOption 2: Show holidays in calendar widget used for selecting timecard\\n period \\n\\\n  c.\\tOption 3:  Show holidays in contextual section of the timecard\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3310,'Feature',1119,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Disabling Fields\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1119\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Offer ability to gray Hours field for certain Hours Types which\\n should only use Start and Stop Times.  This could be accomplished\\n with the use of Time Interaction Rules.\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3311,'Feature',1120,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Auto Formatting of Fields\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1120\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Offer ability to enter a limited or shorthand format for time\\n or hours field and let the field auto format.  For example:  allow\\n for entry of 9 in Start Time and let 9:00 get populated in the Start\\n Time field, based on the defined format for that field.   The format\\n of the field still needs to be in sync with the attribute it is stored\\n against. \\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3312,'Feature',1121,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Shortcut Entry Methods within Timecard\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1121\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>  For the purpose of users who enter  sets of related time attributes,\\n it would improve the efficiency of time entry to offer shortcuts\\n for the population of related fields.  A set of  related values may\\n be entered often by the user, so it would be helpful to allow the\\n user to string them together with a shortcut or combination code.\\n  For the business, there may be a set of related attribute values\\n which are valid for the worker entry.  \\n      In this scenario, the administrator could setup a list of the related\\n attribute values which are relevant for the user and associate them\\n to a shortcut or combination code. This scenario is often true for\\n customers with Project Portfolio Management, who have multiple Project\\n Attributes which are related to each other.  In either scenario,\\n the combination codes which are created have to be unique to the\\n set of attribute values to which they are associated to.  There also\\n has to be a way of refreshing the list of combination codes, as the\\n related values may no longer be valid, as they may have been closed\\n or inactivated.   Additionally, the related attributes may be display\\n only or may be editable by the user.   Below are a few different\\n design options for allowing for the creation of the combination or\\n shortcut code.\\n\\\n  o\\tCombination Code Self-Entry on Template - Add an optional field\\n on the Public and Private Templates within the timecard matrix, to\\n let the user enter a short code that would label the set of attributes\\n they are entering on that line.  Then that code can be used later\\n by the user in timecard entry.\\n\\\n  o\\tCombination Code Self-Entry on Timecard - Add an optional field\\n for \\\"combination code\\\" to the left of the time attributes in the\\n timecard matrix, so the user can enter a code for that set of attributes\\n and then use it later.   In future use of the \\\"combination code\\\"\\n field, all the values that the user entered would be available for\\n his entry.  Once he selected a combination code, the other related\\n time attributes would automatically be populated.  There would need\\n to be some business rules set in place for the saved combination\\n codes, that they were unique, for the set of values being entered.\\n\\\n  o\\tDynamic Alternate Name Set - Enhance the Alternate Name Set so that\\n an administrator can enter a simple code when setting up the Alternate\\n Name values, which can be associated to a set of time attribute values,\\n which can be displayed or not displayed on the timecard matrix. \\n In the Timecard, the Combination Code can be displayed as the \\\"editable\\\"\\n field for entry, using the alternate name set as the choice list,\\n and the related fields would be displayed or not, as per the setup\\n of the Alternate Name.\\n\\\n  There may be a long list of related values which require combination\\n codes to be associated to them.  In this case, there might need to\\n be a batch process to auto-generate unique combination codes for\\n a long list of combinations of values.  There will also need to be\\n a validation process to ensure each value in the combinations is\\n still valid for use.  \\n\\\n  o\\tMost Frequently Used - Allow for user configuration of time attributes\\n to link together to reference for \\\"most frequently used\\\" values.\\n  The display of these values can be auto-generated by the system\\n based on previous usage.  This combination of values can be accessed\\n by the user to apply to new rows of data.\\n\\\n  o\\t\\\"My Favorites\\\" - Values - Allow for user configuration of time attributes\\n to link together for reference for favorites.  As the user enters\\n a combination of values, they should be able to mark them as \\\"favorite\\n combinations\\\" and have them available for future time entry.  \\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:32'),(3313,'Feature',1122,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Clock Times Duration Display\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1122\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Display the duration of hours for a set of clock times or Start\\n and Stop Times.  This allows the user to see a running total of hours\\n for each set of times or punches.  This is also important when rounding\\n rules are used to round punches or durations between punches which\\n are being entered online or imported from time clocks.\\n\\\n  \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tPunch Duration\\n\\\n  \\t8:00  am\\tSTART    \\t10:00  am\\tSTOP\\t\\t2 hours\\n\\\n  \\t10:00  am\\tSTART    \\t1:00   pm\\tSTOP\\t\\t3 hours\\n \\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3314,'Feature',1123,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Filtering Data\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1123\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Allow for the use of the Query By Example Bar at the top of the\\n timecard matrix, configured in the Time Entry Page Composer, as not\\n all users will find this helpful in their time entry process.  This\\n may be more helpful to Project Portfolio Management users who are\\n searching for specific Project time entries.  There will be an icon\\n on the Timecard Matrix toolbar to hide or show the QBE bar.  The\\n bar will be hidden by default.   When data is filtered in the timecard\\n matrix, there are other interactions that need to be accounted for\\n on the timecard such as :\\n\\\n  1.\\tRow and column totals - Row and column totals would be changed\\n with filtered data, as the user is no longer seeing all time stored\\n on the timecard.   To lessen confusion to the user of having to adjust\\n the totals to \\\"filtered totals\\\", it would be better to hide the column,\\n row and Timecard Totals when filters are in use.\\n\\\n  2.\\tLine Numbers with Error Message Display Dialog (Show Messages)\\n - If the Error Message Dialog is open when the QBE field is used,\\n the dialog should close.  The line numbers will change based on the\\n rows brought back from the QBE filtering.  The change in line numbers\\n need to be reflected if the user opens the Error Message Dialog while\\n QBE is enabled.\\n\\\n  3.\\tLine Numbers with Approval Comments Dialog (View Approval Comments)\\n - If the Approval Comments Dialog is open when the QBE field is used,\\n the dialog should close.  The line numbers will change based on the\\n rows brought back from the QBE filtering.  The change in line numbers\\n need to be reflected if the user opens the Approval Comments Dialog\\n while QBE is enabled.\\n\\\n  4.\\tShow Time Entry Summary - Since this dialog shows totals for the\\n timecard, this dialog should be disabled if the QBE filters are in\\n effect, as the timecard totals would not be valid.\\n\\\n  5.\\tAdd Line - If the user decides to add a line when the data has\\n been filtered and not all rows are showing, the row should be displayed\\n without filters next to the row it was added to.  This will alter\\n the line numbers for the timecard matrix, to allow for the insertion\\n of the row.\\n\\\n  6.\\tDelete Line - If the user decides to delete a line when the data\\n has been filtered, the line numbers will be altered to account for\\n the removed line.\\n\\\n  7.\\tApply Template - The timecard action of \\\"Apply Template\\\" should\\n be inactivated when data is filtered, as not all rows will be visible\\n for the user to decide whether to \\\"replace\\\" or \\\"add\\\" to the existing\\n timecard data. A business message should be displayed to the user\\n that this action cannot be processed with filtered data.\\n\\\n  8.\\tSave as Template -   The timecard action of \\\"Save as Template\\\"\\n should be inactivated when data is filtered, as not all rows are\\n visible for the saving of timecard data as a template.  A business\\n message should be displayed to the user that this action cannot be\\n processed with filtered data.\\n\\\n  9.\\tImport Time - The timecard action of \\\"Import Time\\\" should be inactivated\\n when data is filtered, as not all rows are visible for the additional\\n import of time.  A business message should be displayed to the user\\n that this action cannot be processed with filtered data.\\n\\\n  10.\\tDuplicate Line - If the user decides to duplicate a line, the\\n line number will follow the line that is duplicated.  \\n\\\n  11.\\tClear Hours - The user can still use the timecard action of \\\"clear\\n hours\\\" for any rows that are displayed, during filtering of rows\\n\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3315,'Feature',1124,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Evaluation of Setup Profile Options\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1124\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide ability to work in conjunction with Time and Labor Setup\\n Profiles (formerly Preferences) assigned to the worker for timecard\\n display and functions. (See Appendix B for listing of R12 default\\n Preferences).  These setup options will be effective dated, causing\\n possible changes in the timecard over a time period.  This includes\\n the display of fields, timecard sections, timecard process flow,\\n application of rules, timecard access privileges and available templates.\\n\\n\\\n  If there are changes over a timecard period, due to a worker\'s eligibility\\n changes, the following behaviors would occur for the timecard display:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Time Audit Rule Set - We will evaluate this option day by day\\n of the timecard.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Time Calculation Rule Set - We will evaluate this option day\\n by day of the timecard.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Time Entry Rule Set - We will evaluate this option day by day\\n of the timecard.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Time Interaction Rule Set - We will evaluate this option day\\n by day of the timecard.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Time Consumer Set - We will evaluate this option day by day\\n of the timecard.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Public Template Set - We will display the superset of public\\n templates available for the worker during the timecard period\\n\\n\\\n  o     Layout Set - When a layout set change in the profile for a timecard\\n period, we will split the timecard period and use the layout set\\n relevant to the timecard period.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Period - When a timecard period changes for the worker,\\n we will split the timecard period into the valid period instances\\n before and after the effective date of the change.  When the worker\\n navigates to the timecard, he will only have the days displayed which\\n are valid for that timecard.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Attribute choice lists values change over timecard period- \\n we will show the superset of values for the period and employ validations\\n to ensure the values are valid for the reported days.\\n\\n\\\n  Reference:  http://hcmwiki.us.oracle.com:8880/display/HCM/setupOptions+-+List\\n\\\n  +of+Setup+Options</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3316,'Feature',1125,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Access for Terminated Workers\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1125\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>There will be different processing rules which users have with\\n regards to viewing and updating timecards for terminated employees.\\n  In most cases, workers cannot view, update, create or delete any\\n timecards as of their last day of employment.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  For timekeepers, managers or administrators who need to do further\\n processing of timecards for terminated employees, they may have different\\n dates up to which they can do any processing on terminated worker\'s\\n timecards.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Feedback from payroll localization teams note that administrators\\n (and sometimes his/her managers) should have timecard access up to\\n Final Closing Date. Administrator access should be cut off once the\\n final payment to the employee has been done but it should be dependent\\n on internal regulations of employer, the final payment may be done\\n even during 1 year after termination.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Core Pay will support the following three dates for the termination\\n of a Payroll Relationship, Work Term or Assignment:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Last Standard Earning Date (LSED) - the date on which standard\\n earnings are no longer accumulated. Typically in terminations the\\n Actual Termination Date entered by HR. After the LSED, users can\\n still pay someone a recurring element up to LSPD. \\n\\n\\\n  o     Last Standard Process Date (LSPD) - The last date on which the\\n object (Payroll Relationship, Term, Assignment) is consider for normal\\n processing in the Payroll Run. This date is defaulted from the LSED\\n mentioned above but it can be overridden.  After the LSPD, users\\n can only pay someone that has a non-recurring element. \\n\\n\\\n  o     Final Close Date (FCD) - The date from which the object is no\\n longer considered for processing, thus is datetrack ended.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Currently in Projects (PPM) setup, there is a profile option which\\n is \\\"Specify Number of Days to Display People with Terminated Assignments\\\"\\n which controls the display of people in various  PPM pages.\\n\\n \\n\\\n  However, there is open discussion if Projects would want to use a\\n final processing date which is available in Core HR. \\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  The ability to offer flexible setup options for different access needs\\n is an open design issue being discussed with the Payroll and Projects\\n (PPM) team.    This is an open design issue for setup in the Worker\\n Core Processing Setup Profile</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3317,'Feature',1126,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Options\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1126\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> Provide ability to work in conjunction with worker\'s Timecard\\n Options, a portlet displayed on the worker\'s Timecards Workarea landing\\n page, which include number of blank timecard rows to be displayed\\n in the timecard and default template to pre-populate the timecard.\\n   Prior to Fusion these were Preferences defined in EBS Time and\\n Labor R12.\\n\\n\\\n  Blank timecard rows retained while saving timecard (OTL R12.1 Enhancement\\n HRMS-OTL-21) -This allows timecard users to retain timecard row(s)\\n without any hour values when saving the timecard.  Such rows are\\n available when you want to update the saved timecard at later point\\n of time.  Design concern raised on submission of timecard, retaining\\n extra blank rows could add up and impact performance online and also\\n not see the use of maintaining blank rows and sending for approval. \\n\\n\\\n  Default Template - If a default timecard template is defined by an\\n administrator or worker, this timecard template will automatically\\n populate a new timecard as it is opened.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3318,'Feature',1127,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Approval Flow\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1127\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide ability to trigger Approval flows upon timecard submission\\n via the AMX approvals engine.  The flow  triggered will be based\\n on the approval transaction type associated to the timecard, based\\n on the worker\'s time  consumer set.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3319,'Feature',1128,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Entry Rules\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1128\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> Provide ability to incorporate the triggering of Time Entry\\n Rules upon save or submission of the timecard.  These rules will\\n trigger validations, which errors need to be corrected before the\\n timecard can be submitted for approval.\\n\\n\\\n  Seeded Time Entry Rules to include such rules as : Overlapping Time\\n Entries Rule. This rule checks for clock times which overlap each\\n other.  All Seeded Rules will be noted in Rules FDD.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3320,'Feature',1129,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Interaction Rules\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1129\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide ability to incorporate the triggering of Time Interaction\\n Rules upon opening timecard.  These rules will allow for different\\n page displays, different messages, graying of columns, etc.  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3321,'Feature',1130,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Calculation Rules\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1130\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> Provide ability to incorporate the triggering of Time Calculation\\n Rules upon save or submission of the timecard, which will produce\\n rule results.  These results are the conversion of raw time into\\n processed time which will be sent for approval and ultimately transferred\\n to a receiving application such as Payroll or Project Portfolio Management.\\n\\n        All Seeded Rules will be noted in Rules FDD.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3322,'Feature',1131,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Audit Rules\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1131\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> Provide ability to incorporate the triggering of Time Audit\\n Rules upon save or submission of the timecard, if Time          and\\n Labor Setup Profile Options defined the association of a Change and\\n Late Audit Layout Set to the worker.  This             will trigger\\n the user to enter reason codes and comments for changed time or late\\n time entries.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Late Rule - will trigger display of Time Audit Entry page, if\\n there are any time entries identified as being late\\n\\n\\\n  o     Change Rule - will trigger display of Time Audit Entry page,\\n if there are any time entries identified as being changed</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3323,'Feature',1132,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Rule Results\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1132\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide ability to summarize time by Hours Type when applying\\n Time Calculation Rules on the Timecard Review page.   There should\\n be flexibility to place this section in different pages, as long\\n as there is a call to the Time Calculation rules.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3324,'Feature',1133,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Import Time\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1133\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide services to import time into the timecard from clocks\\n or other external time collection integrations.  This includes the\\n ability to import time from an excel spreadsheet, with ability to\\n use templates and downloaded choicelist values on the excel spreadsheet\\n for detached time entry.  See sections 2.3.6 and 2.3.7 for further\\n details on import of time using ADFdi.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3325,'Feature',1134,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Workflow Notifications\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1134\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre> There are various notifications which revolve around the reporting\\n of time.  Below are some of the notifications.  Additional notifications\\n are noted in Item #20 in Section 2.3.1.1. Should Have Functionality\\n for the Worker Timecard.  These notifications would be triggered\\n by different events of the timecard and would trigger workflow tasks.\\n  The output of the workflow notifications could be email notifications,\\n worklist items or both.  Worklist items would display in the main\\n Worklist on the general Welcome tab as well as the on the Timecards\\n Workarea overview page for Time and Labor.  The configuration of\\n which notification types occurs would be in the workflow setup.\\n\\n\\\n  Currently in EBS R12, there is a notification to the manager or employee\\n if a timekeeper has made changes to a timecard or has entered late\\n time.  This notification relates to users who are using the Change\\n and Late Audit functionality for tracking changes to time or late\\n time entries.  There is configuration in Time and Labor to determine\\n which role gets the notification and if the worklist item is actionable\\n or just for their information.\\n\\n\\\n  In Fusion, the determination of who gets the notifications should\\n be handled in the AMX or workflow setup, assuming that roles are\\n supported for routing rules. \\n\\n\\\n  Another option for worklist or email notifications are alerts.  One\\n method for online alerts, are the use of  Watchlist items, which\\n are summaries of items which require attention.  The resulting displays\\n for Watchlists are saved searches.  Watchlist items will be explored\\n further in the Time and Labor Dashboard FDD.\\n\\n\\\n  1.     RequireApproval Notifications - Deliver worklist notifications\\n for timecards requiring approval via AMX Approvals Engine to approvers.\\n  Approvers of timecards (who may be managers) would need to be notified\\n of any timecards requiring their approval. \\n\\n\\\n  2.     Rejected Timecards Notifications -   Deliver worklist notifications\\n for timecards which have been rejected in the approval process via\\n the AMX Approvals Engine to those who need to resolve or correct\\n the rejected timecards, such as workers or timekeepers. \\n\\n\\\n  3.     Time change Notifications - Provide an option to trigger email\\n notifications when a timecard is modified.  This notification should\\n only be triggered on a submit of  a timecard, not on Save.  Options\\n would include notification to worker, to timekeeper or manager. \\n The notification would need to communicate to the recipient if the\\n timecard was modified, including  the fields of  \\\"Last Modified By\\\"\\n and \\\"Date of Action\\\".  Development would need to seed a worklist\\n notification to display for a modified timecard.  Would be beneficial\\n if it can be defined what changes had occurred in the timecard. \\n If this is not possible, there should be a link to the timecard to\\n view the modified timecard.\\n\\n\\\n  4.     Timecard for Resolution Notification - Provide a worklist notification\\n to the timekeeper or administrator of timecards which need error\\n resolution which a worker cannot resolve.  This is normally due to\\n setup object changes which are needed such as rules.  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3326,'Feature',1135,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Retain entry order of time entries\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1135\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide ability to save all time entries in the same order as\\n they were entered.  This is critical for the individual timecard\\n and for group time entry.  If the user wants to see the data in a\\n different order, he should be able to highlight the column to sort\\n by that column and have all data in the table resort according to\\n that column (ascending or descending order).</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3327,'Feature',1136,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Freezing columns by Administrator\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1136\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide ability to configure the freezing of the timecard matrix\\n at a certain column by the administrator in the Time Entry Page Composer.\\n  If set by the administrator in the Time Entry Page Composer, each\\n employee does not need to individually set the correct column to\\n be frozen.  The freezing of the columns should persist for each user\\n session. \\n\\n\\\n  This is in addition to the standard Freeze action in the View menu\\n for tables, as a standard feature in ADF tables.   Also, want to\\n ensure that the top row (column headers)  of the timecard matrix\\n will always be frozen for vertical display of timecard.  The freezing\\n of the columns would behave as noted in Requirement #20, the user\\n will highlight the column he wants to freeze on, and selects the\\n Freeze action from the toolbar or menu action.  All columns to the\\n right of that frozen column can be scrolled across horizontally,\\n while the columns to the left  of the frozen column will remain static.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3328,'Feature',1137,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Payroll and Project Adjustments to Reported Time (raw time)\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1137\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>There is a need to adjust time in timecards after they have been\\n submitted for approval and routed to Payroll or Projects for processing.\\n  There are many reasons why adjustments to the timecard are needed.\\n  It can be that the original time was entered incorrectly, either\\n because time was entered in advance and the actual hours changed\\n or because the hours were booked to the wrong project/tasks or wrong\\n departments.  Additionally, time may have been entered as paid leave\\n to which the employee was not entitled, and the time has to be rebooked\\n as unpaid leave. \\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Payroll Managers may need to go back and ensure adjustments are made\\n to time, in order for time to be paid correctly in payroll.  Project\\n Managers or Project Accountants may need to go back and make changes\\n to time, to rebook hours to different combinations of Projects and\\n Tasks or change work time to sick or vacation time, or visa versa.\\n  These adjustments are required for proper billing to customers and\\n correct updates to project plans.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  In order for Payroll Managers, Project Managers and Project Accountants\\n to make the adjustments to time, the best approach is for them to\\n have access to change time at the source, reported time in the Timecard\\n Entry page.  For that reason, based on role assignment of \\\"timekeeper\\\",\\n they can be given access to our Group Time Entry feature to make\\n these adjustments.  The access to the workers who require adjustments\\n can be derived from defined group criteria.  The display of the needed\\n fields will be determined via delivered Layout sets with Payroll\\n and Projects.    See Group Time Entry FDD for more details on access\\n to employees via Groups and time entry functionality by worker or\\n batch views, as well as mass time entry updates.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  As the flow of these time adjustments may have a hard deadline because\\n of a payroll to be processed or a billing cycle which needs to be\\n closed in Projects, expedited processing is needed.  An attribute\\n could be stored within the timecard to be populated when an adjustment\\n is occurring (upon submit of the adjusted timecard).  If this attribute\\n is populated, then as the timecard enters the AMX Approval flow,\\n this attribute can trigger an auto-approval rule which automatically\\n approves the timecard.  At that point, the timecard will be immediately\\n available for the transfer services to deposit it into the interface\\n tables for immediate retrieval by Payroll and Projects.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3329,'Feature',1138,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Adjustments to Processed Time\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1138\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Processed Time is the net result of time calculation rules being\\n applied to raw time in a timecard.  Normally, processed time should\\n only be updated by the running of these rules in an online or batch\\n process. \\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  There is the situation in which the rule results in processed time\\n were not what was expected.  If the user (timekeeper or administrator)\\n does not have adequate time to change the rules setup , or using\\n override rules on the timecard would not resolve the time correctly,\\n then the user should be able to make adjustments to the actual processed\\n time.  The security for the duty of updating processed time should\\n be very controlled as this is not a normal method of processing time.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  The timekeeper or administrator who is granted access to adjust calculated\\n time, would  be given access to our Group Time Entry feature to make\\n these adjustments.  The access to the workers who require adjustments\\n can be derived from defined group criteria.  The individual timecard\\n view will display a section for Processed Time results.  Based on\\n security and layout set, the administrator will be able to have edit\\n access to this section.  Once the administrator makes his changes\\n and saves or submits the timecard, there will be a message associated\\n with the Process Time Section that \\\"Processed Time has been adjusted\\\".\\n  See Group Time Entry FDD for more details on access to employees\\n via Groups and time entry functionality by worker or batch views,\\n as well as mass time entry updates.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  As with adjustments to raw time, there may be a hard deadline because\\n of a payroll to be processed or a billing cycle which needs to be\\n closed in Projects.  This should invoke the  expedited processing\\n  for the adjusted timecard.  If this is necessary, the administrator\\n can select timecards which are required to be \\\"forced transfer\\\" to\\n time consumers by a separate \\\"forced transfer\\\" action.   The timecards\\n will still be routed through the normal approval flow in AMX, but\\n will be immediately available to be retrieved by time consumers once\\n they are marked as \\\"Forced Transfer\\\".\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  In the future, if there need to be any updates to the raw time of\\n the timecard, we should allow the updates to occur.  After the timecard\\n is submitted, a workflow notification \\\"Review changes to adjusted\\n timecard\\\" should be triggered and sent to the administrator.  This\\n notification will contain the adjustments made to the processed time\\n on the last version of the timecard.  The administrator will need\\n to determine if he needs to reapply adjustments to processed time\\n to the timecard.  Once he is complete, he will submit the timecard,\\n and the timecard will be routed via the AMX approval flow.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  The adjustments to processed time need to be tracked from an audit\\n perspective, just as changed to raw time would.  We need to know\\n the person, role, date/time and updates made to the timecard.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  The complete flow of dealing with adjustments to raw or processed\\n time will be covered in a new FDD, Time and Labor Validations and\\n Adjustments FDD.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3330,'Feature',1139,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Validating Time \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1139\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Validations of time will be applied as the user moves through\\n the timecard process, specific to validations delivered by Payroll\\n or Project sections.  The set of validations and related error messages\\n will be delivered by Payroll and Project Development teams and will\\n be called as services upon either action of the timecard. \\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  We need the ability to validate raw time (originally entered time)\\n or processed time (time processed as a result of time calculation\\n rules).  Validations on raw time is validating what the user actually\\n enters on their timecard entry page.  The validations on processed\\n time is validating the results of applying time calculation rules.\\n The validations on processed time is new for Fusion.   The reason\\n for validating processed time is that is what the time consumers,\\n Payroll and Projects (PPM) will receive and validate as they receive\\n it. Validating the time at the point of entry will save time later\\n from having transfer errors because the timecard could not be accepted\\n by the time consumer. \\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Errors which are generated from validations will be displayed to the\\n user in an error message listing pop-up on the Timecard Entry page.\\n  If the worker or timecard user cannot resolve the errors from processed\\n time validations , due to the fact that setup objects need to be\\n adjusted in some way, the timecard flow needs to continue.  The proper\\n processing of the timecards when validations fail will be covered\\n in depth in a new Time and Labor Validations and Adjustments FDD\\n .\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Please see Adjust and Validations Timecard Flows visio document for\\n reference</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3331,'Feature',1140,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Period Navigation Options\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1140\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>There will be different options to choose for the user to  change\\n time periods on the timecard.  The following are the two preferred\\n options from customer validation  sessions and competitive research.\\n        a.   Local Area Option \\n\\n\\\n  Calendar pop up widget\\n\\\n  To select a different time period from the local area calendar widget:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Click on Calendar widget displayed after the timecard period,\\n select a date and time period is refreshed on page to the period\\n which intersects with that date.  To be determined in technical design\\n if the period exceeds a week, whether the user will be taken to the\\n beginning of the timecard period or to the week which intersects\\n the date.   Also,  will need to determine if a new tab is opened\\n when a new timecard period is selected, or refresh the existing timecard\\n with the new timeperiod, warning the user that their changes need\\n to be saved before navigating away from the timecard period.\\n\\\n  b.    Contextual Area Option\\n\\n\\\n  Open Calendar Navigation\\n\\\n  The idea is to always have an opened calendar display for the user,\\n to highlight the current timecard period which is currently displayed,\\n and be allowed to select the next or previous timecard period by\\n clicking on any date in the calendar month displayed.  Once the new\\n date is clicked on, the related timecard period will be highlighted\\n and the local display of that timecard period would be refreshed\\n to reflect those dates. \\n\\n\\\n  Additionally, if the user is currently in one timecard period and\\n clicks on the calendar widget to open another timecard period, then\\n both timecard periods can be opened in different dynamic tabs.  This\\n is helpful if the user wants to compare entries from one timecard\\n to another.\\n\\n\\\n  Ideally, this display would appear in the Regional section of the\\n timecard, as other navigational tools appear.  Currently, there are\\n constraints on needing it to appear in the Contextual section of\\n the page due to navigational flows and ability to control the calendar\\n display by application specific code. \\n\\n\\\n  Design Note:  This use of the Calendar widget requires enhancements\\n from ADF on this component to support the highlighting of a time\\n period based on a selected date.  Also noted that it would be nice\\n to see the timecard period date range displayed in the calendar widget\\n header based on the period highlighted.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3332,'Feature',1141,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard IntraPeriod Navigation Options\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1141\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Allowing for intraperiod navigation provides for timecards whose\\n length in days might be longer than a week,   to  provide the user\\n an easy way to navigate from week to week.  At this point we are\\n not offering a switcher for less than a  week. \\n\\n\\\n  Prior to Fusion, the timecard user would have a horizontal scroll\\n to navigate through the timecard  days.  The  following are two options\\n the user can choose from in the Time Entry Page Composer. \\n\\n\\\n  The display of a timecard period will always start with the start\\n date of the timecard instance.\\n\\n\\\n  A.  Weekly Selector\\n\\n\\\n  Allows for a user to easily navigate from one week to another for\\n timecard periods which exceed one week.  This option  would allow\\n the user to not have to scroll horizontally through weeks, but be\\n able to click an arrow to the next week or  prior week within the\\n timecard.  This would be most beneficial for bi-weekly timecard users.\\n\\n\\\n  For semi-monthly or monthly timecard periods, there may be days not\\n applicable at the end of the week which are not part of the current\\n period, which would be grayed out. There would be a week selector\\n above the timecard matrix for the user to navigate back and forth\\n between the weeks within the timecard period.  The day/date columns\\n would just change in the user\'s view.  The other attributes would\\n remain in display, as if the columns were frozen before the day/date\\n fields.  The column and row totals would need to reflect only the\\n totals of the days displayed to the user.  As a result, the attributes\\n from one week would display on the other weeks, since only the days\\n are being scrolled to the right.\\n\\\n  Open Design Issue:  An issue with this design is the error messaging\\n reference to the correct location of the error.  If the user is accessing\\n the error message listing pop-up (listed above in Must Have Section\\n 2.3.1), and clicks on the error message, the cursor should take the\\n user to where the error exists in the timecard matrix.  With the\\n intra-period navigation, not all entries are visible at once, so\\n this functionality would not work.  A recommendation from UX is that\\n when the user is accessing errors from the error message listing\\n pop-up the intra-period navigation is hidden and the user will get\\n the normal horizontal scroll through the days.\\n\\n\\\n  B.  Horizontal Scroll with Column Grouping by Week\\n\\n\\\n  This design is an alternate design option to allow for horizontal\\n scroll through the timecard period.  Both options will be available\\n in the timecard layout set creation. The attributes would not scroll,\\n only the days of the week.  As the user clicked on a hyperlink for\\n Week 1, Week 2, etc, the matrix would advance to that week, by displaying\\n the first day of the week within the view of days.  There would not\\n need to be an \\\"overflow\\\" icon, as we would not exceed the display\\n of 4 weeks in a timecard.\\n\\\n  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3333,'Feature',1142,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Period Security Access\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:06 Z\npriority: \nid: 1142\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide ability to restrict access to timecards for prior or\\n future time, by timecard actions, for workers, managers or timekeepers.\\n  This control will be offered in the Worker and Group Time Entry\\n Time and Labor Setup Profiles, in the Timecard Actions table setup. \\n\\n\\\n  The idea is that for each timecard action (create, edit, delete, view)\\n there will be the ability to define for which timecard statuses the\\n user could take this action.  In addition, there would be the ability\\n to define how many days in the future or past that these actions\\n can take place.  This is an enhancement to design on \\\"status allowing\\n edits\\\" preferences in EBS Time and Labor R12.\\n\\n\\\n  If the user is not allowed to take the following Timecard Actions,\\n the following are the expected results:\\n\\n\\\n  Delete Timecard - will disable the Delete icon in the Recent Timecards\\n table in Timecards Work Area and in Manage Timecards search results\\n page\\n\\n\\\n  Edit Timecard - the timecard period link will be disabled in the Recent\\n Timecards table in Timecards Work Area and in Manage Timecards search\\n results page.  There will also be a hover over the disabled hyperlink\\n to explain to the user, \\\"You do not have edit access to this timecard\\n based on current timecard status\\\".\\n\\n\\\n  View Timecard - if the user cannot view a timecard for a selected\\n timecard period , the view timecard icon will be disabled in the\\n Recent Timecards table in Timecards Work Area and in Manage Timecards\\n search results page.  There will also be a hover over the disabled\\n hyperlink to explain to the user, \\\"You do not have view access to\\n this timecard based on current timecard status\\\".\\n\\n\\\n  If the user is currently in a timecard and navigates to another timecard\\n , the expected results are:\\n\\n\\\n  a.  User can view but not edit the timecard for that period - will\\n be taken to a view-only version of the timecard\\n\\n\\\n  b.  User cannot view or edit the timecard for that period - will be\\n issued a business message that they do not have access to the selected\\n timecard based on current timecard status. If the user does not have\\n view or edit access to that timecard,  that timecard should not be\\n included in any listing of timecards or timecard counts in related\\n analytics.   Additionally, the calendar widget which allows navigation\\n to another timecard period will not enable a timecard period to which\\n the user is not allowed any access (view and edit mode).</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3334,'Feature',1143,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Summary\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1143\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Display a configurable Time Summary section as a collapsible\\n section below the timecard matrix.   There would be two views for\\n this summary, table and pie chart view., with the user being able\\n to toggle between the two. This section would allow the user to see\\n summaries of time specific to the attributes that are important to\\n them, such as per project or task.\\n\\n\\\n  Overall Requirements\\n\\n\\\n  o     Table and alternate pie chart views\\n\\n\\\n  o     Ability to summarize hours by one or more time attributes\\n\\n\\\n  o     Ability to configure the summarization labels for the choice\\n list options\\n\\n\\\n  o     Ability to use abstract or physical attributes to summarize time:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Abstract = Example would be \\\"Worked\\\" and \\\"Non-Worked Time\\\" -\\n in which different hours types would add to each type of time\\n\\n\\\n  o     Physical Attributes = Example would be actual attributes which\\n appear on the timecard such as Project, Task, Hours Type\\n\\n\\\n  o     Ability to show a \\\"View By\\\" field which offers a choice list\\n  for the user to select different options to summarize the time entries\\n by, defined in the Time Entry Page Composer.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Ability for total hours not to equal timecard total hours (as\\n the way time is summarized, it may not equal all worked time)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Display message if Time Summary Hours do not equal Timecard Totals\\n\\n\\\n  o     Define a \\\"default\\\" summarization for the Choice List Options\\n\\n\\\n  o     Pie Chart Slices Hover Over - can define the \\\"number of hours\\\"\\n that make up that pie slice, if pie slices are broken down by percentage\\n\\n\\\n  The time summarizations could be comprised of just one time attribute,\\n or a combination of time attributes.  The attributes which are selected\\n for the time category need to be \\\"summarizable\\\" and will be defined\\n as such in the layout set definition.  For example, a comments field\\n would not be included in a time summary section.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  This would also save the user from having to navigate to the timecard\\n review page to see Time Summary.  There should be a Refresh Icon\\n on Timecard Summary toolbar, to update totals by Time Summarization,\\n as the totals cannot dynamically be updated as time is entered, as\\n the time category totals need to be derived from their definitions.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  The default format for the summary would be in a pie chart format,\\n with a hover over of number of hours for each pie section in lieu\\n of percentages.\\n\\\n  An alternate view for the summary would be in a table, to show how\\n the time is broken down by the main attribute, such as by Project.\\n\\\n  Examples of time summarization:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Regular Time and Premium Time\\n\\n\\\n  o     Project, Task, Expenditure Type\\n\\n\\\n  o     Billable and Non-Billable Hours\\n\\n\\\n  o     Total Hours/ Work Hours/ Absence Hours\\n\\n\\\n  o     Worked Time/ Non-Worked Time\\n\\n\\\n  o     Customer\\n\\n\\\n  o     Work Order</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3335,'Feature',1144,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Email notifications\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1144\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>These are additional email notifications which would be triggered\\n in relation to timecards:\\n\\n\\\n  a.     Deleted Timecards - Allow an email notification to be triggered\\n to the manager via workflow if a timecard has been deleted by the\\n worker.\\n\\n\\\n  b.     Timecard Submission Due Date Reminder - to remind the worker\\n that a timecard is coming due for submission.  This notification\\n is dependent on the existence of a timecard submission due date and\\n time defined for the worker.  Configuration would be required for\\n the user to determine when the reminders need to go out before the\\n due date, such as the day before due date, or 2 hours before due\\n date/time.  The user may want to setup multiple times for the notification\\n to be transmitted.\\n\\n\\\n  c.     Attestation Notification - If time or changes to time have\\n been submitted on behalf of a worker, some companies require the\\n worker to attest to the fact that the time he sees in the timecard\\n was what he had worked.  The attestation process allows the worker\\n to agree or disagree with the time in his timecard.  There would\\n be a notification to the worker to agree or disagree with the time\\n entered on his behalf.  The response from the worker would then need\\n to be routed to a payroll manager or person responsible for monitoring\\n the attestations.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3336,'Feature',1145,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Audit Trail on Time Cards Report\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1145\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>This report provides the complete history of timecards from its\\n timecard submission to approval stages.  The report displays details\\n such as the number of times a particular timecard is submitted, modified,\\n or deleted, and various actions done by various employees, approvers\\n on a particular timecard.  Reference: (OTL_TC_Changes_Audit_Report_FDD_66752\\n\\\n  98_12.1.doc)\\n design document for the design.\\n\\n\\\n  An alternate design option is to display an audit trail at the bottom\\n of each timecard, listing the user, role, action taken and action\\n date .  However, this type of audit cannot account for the deletion\\n of timecards.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3337,'Feature',1146,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Audit Log\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1146\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Allow for an ongoing audit display at the footer of the timecard\\n in a collapsible section, to record each time the timecard has been\\n modified.  This would record all possible timecard actions, except\\n deletion which will need to be recorded via an audit report.  The\\n other attributes to be recorded would include:\\n\\n\\\n  o     User - the ID or name of the person making the change\\n\\n\\\n  o     Action - actions which have occurred on the timecard such as:\\n timecard modified, timecard created, timecard approved\\n\\n\\\n  o     Date Timestamp - actual date and time of the timecard action\\n as it was saved or submitted\\n\\n\\\n  o     Role - job role of the user who took action on the timecard\\n\\n\\\n  This Audit log feature expands on the enhancement made in EBS OTL\\n R12.1 - Display last person who updated timesheet (HRMS-OTL-31) \\n  This enhancement enabled the user to view the person who last updated\\n the time details on the timecard. As a timecard can undergo many\\n changes after an employee creates it, providing this information\\n on the timecard enables you to identify the person who last made\\n changes to the timecard.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3338,'Feature',1147,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Transfer of partial timecard to other applications\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1147\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Allow for option to transfer timecards differently for different\\n worker groups.  For example, if one day is in error for a whole timecard\\n period, user would want days which are correct to be transferred\\n for exempt employees, but for biweekly staff they might want to hold\\n all time in an errored timecard, since there are dependent rules\\n that would execute.  This would be a change in the approval rules,\\n in which only a portion of the timecard would be approved related\\n to the non-errored time, whereas the errored time would not yet be\\n approved.  Therefore a partially approved timecard would be transferred\\n to one or more applications.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3339,'Feature',1148,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Warning messages display to managers\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1148\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>If timecards have been processed by workers or timekeepers, allow\\n for the warning messages to be stored so the managers can see the\\n warning messages associated to the timecards, to determine time entry\\n issues.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3340,'Feature',1149,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Summarize Approval Comments by Time Attribute\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1149\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Allow for the administrator to summarize approval comments by\\n time attributes of the timecard.  There may be many rows of entries\\n which are rejected and it would be easier to categorize the rejection\\n comments for the error message summary.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3341,'Feature',1150,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Summarize Approval Comments by Assignment\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1150\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide ability to see approval comments by worker\'s different\\n assignments related to the timecard.  This could be done if the approval\\n rules are able to differentiate by assignments and the approval rule\\n output could then be split accordingly. The comments need to be summarized\\n by assignment.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3342,'Feature',1151,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Calendar Time Entry\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1151\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Provide ability to report time via the use of a calendar.  The\\n calendar can be used to display reported hours, scheduled hours,\\n calculated hours (results from time calculation rules), as well as\\n a method to report time. The calendar could be color-coded to show\\n the different types of time or the user could change the display\\n type by a choice list. A user could report time in a variety of ways:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Click on a day, a pop-up page is display, enter hours and time\\n attributes and upon close of the pop-up, the time will be saved for\\n the day\\n\\n\\\n  o     Highlight a range of dates in the calendar, and enter number\\n of hours and time attributes which should be associated to each day\\n in that highlighted range, via a pop up page.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3343,'Feature',1152,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Embedded Timecard in other Applications\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1152\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Allow for the timecard to be embedded as a portlet in other applications\\n such as the Project Team Member page in Project Portfolio Management,\\n or other application dashboards which require time entry.  The related\\n application validations will need to be associated to the portlet,\\n as well as services to store the timecard updates and run relevant\\n time-related rules.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3344,'Feature',1153,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Worker Navigation Options\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1153\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>A worker may be accessing his information from different navigations,\\n depending on his other tasks he is performing.  The following would\\n be some navigational options for the worker:\\n\\n\\\n  v     Person Portrait:  Navigating from Welcome Tab: Person Gallery->Person\\n Portrait:Actions:Report Time:Time Entry page for current timecard\\n period\\n\\n\\\n  v     Timecard Work Area: Navigating from My Information:Time:Timecards\\n Work Area; Create or View Timecards options\\n\\n\\\n  v     Worker Dashboard (post v1):  Timecard Portlet: Enter My Timecard:Pop-up\\n page of quick time entry\\n\\n\\\n  v     Project Portfolio Management Team Member Dashboard or Payroll\\n Dashboard could also be options for embedding the timecard for access</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:33'),(3345,'Feature',1154,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Individual Timecard: RequiredFunctionality for Line Manager\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1154\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>The following are the requirements for the manager\'s use of timecards:\\n\\n\\\n  1.     All requirements covered in the Individual Timecard: Worker\\n  for Must Have , Should Have and Nice to Have\\n\\n\\\n  2.     Provide ability to easily report time or view time for manager\'s\\n direct reports\\n\\n\\\n  3.     Person navigation- Use of Mini My Organization in Regional\\n Area of timecard page for manager to select other workers.\\n\\n\\\n  4.     Allow manager to access his own timecard in the listing of\\n timecards from his Manage Timecards navigation, to avoid navigating\\n to a different task for reporting time for his own timecard\\n\\n\\\n  5.     Easy to find navigation for managers to report time, such as\\n from Manager Dashboard Actions, My Organization and Employee\'s Portrait,\\n as well as the Timecard Work Area\\n\\n\\\n  6.     Allowance for additional fields for manager entry which their\\n workers\' may not have security access to view</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3346,'Feature',1155,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Individual Timecard: Should Have Functionality for Line Manager\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1155\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>Messaging Rules for Flexible Page Header - Use Message Rules\\n to generate output at the top of the timecard to indicate someone\\n other than the worker is reporting time for him/her.  This allows\\n for the use of the same time entry page for all users - timekeeper,\\n manager or worker.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3347,'Feature',1156,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Individual Timecard: Line Manager Navigation Options\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1156\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>A manager may be accessing his information from different navigations,\\n depending on his other tasks he is performing.  The following would\\n be some navigational options for the manager:\\n\\n\\\n  1.     Person Portrait:  Navigating from Welcome Tab: Person Gallery->Person\\n Portrait:Actions:Report Time:Time Entry page for current timecard\\n period\\n\\n\\\n  2.     Portait Gallery - >Organization Chart:Actions.-->Report Time:Timecard\\n Entry page for default timecard period\\n\\n\\\n  3.     Timecard Work Area: Navigating from Manager Resources:Time\\n Management:Timecards Work Area; Create or View Timecards options\\n\\n\\\n  4.     Manager Dashboard: Manager Resources:My Organization:Actions:Report\\n Time:Time Entry page for current timecard period</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3348,'Feature',1157,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Individual Timecard Search: For Worker\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1157\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>This page facilitates Time and Labor self service users searching\\n for timecards.\\n\\n\\\n  In R12 there was a separate navigation link for Timecard Search and\\n another link to Time Entry, which displayed a Recent Timecard search.\\n\\n\\\n  In Fusion, there will just be one search navigation which will bring\\n the user to the Manage Timecards page. In the Regional pane, there\\n will be a \\\"Search: Timecards\\\" pane which will be the Basic Search\\n for timecards.  The fields for searching for the worker will be timecard\\n period or From and To Date. \\n\\n\\\n  The Manage Timecards page will also offer the basic and advanced search\\n functionality for a user to narrow their search to date ranges, etc.\\n  Additionally, there will be two views of the timecards search results:\\n table and Gantt chart view.   The default table view can show all\\n timecards for the worker, with the most recent timecard periods sorted\\n to the top of the table.  All columns in the search results should\\n be sortable and allow the user to retain a different sort order if\\n he chooses.  As the user enters fields for search, the search results\\n will be replaced with the relevant results.  There should be a refresh\\n default option to bring back the default view of the timecard results.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Advanced Search:\\n\\n\\\n  Allows the user the ability to string multiple lines of search attributes\\n together with \\\"and\\\" and \\\"or\\\" statements, using the following search\\n fields and operators, with the ability to configure additional search\\n fields based on added timecard fields, which are made available in\\n layout sets.\\n\\n\\\n  Fields:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Detail Comment\\n\\n\\\n  o     Reported Hours\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Period\\n\\n\\\n  o     Project\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Status\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Submission Date\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Due Date (new for Fusion)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Task\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Comment\\n\\n\\\n  Operators for Search\\n\\n\\\n  o     Less Than\\n\\n\\\n  o     Less Than or Equal to\\n\\n\\\n  o     Not Equal To\\n\\n\\\n  o     Equal To\\n\\n\\\n  o     Greater Than\\n\\n\\\n  o     Greater Than or Equal To\\n\\n\\\n  o     Like\\n\\n\\\n  o     Not Like\\n\\n\\\n  o     Basic Search\\n\\n\\\n  o     From Date\\n\\n\\\n  o     To Date\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Period\\n\\n\\\n  o     Create Timecard button -  when clicking on this action, a calendar\\n widget will pop up for the worker to select a date, which will select\\n the timecard period which intersects with that date,   then be taken\\n to the Create Timecard page for that worker.\\n\\n\\\n  Columns in Search Results Table\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Period - display of the start and end date of the timecard\\n period, with a hyperlink to allow editable access to this timecard.\\n  If the user does not have edit access to the timecard, the link\\n will be disabled, with a hover over message to alert the user \\\"You\\n do not have edit access to this timecard.\\\"\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Status - status of the timecard (working, saved, submitted,\\n approved, rejected, in error, etc)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Approval Flow Data - icon displayed if the timecard has entered\\n the approval workflow process, the user can click on the icon and\\n see a display of where the timecard is in the approval process by\\n which approvers have acted on the timecard and which approvers remain.\\n  This section will be using existing AMX UI display for showing approval\\n status/history.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Recorded Hours - a total of all hours reported on the timecard.\\n  The display would be in hours and minutes, as there are no rounding\\n rules in effect.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Submission Date - the date the timecard has been submitted for\\n approval\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Due Date - (new for Fusion)  would be nice to show\\n the due date of the timecard, especially if it is not submitted as\\n of yet\\n\\n\\\n  o     Audit Data - this column will display an icon if the timecard\\n contains change and late audit data (reason codes for why time was\\n changed or was entered late)\\n\\n\\\n  o     View Summary- this column will display an icon to allow the\\n user to view the timecard (will display the \\\"View Timecard\\\" layout\\n page per the associated layout set.  This is a read only version\\n of the timecard which is similar to the Timecard Review page, containing\\n time entry detail, rule results, time summary information, change\\n and late audit summary information,  and audit details.  Additionally,\\n there will be a print function from this page,\\n\\n\\\n  o     Delete - this column will display an \\\"X\\\" to the user to allow\\n delete of the timecard if the user has access to perform this function,\\n based on his Time and Labor Setup Profile options.  If the user attempts\\n to delete a timecard, a warning message will be issued to ask \\\"Delete\\n selected timecard\\\"?\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Toolbar and Menu Options for Search Results Table\\n\\n\\\n  o     Create Timecard action - transfers user to a new timecard  (also\\n a button on toolbar\\n\\n\\\n  o     View Menu - to allow hiding of columns were are optional such\\n as:  Audit Data, Recorded Hours, Submission Date, Approval Chain\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enable QBE - so user can filter on any column in the search\\n results table\\n\\n\\\n  Fusion additional functionality\\n\\n\\\n  o     Saved Searches - a user will have the ability to save his basic\\n and/or advanced searches for future use.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Approval Flow Data - (New for Fusion)  have a column related\\n to the approval flow data of the timecard, with further drill down\\n detail as to where the timecard is in the approval chain\\n\\n\\\n  o     Transfer To -   (New for Fusion)  ability to see to which time\\n consumers the timecard has been transferred, as a column in the Search\\n Results - Transferred to Payroll, Project Portfolio Management, both,\\n etc.  This is enhancement in 12.1.1. Release to be brought into Fusion. \\n\\n\\\n  o     Calendar View\\n\\n\\\n  There will be a view of timecards for the user to view and access\\n his timecards from a calendar display.  There will be three months\\n displayed at a time, with the ability to scroll to the next three\\n or prior three months. Each timecard period will be highlighted on\\n the calendar, and the user just needs to click on any date in that\\n timecard period, and will be transferred to that timecard.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3349,'Feature',1158,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worker Timecards Display: Timecards Portlet\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1158\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>This page allows the worker to view his timecards in timecard\\n period descending order, with the most recent timecards listed on\\n top of the table.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Add filter with options    Show: Timecards in Progress; All Timecards\\n\\n\\\n  o     For  \\\"Timecards in Progress\\\" - let the worker select the timecard\\n statuses they want to see for this filtered view in a drop down list\\n of multi-select checkboxes\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Status options:  Draft, Submitted, In Error, Pending\\n Resolution, Rejected, Approved\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enable QBE for the table, for sorting on any column, with ability\\n to default back to the delivered view\\n\\n\\\n  o     Show Table View or Calendar View\\n\\n\\\n  o     Add View Menu, so user can hide any optional columns in table:\\n Audit Data, Recorded Hours, Submission Date, Approval Chain\\n\\n\\\n  Columns Displayed:\\n\\n\\\n  v     Timecard Period - display of the start and end date of the timecard\\n period, with a hyperlink to allow editable access to this timecard.\\n  If the user does not have edit access to the timecard, the link\\n will be disabled, with a hover over message to alert the user \\\"You\\n do not have edit access to this timecard.\\\"\\n\\n\\\n  v     Timecard Status - status of the timecard (working, saved, submitted,\\n approved, rejected, in error, etc)\\n\\n\\\n  v     Approval Chain - icon displayed if the timecard has entered\\n the approval workflow process, the user can click on the icon and\\n see a display of where the timecard is in the approval process by\\n which approvers have acted on the timecard and which approvers remain.\\n  This section will be using existing AMX UI display for showing approval\\n status/history.\\n\\n\\\n  v     Recorded Hours - a total of all hours reported on the timecard.\\n  The display would be in hours and minutes, as there are no rounding\\n rules in effect.\\n\\n\\\n  v     Submission Date - the date the timecard has been submitted for\\n approval\\n\\n\\\n  v     Timecard Due Date - (new for Fusion)  would be nice to show\\n the due date of the timecard, especially if it is not submitted as\\n of yet\\n\\n\\\n  v     Audit Data - this column will display an icon if the timecard\\n contains change and late audit data (reason codes for why time was\\n changed or was entered late)\\n\\n\\\n  v     View Summary- this column will display an icon to allow the\\n user to view the timecard (will display the \\\"View Timecard\\\" layout\\n page per the associated layout set.  This is a read only version\\n of the timecard which is similar to the Timecard Review page, containing\\n time entry detail, rule results, time summary information, change\\n and late audit summary information,  and audit details.  Additionally,\\n there will be a print function from this page,\\n\\n\\\n  v     Delete - this column will display an \\\"X\\\" to the user to allow\\n delete of the timecard if the user has access to perform this function,\\n based on his Time and Labor Setup Profile options.  If the user attempts\\n to delete a timecard, a warning message will be issued to ask \\\"Delete\\n selected timecard\\\"?\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Table Actions\\n\\n\\\n  v     Create Timecard-  when clicking on this action, a calendar widget\\n will pop up for the worker to select a date, which will select the\\n timecard period which intersects with that date,   then be taken\\n to the Create Timecard page for that worker.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Calendar View\\n\\n\\\n  There will be a view of timecards for the user to view and access\\n his timecards from a calendar display.  There will be three months\\n displayed at a time, with the ability to scroll to the next three\\n or prior three months. Each timecard period will be highlighted on\\n the calendar, and the user just needs to click on any date in that\\n timecard period, and will be transferred to that timecard.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3350,'Feature',1159,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Manager Timecard Summary Display: Timecards in Progress Portlet\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1159\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>This portlet allows the manager  to view his workers\' timecards\\n in timecard period descending order.\\n\\n\\\n  Filter\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecards in Progress-add this as a filter, with a multi-checkbox\\n selection, for the user to define what timecard statuses make up\\n \\\"in progress\\\"        \\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Status options:  Draft, Submitted, In Error, Pending\\n Resolution, Rejected, Approved\\n\\n\\\n  Columns Displayed:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Period - display of the start and end date of the timecard\\n period\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Status - status of the timecard (working, saved, submitted,\\n approved, rejected, in error, etc)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Approval Chain - icon displayed if the timecard has entered\\n the approval workflow process, the user can click on the icon and\\n see a display of where the timecard is in the approval process by\\n which approvers have acted on the timecard and which approvers remain.\\n  This section will be using existing AMX UI display for showing approval\\n status/history.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Reported Hours - a total of all hours reported on the timecard.\\n  The display would be in hours and minutes, as there are no rounding\\n rules in effect.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Submission Date - the date the timecard has been submitted for\\n approval\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Due Date - (new for Fusion)  would be nice to show\\n the due date of the timecard, especially if it is not submitted as\\n of yet\\n\\n\\\n  o     Audit Data - this column will display an icon if the timecard\\n contains change and late audit data (reason codes for why time was\\n changed or was entered late)\\n\\n\\\n  o     View Timecard - this column will display an icon to allow the\\n user to view the timecard (will display the \\\"View Timecard\\\" layout\\n page per the associated layout set.  This is a read only version\\n of the timecard which is similar to the Timecard Review page, containing\\n time entry detail, rule results, time summary information, change\\n and late audit summary information,  and audit details.  Additionally,\\n there will be a print function from this page,\\n\\n\\\n  o     Delete - this column will display an \\\"X\\\" to the user to allow\\n delete of the timecard if the user has access to perform this function,\\n based on his Time and Labor Setup Profile options.\\n\\n\\\n  Toolbar and Menu Options for Table\\n\\n\\\n  o     Create Timecard action - manager must select a worker (choice\\n list of available direct reports in the table)  and then select a\\n date from a calendar widget, to create for the correct timecard period,\\n then be taken to the Create Timecard page for that worker.\\n\\n\\\n  o     View Menu - to allow hiding of columns were are optional such\\n as:  Audit Data, Recorded Hours, Submission Date, Approval Chain\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enable QBE - so user can filter on any column in the search\\n results table\\n\\n\\\n  o     Gantt Chart View (open issue) - this component needs a lot of\\n space, and should be on its own tab\\n\\n\\\n  o     Gantt View - when use search results on page, just show the\\n people that match the search results, but show all timecards When\\n doing a search, if there are multiple timecards which match the search\\n criteria, change the time focus display by zooming in or zooming\\n out to show the right view (by 3 months, month, week) to show the\\n timecards that match the search.  Do not gray out the timecards which\\n do not match the search criteria\\n\\n\\\n  o     \\n\\n\\\n  (New for Fusion)  Alternate Gantt chart display - As in the Manage\\n Timecards search results table, this table listing will also allow\\n for an alternate view of the timecard search results in a Gantt chart\\n display.  This display would allow the user to scroll through time\\n to find timecards for any of his workers.  There would be additional\\n detail about each timecard as the manager clicks on the timecard\\n cell.  There would also be a color coded legend to define what timecard\\n status each timecard block represents.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3351,'Feature',1160,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Adoption of 3 Tier Levels of Fusion Employment Model\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1160\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>To provide the ability to report time at any of the 3 levels\\n of employment: Work Relationship, Employment terms or Assignments,\\n we need to provide these as components for the users to choose to\\n select for display on their timecard layouts.  Even if the user decides\\n to not to report to the assignment level, it is critical to know\\n that we will always store the reported time in the primary assignment\\n level.\\n\\n\\\n  In our retrieval processes with existing applications such as Project\\n Portfolio Management and Payroll, we need to provide the levels of\\n time reporting that the customer needs, so we need to derive the\\n highest to lowest level of detail when transferring the time data.\\n\\n\\\n  In our timecard validation processes, we also need to validate to\\n the correct employment levels as well, depending on what has been\\n allowed for in the application validation rules.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3352,'Feature',1161,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Import and Entry Excel Import Template\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1161\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>An end user can record time entry items in an ADFdi-enabled Excel\\n spreadsheet and upload them into the application when they are connected\\n to it.  The spreadsheet must be MS Excel 2007 Standard Edition license.\\n\\n\\\n  The spreadsheet is a complementary \\\"Excel UI\\\" for users to track time\\n entry items.  Users can accomplish this by entering data into the\\n ADFdi-enabled spreadsheet and uploading that data (via ADFdi\'s feature\\n set) to the Time and Labor application.  Invalid data or system errors\\n are highlighted to the end user for edit and re-upload.\\n\\n\\\n  In order to access this spreadsheet, there should be an ADFdi enabled\\n spreadsheet invoked from the Private Templates, \\\"Download Template\\\".\\n  The user must be connected to the application in order to export\\n (download) it.  By being in the connected mode upon export, the contents\\n of the smart choice lists for the time attributes in the template,\\n along with values for the dependent fields and descriptive flexfields\\n should be downloaded as well.  As the contents of the choice lists\\n can change from timecard period to timecard period, the user should\\n select for which timecard period they want to export the template.\\n  As they invoke the Download Template action, there should then be\\n a calendar widget pop-up which has the user \\\"Select Timecard Period\\\"\\n for the download.  Once the timecard period is selected, the download\\n of the template and its related choice list values should begin and\\n open into an excel spreadsheet.\\n\\n\\\n  After the ADFdi-enabled spreadsheet has been exported, data can be\\n manually entered or copied/pasted into the spreadsheet.   Time entry\\n items can be added to a new timecard or to a saved, existing timecard.\\n  All timecard entries that are uploaded are updated with a status,\\n \\\"Row inserted successfully\\\".\\n\\n\\\n  For the design of the spreadsheet, it is to be determined if it is\\n a single editable table for entry of time, or a master-detail form\\n or if there are multiple tabs for the detail for the time entries\\n as well.  The spreadsheet will need to account for multiple smart\\n choice lists for time attributes, which may also include descriptive\\n flexfields.\\n\\n\\\n  The fields to be imported should include:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Person Name/ Person Number\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Period\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard Comments\\n\\n\\\n  o     Day of the Week\\n\\n\\\n  o     Date\\n\\n\\\n  o     Hours Type\\n\\n\\\n  o     Time Attribute Values, Daily Details and Daily Comments associated\\n to worker\'s layout set\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  When the user is ready to import their offline time entries back to\\n the system, they should be connected to the system and click on \\n \\\"Upload\\\" in the ADFdi spreadsheet, to upload the timecard entry data\\n for that timecard period into the system.\\n\\n\\\n  ADFdi Workbook Actions Menu\\n\\n\\\n  The Actions that will appear in the Actions menu consist of:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Login - Logs user into Fusion application.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Logout - Logs user out of Fusion application.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Clear All Data - clears data from spreadsheet\\n\\n\\\n  o     About - Information to assist in diagnosing environmental issues\\n (i.e. version number of the spreadsheet)\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Upload Options Pop-Up\\n\\n\\\n  o     Upload to an Existing Timecard\\n\\n\\\n  o     Upload to a New Timecard\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Additional Attributes (context dependent segments based on Flexfields)\\n\\n\\\n  Additional Information window\\n\\n\\\n  This window would provide for flexfield segments which are dependent\\n on the entry of other fields.  They may include text fields, choice\\n lists..  Information entered in this window is accepted by clicking\\n the \\\"OK\\\" button and dismissed by clicking the \\\"Cancel\\\" button.  Each\\n field is validated based on the validation type. This window is only\\n accessible when the user is connected to the network application.\\n\\n\\\n  1.  Reference Design Guidelines:  Desktop Integration: ADFdi MS Excel\\n 2007\\n\\n\\\n  http://fusiongps.us.oracle.com/guidelines/content/guidelines/adfdi/index.htm\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  2.  Example: Expenses Excel Import Template\\n\\n\\\n  http://files.oraclecorp.com/content/AllPublic/SharedFolders/Fusion%20Delivera\\n\\\n  bles-Public/Fin/Expenses/UI%20Design/FIN_EXM_ADFdi_PT.xls\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  3.  Expenses Import FDD\\n\\n\\\n  http://files.oraclecorp.com/content/AllPublic/SharedFolders/Fusion%20Delivera\\n\\\n  bles-Public/Fin/Expenses/Functional%20Design/FIN_EXM_ADFdi_FDD.doc\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  4.  Reference:  Financials Management: Desktop Integration Project:\\n\\n\\\n  https://kix.oraclecorp.com/KIX/display.php?labelId=1995&articleId=55807</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3353,'Feature',1162,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Timecard Options for Worker\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1162\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>This portlet on the Timecard Workarea landing page for the employee\\n replaces the Self Service Preferences page in EBS R12.  The benefit\\n for placing these options on the workarea landing page is that the\\n user can easily find them as they access their timecards.\\n\\n\\\n  The portlet facilitates the worker being able to change their time\\n entry preferences to suit their own requirements, e.g. the number\\n of empty rows shown on the timecard entry page and what their default\\n private template should be, if they are using private templates.\\n  The number of empty rows will display on a new timecard and also\\n when a timecard has been saved, that many rows will be displayed\\n at the bottom of the table.  The default template will always prepopulate\\n the timecard with data as the worker accesses a new timecard.  The\\n UI for this portlet will be represented in the Workarea section of\\n the Analytics FDD.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3354,'Feature',1163,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Manage Templates\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1163\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>This page facilitates Time and Labor workers managing their own\\n pre-populated timecard templates which can be applied for future\\n timecard entry use.  They can search, create, view or delete or export\\n templates from the search/search results page.\\n        These are the search fields for finding a private template:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Basic/Advanced Search page for Repeating Time Periods which\\n contain the following fields:\\n\\n\\\n  Basic Search\\n\\n\\\n  o     Name - User name for private template\\n\\n\\\n  Advanced Search\\n\\n\\\n  o     Name - User name for private template\\n\\n\\\n  o     Status - Inactive or Active\\n\\n\\\n  o     Operator - this field is coupled with both the Name field, to\\n allow more flexibility to search\\n\\n\\\n  The options for the operator values are: \\n\\n\\\n  o     Greater than\\n\\n\\\n  o     Equals\\n\\n\\\n  o     Does Not Equal\\n\\n\\\n  o     Less Than\\n\\n\\\n  o     Greater Than\\n\\n\\\n  o     Between\\n\\n\\\n  o     Not Between\\n\\n\\\n  o     Is Blank\\n\\n\\\n  o     Is Not Blank\\n\\n\\\n  Also allow for wildcard search in each field.\\n\\\n  Search Results Section\\n\\n\\\n  o     Search Results Grid : displays the user created private templates,\\n and also provides actions which can be applied to private templates.\\n  The columns listed in the search results are the following:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Name - User name for private template\\n\\n\\\n  o     Status - Inactive or Active\\n\\n\\\n  o     Total Hours- Total number of hours for created template\\n\\n\\\n  There will not be seeded private templates, since these are specific\\n to the user..\\n\\\n  Actions for Manage Templates\\n\\n\\\n  o     Create Template\\n\\n\\\n  When using the \\\"create\\\" action or \\\"create\\\" button from the Search\\n Results grid, a user will be able to create a new private template\\n\\n\\\n  o     Edit Template\\n\\n\\\n  When user selects the \\\"edit\\\" action or \\\"edit\\\" button from the Search\\n Results grid, a user will be able to edit an existing private template.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Delete Template\\n\\n\\\n  When user selects the \\\"delete\\\" action or \\\"delete\\\" button from the\\n Search Results grid, a user will be able to delete an existing private\\n template.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Download Template\\n\\n\\\n  When user selects the \\\"Download Template\\\" menu action or \\\"Download\\n template\\\" toolbar button from the Search Results grid, a user will\\n be able to export the template and related choice list values to\\n an excel spreadsheet via ADFdi integration.  See Section 2.3.7 for\\n more information on the ADFdi flow to support disconnected or offline\\n entry mode.  </pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3355,'Feature',1164,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Private Template Page\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1164\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 117\ndescription: \"<pre>This page facilitates Time and Labor workers pre-populating new\\n or existing timecards with sets of commonly used timecard entries. \\n\\n\\\n  The template contains the timecard matrix information, derived from\\n the worker\'s currently assigned layout set and timecard period associated\\n to their Worker Web Time Entry Setup Profile.   The worker is also\\n able to name the template and populate the timecard matrix for reuse\\n in other timecards.\\n\\n\\\n  There are four delivered repeating period types: daily, weekly, semi-monthly\\n and monthly which can be used as timecard periods.  We will support\\n daily, weekly and biweekly timecard periods for a worker to enter\\n both hours (times) and time attribute values.  If the worker is creating\\n a private template for a semi-monthly or monthly timecard period,\\n the template will just show attributes as editable with no display\\n of days , with a business message displayed  upon creation that \\\"Only\\n attribute values can be defined for this timecard period type.\\\"\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  A. Create Template page\\n\\n\\\n  The following are the fields to be displayed when creating a new private\\n template:\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Section: Template Detail\\n\\n\\\n  o     Template Name: user defined name for the private template\\n\\n\\\n  o     Status:  Active/Inactive  \\n\\n\\\n  A worker can inactivate a private template if it is no longer usable\\n for their current layout or timecard period.  The default value is\\n active.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Section: Template Entry\\n\\n\\\n  o     Timecard matrix for entering hours/ Start/Stop Times and additional\\n time attribution such as  Hours Type, Work Location, Cost Center.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Days of the week will be displayed without dates for those timecard\\n periods which can have pre-populated hours (daily, weekly, biweekly).\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Page Actions:   Save  - user saves the page and remains on page\\n\\n\\\n  Save and Close - user saves the page and page closes\\n\\n\\\n  Cancel - user cancels out of the page\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  B. Edit Template page\\n\\n\\\n  All template entry fields are editable on the private template as\\n well as the page name.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Page Actions:   Save \\n\\n\\\n  Save and Close\\n\\n\\\n  Cancel</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3356,'FunctionalWorkUnit',117,'destroy','1','--- \nname: Time and Labor Report Time\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:05 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 117\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3357,'Feature',1165,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Rule Template Search\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1165\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 118\ndescription: |-\n  This feature will allow the user to search for any existing rule templates, with a filter of rule type: time entry, time calculation and time audit rule templates.  The user can also perform the search without using the filter.  In addition, the user can create, edit, or delete rule templates from the search results section.\n  \n  Must Have Features:\n  \n  o     Basic/Advanced Search page for Rule Templates which contain the following fields:\n  \n  Basic Search\n  \n  o     Template Type: Time Entry, Time Audit, Time Calculation\n  \n  o     Name: Template Name\n  \n  Advanced Search\n  \n  o     Description: Template Description\n  \n  o     Tag: User Defined name for easy search\n  \n  o     Fast Formula\n  \n  o     Search Results Grid\n  \n  o     Template Type\n  \n  o      Name\n  \n  o     Description\n  \n  o     Tag\n  \n  Note:  The search results should initially default to the last 10 rule templates created.  Seeded time entry rule templates will also be listed.\n  \n  o     Available Create Menu Actions on Search Results Menu\n  \n  o     Create Time Entry Rule Template\n  \n  o     Create Time Audit Rule Template\n  \n  o     Create Time Calculation Rule Template\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3358,'Feature',1166,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Enable Configurable Sort options for Timecard Entries prior to application of (TER, TCR, TAR, TIR (future)) Rules \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1166\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 118\ndescription: |-\n  The Rule set for each type of rule (TER, TCR, TAR, etc) must allow for a sort option, where OTL Development delivers the standard sort option used in EBS R12.  The Sort Option will reference a choice list where customer defined functions may be registered, and displayed for selection.  The sort options will then affect the execution of rules, since specific entries processed first may result in different end values.\n  \n  OTL Development will also deliver information on how to define new sort options and how to register them.\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3359,'Feature',1167,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: OTL Rules are consistent across the OTL Application\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1167\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 118\ndescription: OTL will deliver rules of different types (TER, TCR, TAR, and TIR) that are defined and assigned in a similar manner.  The Rule engine may or may not be the same (based on Development design) but should appear the same functionally.\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3360,'Feature',1168,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Allow for overrides of Calculated Rule Results\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1168\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 118\ndescription: \"OTL Development will allow for Layouts defined with an editable rule result section to be assigned to timekeepers to manually adjust calculated results.  The Timecard containing adjusted results should be \\xE2\\x80\\x98identifiable\\xE2\\x80\\x99 so that a message may be shown explain how the results were arrived at. \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3361,'Feature',1169,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Entry Rule Template\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1169\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 118\ndescription: \"This feature denotes an online association of an HR Fast Formula to a Time and Labor defined time entry rule template id, which will derive inputs and outputs from the associated formula.  This association is done via the use of an OTL Formula Flexfield, in which the context will be the same as the new time entry rule template.  The segments for this flexfield will relate to the rule template input variables or tokens. The generation of this flexfield will occur on the save of the rule template.\\n\\n\\\n  Must Have Features:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Create Time Entry Rule Template:     From the Rule Template Search Results page, a user can create a new rule template using the Create Time Entry Rule Template from Actions menu.  There will be a train design pattern, to assist the user in defining the following 5 steps of creating and reviewing the rule template:\\n\\n\\\n  1     Rule Template Definition \\xE2\\x80\\x93 selection of Fast Formula, entering the rule template name, description and tag.  Once the Fast Formula is selected, the detail of the formula will be displayed in a read-only format for reference in a long text field.  There should be an option to navigate to the Fast Formula page to create another formula if one is not found that is needed.\\n\\n\\\n  Note:  Must have a \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cfast formula type\\xE2\\x80\\x9D for time entry, time audit and time calculation rules, to make it easier for the user to have a filtered view of fast formulas for selection.  This must be done in conjunction with the Payroll team.\\n\\n\\\n  2     Inputs \\xE2\\x80\\x93 this page will derive the inputs from the Fast Formula selected, and allow the user to enter user defined labels for these \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cparameters\\xE2\\x80\\x9D and assign value sets for these parameters, to be selected from on the rule page.\\n\\n\\\n  3     Outputs \\xE2\\x80\\x93 this page will allow the user to define the outputs of the fast formula and assign a user defined name for the rule result and identify the rule result type, such as message and / or rule status (status being Error, Warning, Business Message).\\n\\n\\\n  4     Rule Explanation \\xE2\\x80\\x93 this page will allow the user to describe the business purpose of the rule template, with placeholders for the input and output values to be displayed in the actual rule, when the user selects the actual values.\\n\\n\\\n  5     Review- this page will be a read-only display of all prior pages, with a section to represent each prior page. This is to assist the user to determine if they have created the rule template as needed.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Update Time Entry Rule Template:  From the Rule Template Search Results page, a user can select and edit a rule template using the Actions menu or Edit button.  There will be a train design pattern, to assist the user in defining the following 5 steps of editing and reviewing the rule template:\\n\\n\\\n  1     Rule Template Definition \\xE2\\x80\\x93 selection of Fast Formula, entering the rule template name, description and tag.  Once the Fast Formula is selected, the detail of the formula will be displayed in a read-only format for reference in a long text field. \\n\\n\\\n  2     Inputs \\xE2\\x80\\x93 this page will derive the inputs from the Fast Formula selected, and allow the user to enter user defined labels for these \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cparameters\\xE2\\x80\\x9D and assign value sets for these parameters, to be selected from on the rule page.\\n\\n\\\n  3     Outputs \\xE2\\x80\\x93 this page will allow the user to define the outputs of the fast formula and assign a user defined name for the rule result and identify the rule result type, such as message or rule status.\\n\\n\\\n  4     Rule Explanation \\xE2\\x80\\x93 this page will allow the user to describe the business purpose of the rule template, with placeholders for the input and output values to be displayed in the actual rule, when the user selects the actual values.\\n\\n\\\n  5     Review- this page will be a read-only display of  all prior pages, with a section to represent\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Delete Time Entry Rule Template: action to be taken from the Rule Template Search Results page to delete a rule template. The template should not be able to be deleted if it is in use, i.e. being associated to a rule.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Application for Multiple Assignments-  A Time Entry Rule Template can be applied against one or more worker assignments, depending on how the fast formula associated to the Time Entry Rule Template was created.  Within the Fast Formula, the user has the ability to specifically define if the formula is to be defined against the \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cwhole person\\xE2\\x80\\x9D or against individual assignments.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Must Have:  See Section 21.6 for Seeded Time Entry Rule Templates (Fast Formulas for TERs) that must be delivered\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3362,'Feature',1170,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Audit Rule Template\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1170\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 118\ndescription: \"This feature denotes an online association of an HR Fast Formula to a Time and Labor defined time audit rule template id, which will derive inputs from the associated formula.  This association is done via the use of an OTL Formula Flexfield, in which the context will be the same as the new time audit rule template.  The segments for this flexfield will relate to the rule template input variables or tokens. The generation of this flexfield will occur on the save of the rule template.\\n\\n\\\n  Must Have Features:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Create Time Audit Rule Template:     From the Rule Template Search Results page, a user can create a new rule template using the Create Time Audit Rule Template from Actions menu.  There will be a train design pattern, to assist the user in defining the following 4 steps of creating and reviewing the rule template\\n\\n\\\n  1.     Rule Template Definition \\xE2\\x80\\x93 selection of Fast Formula, entering the rule template name, description and tag.  Once the Fast Formula is selected, the detail of the formula will be displayed in a read-only format for reference in a long text field. \\n\\n\\\n  2.     Inputs \\xE2\\x80\\x93 this page will derive the inputs from the Fast Formula selected, and allow the user to enter user defined labels for these \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cparameters\\xE2\\x80\\x9D and assign value sets for these parameters, to be selected from on the rule page.\\n\\n\\\n  3.     Outputs \\xE2\\x80\\x93 this page will be blank as of Fusion v1, with an informational message that no outputs are being derived from the fast formula.  The tab is being displayed for consistency across all template types.\\n\\n\\\n  4.     Rule Explanation \\xE2\\x80\\x93 this page will allow the user to describe the business purpose of the rule template, with placeholders for the input values to be displayed in the actual rule, when the user selects the actual values.\\n\\n\\\n  5.     Review- this page will be a read-only display of all prior pages, with a section to represent each prior page. This is to assist the user to determine if they have created the rule template as needed.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Update Time Audit Rule Template:  From the Search Results page, a user can select and edit a rule template using the Actions menu or Edit button.  There will be a train design pattern, to assist the user in defining the following 4 steps of editing and reviewing the rule template:\\n\\n\\\n  1     Rule Template Definition \\xE2\\x80\\x93 selection of Fast Formula, entering the rule template name, description and tag.  Once the Fast Formula is selected, the detail of the formula will be displayed in a read-only format for reference in a long text field. \\n\\n\\\n  2     Inputs \\xE2\\x80\\x93 this page will derive the inputs from the Fast Formula selected, and allow the user to enter user defined labels for these \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cparameters\\xE2\\x80\\x9D and assign value sets for these parameters, to be selected from on the rule page.\\n\\n\\\n  3     Outputs \\xE2\\x80\\x93 this page will be blank as of Fusion v1, with an informational message that no outputs are being derived from the fast formula.  The tab is being displayed for consistency across all template types.\\n\\n\\\n  4     Rule Explanation \\xE2\\x80\\x93 this page will allow the user to describe the business purpose of the rule template, with placeholders for the input and output values to be displayed in the actual rule, when the user selects the actual values.\\n\\n\\\n  5     Review- this page will be a read-only display of all prior pages, with a section to represent each prior page. This is to assist the user to determine if they have created the rule template as needed.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Delete Time Entry Rule Template: action to be taken from the Rule Template Search Results page to delete a rule template. The template should not be able to be deleted if it is in use, i.e. being associated to a rule.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Application for Multiple Assignments-  A Time Audit Rule Template can be applied against one or more worker assignments, depending on how the fast formula associated to the Time Audit Rule Template was created.  Within the Fast Formula, the user has the ability to specifically define if the formula is to be defined against the \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cwhole person\\xE2\\x80\\x9D or against individual assignments.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Must Have:  See Section 21.6 for Seeded Time Audit Rule Templates (Fast Formulas for CLAs) that must be delivered\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34');
INSERT INTO `versions` VALUES (3363,'Feature',1171,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Rule Search\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1171\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 118\ndescription: \"This feature will allow the user to search for any existing rules, with a filter of rule type: time entry, time calculation and time audit rules.  The user can also perform the search without using the filter.  In addition, the user can create, edit, duplicate or delete rules from the search results section.\\n\\n\\\n  Must Have Features:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Basic/Advanced Search page for Rules which contain the following fields:\\n\\n\\\n  Basic Search\\n\\n\\\n  o     Rule Type: Time Entry, Time Audit, Time Calculation\\n\\n\\\n  o     Name: Rule Name\\n\\n\\\n  o     Effective As Of:  Date as of when the Rule is effective\\n\\n\\\n  Advanced Search\\n\\n\\\n  o     Description: Rule Description\\n\\n\\\n  o     Tag: User Defined name for easy search\\n\\n\\\n  o     Used In:  List of rule sets for which a user can find this rule.  The number of rule sets should be the hyperlinked field that a user can select and get a pop up page of all rule sets which contains this rule.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Search Results Grid\\n\\n\\\n  o     Rule Type\\n\\n\\\n  o      Name\\n\\n\\\n  o     Description\\n\\n\\\n  o     Tag\\n\\n\\\n  o     Effective Start Date\\n\\n\\\n  o     Effective End Date\\n\\n\\\n  o     Used In:  Denote which rule sets this rule is listed in, with a hyperlink on the number of rule sets that the rule is contained in, displaying a pop up list of all Rule Sets.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Actions available from the Search Results grid\\n\\n\\\n  o     Create (Create Time Entry Rule; Create Time Audit Rule; Create Time Calculation Rule)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Edit\\n\\n\\\n  o     Delete\\n\\n\\\n  o     Duplicate\\n\\n\\\n  NOTE \\xE2\\x80\\x93 With Date Effectivity \\xE2\\x80\\x93 Actions are taken within the page, with date selection and restrictions following design patterns\\n\\n\\\n  Note:  The search results should initially default to the last 10 rules created.  Seeded time entry rules will also be listed.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3364,'Feature',1172,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Entry Rules\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1172\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 118\ndescription: \"This feature denotes an online association a pre-defined time entry rule template id, which will derive inputs and outputs from the associated formula.  When a time entry rule template is selected, the associated conditions or parameters for that rule will automatically be populated from the rule template inputs and outputs.\\n\\n\\\n  Must Have Features:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Create Time Entry Rule:     From the Rule Search Results page, a user can create a new time entry rule using the \\xE2\\x80\\x9CCreate Time Entry Rule\\xE2\\x80\\x9D from the Actions menu.  The following will be the steps to take on one page for the time entry rule:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Select a Rule Type\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter a Rule Name\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter a Rule Description\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter Run Event \\xE2\\x80\\x93 the determination of when in the timecard submission process this rule should fire.  The possible value options are \\xE2\\x80\\x9Csave, submission, delete, resubmission, submission/resubmission, submission,/resubmission/ delete\\xE2\\x80\\x9D. \\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter a Tag (optional)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Select a Rule Template\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter an Effective Start Date\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter the Parameter values (conditions) based on the Template display\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter Message Severity\\xE2\\x80\\x93 to define the messages for an outcome of error, warning or informational message.  There may be one or more conditions from the rule template which require the selection of messages. \\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter Run Condition: A run condition is a time category, which will be promoted outside of the rule definition, to provide the ability to offer conditions outside of the fast formula.  This field will control if this rule is executed or not.  The default value will be \\xE2\\x80\\x9CAll the time\\xE2\\x80\\x9D, which means the rule will always be executed. \\n\\n\\\n  NOTE: The Run Condition has been moved to the Rule Set level \\xE2\\x80\\x93 to define or not define additional conditions (when true) when using the rule (gives more flexibility in defining a rule and separating from a possible condition)\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Update Time Entry Rule:  From the Rule Search Results page, a user can edit a rule using the Actions menu or Edit button.  The following will be the actions to take on one page for the time entry rule:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Effective Start or add Effective End Date\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Parameter values (conditions) based on the Template display\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Message Severity \\xE2\\x80\\x93 to define the messages outcome of error, warning or informational message\\n\\n\\\n  o     Rule Template \\xE2\\x80\\x93 the associated rule template should not be changed on an existing rule.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Run Condition \\xE2\\x80\\x93 A run condition is a time category, which will be promoted outside of the rule definition, to provide the ability to offer conditions outside of the fast formula.  This field will control if this rule is executed or not.  The default value will be \\xE2\\x80\\x9CAll the time\\xE2\\x80\\x9D, which means the rule will always be executed.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Run Event - the determination of when in the timecard submission process this rule should fire.  The possible value options are \\xE2\\x80\\x9Csave, submission, delete, resubmission, submission/resubmission, submission,/resubmission/ delete\\xE2\\x80\\x9D. \\n\\n\\\n  o     Duplicate Time Entry Rule: From the Rule Search Results page, a user can duplicate a time entry rule and will be required to rename the new time entry rule.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Delete Time Entry Rule: action to be taken from the Search Results page to delete a rule.  A rule should not be deleted if in use, . i.e. associated to a rule set.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Application for Multiple Assignments-  A Time Entry Rule can be applied against one or more worker assignments, depending on how the fast formula associated to the Time Entry Rule Template was created.  Within the Fast Formula, the user has the ability to specifically define if the formula is to be defined against the \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cwhole person\\xE2\\x80\\x9D or against individual assignments.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Must Have:  See Section 21.6 for Seeded Time Entry Rules  (TERs) that must be delivered.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3365,'Feature',1173,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Execution of Time Entry Rules \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1173\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 118\ndescription: \"Allowing the user to determine if rules should be applied on originally entered time (raw time) or  time that has had rules applied (calculated time) or both types of time.   This option would be most appropriate to offer on time entry rules as a \\xE2\\x80\\x9Ctime type\\xE2\\x80\\x9D option\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3366,'Feature',1174,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Audit Rules\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1174\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 118\ndescription: \"This feature denotes an online association a pre-defined time audit rule template id, which will derive inputs from the associated formula.  When a time audit rule template is selected, the associated conditions or parameters for that rule will automatically be populated from the rule template inputs.  No outputs need to be defined, as the resulting outcome of this rule will be the display of the Audit Information page in the Timecard layout. \\n\\n\\\n  However, in future versions it will be determined if there would be flexibility of allowing the user to define the layout that should be generated in the timecard flow, as a result of the input triggers.\\n\\n\\\n  Must Have Features:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Create Time Audit Rule:     From the Search Results page, a user can create a new rule using the Actions menu or Create button.  The following will be the actions to take on one page for the time audit rule:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Select a Rule Type\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter a Rule Name\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter a Rule Description\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter Rule Usage \\xE2\\x80\\x93 the determination of when in the timecard submission process this rule should fire.  The possible timecard status value options are \\xE2\\x80\\x9Csave, submission, delete, resubmission, submission/resubmission, submission,/resubmission/ delete\\xE2\\x80\\x9D. \\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter a Tag (optional)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Select a Rule Template\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter an Effective Start Date\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter the Parameter values (conditions) based on the Template display\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter the Run Condition \\xE2\\x80\\x93 A run condition is a time category, which will be promoted outside of the rule definition, to provide the ability to offer conditions outside of the fast formula.  This field will control if this rule is executed or not.  The default value will be \\xE2\\x80\\x9CAll the time\\xE2\\x80\\x9D, which means the rule will always be executed.\\n\\n\\\n  NOTE: The Run Condition has been moved to the Rule Set level \\xE2\\x80\\x93 to define or not define additional conditions (when true) when using the rule (gives more flexibility in defining a rule and separating from a possible condition)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter the Run Event - the determination of when in the timecard submission process this rule should fire.  The possible value options are \\xE2\\x80\\x9Csave, submission, delete, resubmission, submission/resubmission, submission,/resubmission/ delete\\xE2\\x80\\x9D. \\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Update Time Audit Rule:  From the Search Results page, a user can edit a rule using the Actions menu or Edit button.  The following will be the possible actions to take on one page for the time audit rule:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Effective Start or End Date\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Rule Description\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Tag (optional)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Parameter values (conditions) based on the Template display\\n\\n\\\n  o     Rule Template \\xE2\\x80\\x93 the associated rule template should not be changed on an existing rule.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Run Condition \\xE2\\x80\\x93 A run condition is a time category, which will be promoted outside of the rule definition, to provide the ability to offer conditions outside of the fast formula.  This field will control if this rule is executed or not.  The default value will be \\xE2\\x80\\x9CAll the time\\xE2\\x80\\x9D, which means the rule will always be executed.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Run Event - the determination of when in the timecard submission process this rule should fire.  The possible value options are \\xE2\\x80\\x9Csave, submission, delete, resubmission, submission/resubmission, submission,/resubmission/ delete\\xE2\\x80\\x9D. \\n\\n\\\n  o     Duplicate Time Audit Rule: From the Rule Search Results page, a user can duplicate a time audit rule and will be required to rename the new time audit rule.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Delete Time Audit Rule: action to be taken from the Search Results page to delete a rule. A rule should not be deleted if in use, i.e. associated to a rule set.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Application for Multiple Assignments-  A Time Audit Rule can be applied against one or more worker assignments, depending on how the fast formula associated to the Time Audit Rule Template was created.  Within the Fast Formula, the user has the ability to specifically define if the formula is to be defined against the \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cwhole person\\xE2\\x80\\x9D or against individual assignments.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Must Have:  See Section 21.6 for Seeded Time Audit Rules  (CLA Rules) that must be delivered\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3367,'Feature',1175,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Rule Set Search\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1175\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 118\ndescription: |-\n  This feature will allow the user to search for any existing rule sets, with a filter of rule type: time entry, time calculation and time audit rules.  The user can also perform the search without using the filter.  In addition, the user can create, edit, duplicate or delete rule sets from the search results section.\n  \n  Must Have Features:\n  \n  o     Basic/Advanced Search page for Rule Sets which contain the following fields:\n  \n  Basic Search\n  \n  o     Rule Set Type: Time Entry, Time Audit, Time Calculation\n  \n  o     Name: Rule Set Name\n  \n  o     Effective As Of:  Date as of when the Rule Set is effective\n  \n  Advanced Search\n  \n  o     Description: Rule Set Description\n  \n  o     Tag: User Defined name for easy search\n  \n  o     Uses Rule: ability to select a rule, and search for rule sets which contain that rule\n  \n  o     Search Results Grid\n  \n  o     Rule Set Type\n  \n  o      Name\n  \n  o     Description\n  \n  o     Tag\n  \n  o     Effective Start Date\n  \n  o     Effective End Date\n  \n  Note:  The search results should initially default to the last 10 rule sets created. \n  \n  o     Actions available from the Search Results grid\n  \n  o     Create (Create Time Entry Rule Set; Create Time Audit Rule Set; Create Time Calculation Rule Set)\n  \n  o     Edit\n  \n  o     Delete\n  \n  o     Duplicate\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3368,'Feature',1176,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Entry Rule Sets\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1176\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 118\ndescription: \"This feature allows a user to assemble multiple time entry rules together in a set, for assignment to users via Time and Labor Setup Options. \\n\\n\\\n  Must Have Features:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Create Time Entry Rule Set:     From the Search Results page, a user can create a new rule set using the Actions menu.  The following will be the actions to take on one page for the time entry rule set:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Select a Rule Set Type\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter a Rule Set Name\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter an Effective Start Date\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter a Rule Set Description\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter a Tag (optional)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter the Time Entry Rules for this set   - once each rule is selected, there will be a view only display of the rule template from which the rule has been created.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter Run Condition (optional)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter Processing Order\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter (update) Date From / Date To\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Update Time Entry Rule Set:  From the Search Results page, a user can edit a rule set using the Actions menu or Edit button.  The following will be the possible actions to take on one page for the time entry rule set:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Effective Start or add an Effective End Date\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Rule Set Description\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Tag\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the rules listed in the rule set\\n\\n\\\n  o     Duplicate Time Entry Rule Set: From the Rule Search Results page, a user can duplicate a time entry rule set and will be required to rename the new time entry rule set.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Delete Time Entry Rule Set: action to be taken from the Search Results page to delete a time entry rule set. A rule set should not be allowed to be deleted if in use, i.e. associated to an employee via Time and Labor Setup Options.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Assignment of Time Entry Rule Sets:  Time Entry Rule Sets will be assigned to a worker via Time and Labor Setup Options (formerly Preferences in EBS R12).  The assignment of these rule sets will be to the primary assignment only, as for the first version of Fusion, Time and Labor Setup Options will only support the assignment of Options to the primary assignment.  Even though the assignment of rules will be at the primary assignment level, if the user has a multiple assignment implementation, the actual application of rules can be done at any level.   Please review the Time Entry Rule Template and Rule Sections for the note on  \\xE2\\x80\\x9CApplication for Multiple Assignments\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3369,'Feature',1177,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Audit Rule Sets\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1177\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 118\ndescription: \"This feature allows a user to assemble multiple time audit rules together in a set, for assignment to users via Time and Labor Setup Options. \\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  Must Have Features:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Create Time Audit Rule Set:     From the Search Results page, a user can create a new rule set using the Actions menu.  The following will be the actions to take on one page for the time audit rule set:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Select a Rule Set Type\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter a Rule Set Name\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter an Effective Start Date\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter a Rule Set Description\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter a Tag (optional)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Enter the Time Audit Rules for this set -- once each rule is selected, there will be a view only display of the rule template from which the rule has been created.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Update Time Audit Rule Set:  From the Search Results page, a user can edit a rule set using the Actions menu or Edit button.  The following will be the possible actions to take on one page for the time audit rule set:\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Effective Start or Effective End Date\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Rule Set Description\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the Tag (optional)\\n\\n\\\n  o     Update the rules listed in the rule set\\n\\n\\\n  o     Duplicate Time Audit Rule Set: From the Rule Search Results page, a user can duplicate a time audit rule set and will be required to rename the new time audit rule set.\\n\\n \\n\\n\\\n  o     Delete Time Audit Rule Set: action to be taken from the Search Results page to delete a time audit rule set. A rule set should not be allowed to be deleted if in use, i.e. associated to an employee via Time and Labor Setup Options.\\n\\n\\\n  o     Assignment of Time Audit Rule Sets:  Time Audit Rule Sets will be assigned to a worker via Time and Labor Setup Options (formerly Preferences in EBS R12).  The assignment of these rule sets will be to the primary assignment only, as for the first version of Fusion, Time and Labor Setup Options will only support the assignment of Options to the primary assignment.  Even though the assignment of rules will be at the primary assignment level, if the user has a multiple assignment implementation, the actual application of rules can be done at any level.   Please review the Time Audit Rule Template and Rule Sections for the note on  \\xE2\\x80\\x9CApplication for Multiple Assignments\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3370,'FunctionalWorkUnit',118,'destroy','1','--- \nname: \"Time and Labor Setup Changes: Time Entry Rules and Rule Sets\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 118\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3371,'Feature',1178,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: No Name\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1178\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 119\ndescription: \"\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3372,'FunctionalWorkUnit',119,'destroy','1','--- \nname: \"Time and Labor Setup Changes: Time Audit Rules and Rule Sets\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 119\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3373,'Feature',1179,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: OTL Rules are consistent across the OTL Application\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1179\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 120\ndescription: \"OTL will deliver rules of different types (TER, TCR, TAR, and TIR) that are defined and assigned in a similar manner.  The Rule engine may or may not be the same (based on Development design) but should appear the same functionally.  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3374,'Feature',1180,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: TCR-Rules Processing Engine\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1180\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 120\ndescription: \"The Time Calculation Rules Processing Engine will be the heart of the TCR module.  It will be capable of interpreting the Time Calculation Rules written as Fast Formulas and apply them to raw Time Entries on a Timecard.  It will write the resulting calculated time entries as a Calculated Timecard to the OTL TimeStore and related it to the raw Entries.\\n\\n\\\n  It will have the ability to \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cunderstand\\xE2\\x80\\x9D time entries (Time Building Blocks and Attributes) and prepare them for the Fast Formula, pass them to the Fast Formula and process the results of those Fast Formulas, turning them back into time entries.  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3375,'Feature',1181,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Processing Time Calculation Rules in Batch Mode\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1181\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 120\ndescription: \"Besides being able to perform TCR Calculations online (during the Timecard Creation flow), we have requirements that request we perform these calculations in batch mode for many timecards.  We should be able to leverage the same code to perform calculations on many timecards in batch mode.  We will provide a Concurrent Program that can be used for this, probably with some parameterization to allow customers to target specific Timecards in the TimeStore.\\n\\n\\\n  This feature will also be used for performing calculations on timecards in the future when changes are made to timecards in the past.  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:34'),(3376,'Feature',1182,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Allow TCR during Time Keeper Entry Mode\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1182\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 120\ndescription: \"In one way, this is closely related to the previous feature.  The Time Keeper module allows Time Keepers to enter time for many employees in a quick heads-down data entry way.  Because this needs to be as quick as possible, most likely they would not want to perform the TCR calculation for every timecard they enter after they enter it because it would slow them down and they would not be interested in/look at the result anyway (its not their timecard).  This is why we need to develop a Batch Mode so that the TCR calculations can be done after timecard entry for all these timecards.\\n\\n\\\n  NOTE \\xE2\\x80\\x93 Batch refers to a group of timecards, so that they may be acted on \\xE2\\x80\\x98en mass\\xE2\\x80\\x99 rather than one by one.\\n\\n\\\n  Furthermore, in some cases, the Time Keeper might be interested in the actual TCR calculation results and would like to see them during or after creating the Timecard.  For these cases, we need to provide a feature that allows them to do just this.  This can be a simple button on the Time Keeper entry form that will start the TCR calculation on-line and shows them the results in a separate window (one timecard with rule results at a time)  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3377,'Feature',1183,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Multiple Assignment Support\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1183\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 120\ndescription: \"As with other requirements, this will be taken into consideration at design time (i.e. TCR will be multiple assignment aware), but no special effort will be put into actually providing features for multiple assignments.  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3378,'Feature',1184,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Retrieval of Calculated Time to any application\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1184\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 120\ndescription: \"The generic retrieval currently only retrieves raw entered time to recipient applications.  Obviously the recipient applications would be interested in retrieving calculated time since they are also the parties requesting rules to calculate time.  This will require OTL to change the Generic Retrieval process.  Change will probably not be require for the recipient applications specific retrieval code as we anticipate the format of time we send not to change (it will just contain calculated time entries instead of raw time entries, but they are indistinguishable from each other).  Note that the SOA uptake might change what we send to recipient applications but that has nothing to do with this feature, at least this feature will most likely not cause such a change.  Obviously if an application does not calculate any time, what gets send to them is the raw time, as we do now.\\n\\n\\\n  Additionally we will simplify the retrieval process of exploded time steps so that calculated time can be retrieved like raw time without additional processes to be run.  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3379,'Feature',1185,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Enable Configurable Rule Processing Order Options for Measure Timecard Entries prior to application of (TER, TCR, TAR, TIR (future)) Rules\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1185\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 120\ndescription: \"The Rule set for each type of rule (TER, TCR, TAR, etc) must allow for a sort option, where OTL Development delivers the standard sort option used in EBS R12.  The Rule Processing Order Option will reference a choice list where customer defined functions may be registered, and displayed for selection.  The sort options will then affect the execution of rules, since specific entries processed first may result in different end values.\\n\\n\\\n  OTL Development will also deliver information on how to define new sort options and how to register them.  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3380,'Feature',1186,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Allow for overrides of Calculated Rule Results \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1186\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 120\ndescription: \"OTL Development will allow for Layouts defined with an editable rule result section to be assigned to timekeepers to manually adjust calculated results.  The Timecard containing adjusted results should be \\xE2\\x80\\x98identifiable\\xE2\\x80\\x99 so that a message may be shown explain how the results were arrived at.\\n\\n\\\n  NOTE: The adjustments to calculation results (with a message to the user / viewer that the results have been manually updated may be the required solution, time permitting.  The assumption is the adjustment to calculated results should not be undertaken lightly.  The raw entries should reflect what took place, while the Process result entries are from the rules.  If  the results are not as expected and an advanced admin (timekeeper) may be given the privilege to change the calculated results prior to fixing the calculations to get the desired results.  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3381,'FunctionalWorkUnit',120,'destroy','1','--- \nname: Time Calculation Rules Engine\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 120\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3382,'Feature',1187,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: No Name\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1187\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 121\ndescription: \"  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3383,'FunctionalWorkUnit',121,'destroy','1','--- \nname: \"Time and Labor Group Time Entry \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 121\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3384,'Feature',1188,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Timecards Work Area: Manager View\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1188\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 122\ndescription: \"\\n        \\tThe Timecards work area is comprised of a complete set \\n                of tasks, reports, business intelligence and searches related to \\n                processing timecards.  The two key components of the workarea \\n                are the landing page (entry page) displayed in the local area, \\n                and available tasks listed in the Task pane, in the regional \\n                section of the page. \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3385,'Feature',1189,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Manager Timecards Work Area : Manager regional area\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1189\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 122\ndescription: \"\\n        <ol>\\n        <dt>Task Pane:  The three tasks for the task pane will be :</dt>\\n        <dd>o\\tCreate Timecard : upon clicking the Create Timecard link, a calendar widget will open, for the user to select a date.  The worker will then be taken to the timecard which intersects that date in a new dynamic tab.  When the worker has submitted that timecard, the dynamic tab will close.</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tManage Timecards : a link to the Manage Timecards page, which has a search and search results section for the worker\'s timecards, with a default listing of the last 5 recent timecards.  Additionally, it will have the actions of create, delete, edit or view a timecard.  See Section 2.3.3.  Manage Timecards in Report Time FDD for more details.</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tManage Templates : this link will navigate the worker to his Manage Templates page, in which he can view, create, edit or delete his private templates.</dd>\\n        <ol>\\n      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3386,'Feature',1190,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Manager Timecards Work Area : My Org table\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1190\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 122\ndescription: \"\\n        \\n        <p>    \\tMini My Organization table : this will be a smaller version of the \\n        table displayed on the Line Manager Dashboard, owned by Core HR.  There will\\n        be a Report Time action on this table.  The manager can select a person and \\n        click on the Report Time Action, a calendar widget will open, for the user\\n        to select a date.  The worker will then be taken to the timecard which \\n        intersects that date in a new dynamic tab.  When the manager has submitted \\n        that timecard, the dynamic tab will close.</p>\\n      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3387,'Feature',1191,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Manager Timecards Work Area : Search Region\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1191\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 122\ndescription: \"\\n        \\t<p>This region will display a basic search for timecards.  The \\n                basic fields will be for Timecard Period  or From and To Date.  \\n                If the search has only one result, it will take the user to that\\n                timecard.  If there are multiple results, it will take the user \\n                to the Manage Timecards search and search results page in a new \\n                dynamic tab.  If the user clicks on the Advanced Search button, \\n                it will take the user to the Manage Timecards search page as well.\\n                </p>\\n      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3388,'Feature',1192,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Manager Timecards Work Area : Local area\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1192\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 122\ndescription: \"\\n        \\t\\n        <ol>\\n\\\n  \\t<dt>Timecards Requiring Approval tab</dt>\\n\\\n  \\t<dt>A custom worklist view of timecards requiring approval by this manager, with approval actions on the tab,  The columns \\tdisplayed for this tab are:</dt>\\n\\n        <dd>o\\tPerson Name</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tRole</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tTimecard Period</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tTimecard Status</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tTotal Hours </dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tPremium Hours</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tNon Worked Hours</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tSubmission Date</dd>\\n        </ol>\\n      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3389,'Feature',1193,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Manager Timecards Work Area : My Directs Timecards\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\npriority: \nid: 1193\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 122\ndescription: \"\\n        \\t<ol><dt>There will be two views available on this tab for ease of finding worker\'s timecards:</dt>\\n\\n        <dd>Gantt View:  This view will display a gantt chart slider across time, in which the manager can see for all of his direct reports, a color display of cells in a grid, each representing a timecard in its own status.  The timecard status colors will be defined in a legend.  The user will be able to expand his display to a 3 month view or drill into a weekly display to get more defined viewing of his timecards.  He will be able to click once to navigate into the timecard from the color cell block.  There will be additional filters to select icons to show additional information about timecards, such as denoting which timecards were late.  The idea behind this view is for the user to easily scroll left and right to find timecards or to see where there are gaps in timecards being entered or find timecards which require attention for a given timeframe.  Page shots of Gantt view in Report Time FDD with further detailed descriptions.\\n        \\n        <dd>Table View:\\n        <ol><dt>The table view will also display timecards for all of the manager\'s direct reports.  The manager should have links to all recent timecards for his workers\' plus any timecards in progress.  This tab should resolve to any timecard watchlist items for the manager.  (Design Issue:  Timecards in Progress may need to be configured at the User \\tPreference level to determine which timecard statuses should be displayed in this region).\\n\\n\\\n  \\tThe filters for this table will be Timecard Status and month.  The actions from this table will be to create timecard.  The \\tcolumns in the table are :</dt>\\n        <dd>o\\tTimecard Period : hyperlinked to take user to that timecard in edit mode, if it is not hyperlinked they do not have access rights to edit that timecard</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tTimecard Status : In Error, Rejected, Submitted, Draft, Approved, Transferred</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tReported Hours : total number of reported hours in the timecard</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tOvertime Hours : total number of overtime hours for the timecard determined by seeded time category</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tSubmission Date : the date the timecard was submitted (if in submitted status)</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tApproval Chain : icon which triggers a pop up of the approval graph display from AMX of the flow of approvers, if has \\tentered Approval flow.  If the timecard has not yet been submitted, the Approval Chain icon will not display.</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tAudit Data : will display a read only checkmark to indicate that this timecard contains a time audit entry page for change and late requirements</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tView Summary : will display an icon, when clicked will take the user to a read only form of the timecard which is configured in the Time Entry Page Composer as a viewable timecard layout.</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tDelete : delete icon to allow the user to delete the timecard.  If the user does not have access rights to delete the timecard, the icon will be grayed out</dd>\\n        </ol>\\n        </dd>\\n        <ol>\\n      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3390,'Feature',1194,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Manager Timecards Work Area : My Timecards\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1194\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 122\ndescription: \"\\n        \\t<ol><dt>There will be two views available on this tab for ease of finding worker\'s timecards:</dt>\\n\\n        <dd>Gantt View:  This view will display a gantt chart slider across time, in which the manager can see for all of his direct reports, a color display of cells in a grid, each representing a timecard in its own status.  The timecard status colors will be defined in a legend.  The user will be able to expand his display to a 3 month view or drill into a weekly display to get more defined viewing of his timecards.  He will be able to click once to navigate into the timecard from the color cell block.  There will be additional filters to select icons to show additional information about timecards, such as denoting which timecards were late.  The idea behind this view is for the user to easily scroll left and right to find timecards or to see where there are gaps in timecards being entered or find timecards which require attention for a given timeframe.  Page shots of Gantt view in Report Time FDD with further detailed descriptions.\\n        \\n        <dd>Table View:\\n        <ol><dt>The table view will also display timecards for all of the manager\'s direct reports.  The manager should have links to all recent timecards for his workers\' plus any timecards in progress.  This tab should resolve to any timecard watchlist items for the manager.  (Design Issue:  Timecards in Progress may need to be configured at the User \\tPreference level to determine which timecard statuses should be displayed in this region).\\n\\n\\\n  \\tThe filters for this table will be Timecard Status and month.  The actions from this table will be to create timecard.  The \\tcolumns in the table are :</dt>\\n        <dd>o\\tTimecard Period : hyperlinked to take user to that timecard in edit mode, if it is not hyperlinked they do not have access rights to edit that timecard</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tTimecard Status : In Error, Rejected, Submitted, Draft, Approved, Transferred</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tReported Hours : total number of reported hours in the timecard</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tOvertime Hours : total number of overtime hours for the timecard determined by seeded time category</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tSubmission Date : the date the timecard was submitted (if in submitted status)</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tApproval Chain : icon which triggers a pop up of the approval graph display from AMX of the flow of approvers, if has \\tentered Approval flow.  If the timecard has not yet been submitted, the Approval Chain icon will not display.</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tAudit Data : will display a read only checkmark to indicate that this timecard contains a time audit entry page for change and late requirements</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tView Summary : will display an icon, when clicked will take the user to a read only form of the timecard which is configured in the Time Entry Page Composer as a viewable timecard layout.</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tDelete : delete icon to allow the user to delete the timecard.  If the user does not have access rights to delete the timecard, the icon will be grayed out</dd>\\n        </ol>\\n        </dd>\\n        <ol>\\n      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3391,'Feature',1195,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worker Timecards Work Area : Regional Area\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1195\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 122\ndescription: \"\\n        <ol><dt>Task Pane:  The three tasks for the task pane will be :<dt>\\n        <dd>o\\tCreate Timecard : upon clicking the Create Timecard link, a calendar widget will open, for the user to select a date.  The worker will then be taken to the timecard which intersects that date in a new dynamic tab.  When the worker has submitted that timecard, the dynamic tab will close.\\n        <dd>o\\tManage Timecards : a link to the Manage Timecards page, which has a search and search results section for the worker\'s timecards, with a default listing of the last 5 recent timecards.  Additionally, it will have the actions of create, delete, edit or view a timecard.  See Section 2.3.3.  Manage Timecards in Report Time FDD for more details.\\n        <dd>o\\tManage Templates : this link will navigate the worker to his Manage Templates page, in which he can view, create, edit or delete his private templates.\\n                \\n        <dt>o\\tSearch Region</dt>\\n\\\n  \\t<dd>Search:  Timecards\\n\\\n  \\tThis region will display a basic search for timecards.  The basic fields will be for Timecard Period  or From and To Date.  If the search has only one result, it will take the user to that timecard.  If there are multiple results, it will take the user to the Manage Timecards search and search results page in a new dynamic tab.  If the user clicks on the Advanced Search button, it will take the user to the Manage Timecards search page as well.</dd>\\n        <ol>\\n      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3392,'Feature',1196,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worker Timecards Work Area : Local Area: Recent timecards\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1196\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 122\ndescription: \"\\n        <ol><dt>Timecards in Progress  table</dt>\\n\\\n  \\t<ol><dt>There will be two views available in this area,  for ease of finding worker\'s timecards:</dt>\\n\\n\\\n  \\t<dd>Calendar View: \\n        There will be a view of timecards for the user to view and access his timecards from a calendar display.  There will be three months displayed at a time, with the ability to scroll to the next three or prior three months. Each timecard period will be highlighted on the calendar, and the user just needs to click on any date in that timecard period, and will be transferred to that timecard.</dd>\\n\\n\\\n  \\t<dd>Table View:\\n\\\n  \\tThis table should contain a listing of all timecards in progress for the manager.  (Design Issue:  Timecards in Progress \\tmay need to be configured at the User Preference level to determine which timecard statuses should be displayed in this \\tregion).\\n\\n\\\n  \\tThis table will be at the top of the workarea page and should resolve to any watchlist items for the worker.  This should \\tbe a listing of all timecards in progress.  (Design Issue:  Timecards in Progress may need to be configured at the User \\tPreference level to determine which timecard statuses should be displayed in this region).</dd>\\n        <ol><dt>\\n\\\n  \\tThe filters for this table will be Timecard Status and month.  The actions from this table will be to create timecard.  The \\tcolumns in the table are :</dt>\\n        <dd>o\\tTimecard Period : hyperlinked to take user to that timecard in edit mode, if it is not hyperlinked they do not have access rights to edit that timecard</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tTimecard Status : In Error, Rejected, Submitted, Draft, Approved, Transferred</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tReported Hours : total number of reported hours in the timecard</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tOvertime Hours : total number of overtime hours for the timecard determined by seeded time category</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tSubmission Date : the date the timecard was submitted (if in submitted status)</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tApproval Chain : icon which triggers a pop up of the approval graph display from AMX of the flow of approvers, if has \\tentered Approval flow.  If the timecard has not yet been submitted, the Approval Chain icon will not display.</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tAudit Data : will display a read only checkmark to indicate that this timecard contains a time audit entry page for change and late requirements</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tView Summary : will display an icon, when clicked will take the user to a read only form of the timecard which is configured in the Time Entry Page Composer as a viewable timecard layout.</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tDelete ? delete icon to allow the user to delete the timecard.  If the user does not have access rights to delete the timecard, the icon will be grayed out</dd>\\n        </ol></ol></ol>        \\n      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3393,'Feature',1197,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worker Timecards Work Area : Local Area: Current Time period\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1197\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 122\ndescription: \"\\n        \\xC2\\xA7\\tLists Timecard Period in display only mode\\n        \\xC2\\xA7\\tLists Timecard Due On \\\"Date/Time\\\"  (if implement Timecard Submission Due Date) in display only mode\\n        \\xC2\\xA7\\tDaily Punch Summary (if worker has clock time in layout)\\n        \\xC2\\xA7\\tWill list current date and total hours logged thus far\\n        \\xC2\\xA7\\tEnter Daily Punch : button which will trigger a pop up screen for clocking in or out and entering timecard \\t\\t\\tfields with it.  (Design to be determined in Web Clock FDD)\\n      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3394,'Feature',1198,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worker Timecards Work Area : Local Area: Timecard Preferences section\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1198\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 122\ndescription: \"\\n        \\xC2\\xA7\\tLists Default Number of Blank Rows (editable by worker via pencil icon) : worker can change the default number of blank rows displayed on a new timecard\\n        \\xC2\\xA7\\tDefault Template : display of worker\'s default private template, with ability to change the template with a pop up\\n\\n      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3395,'Feature',1199,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worker Timecards Work Area : Local Area: Accrual Balances Table\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1199\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 122\ndescription: \"\\n       Table listing of the leave balance accruals with an as of date.  The content \\n       of this table will be determined in Timecard Integration with Absence Management \\n       FDD.\\n      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3396,'Feature',1200,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worker Timecards Work Area : Local Area: Project Plan Snapshot\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1200\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 122\ndescription: \"\\n       Snapshot of the worker\'s current scheduled tasks in the Projects project plan      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3397,'Feature',1201,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worker Timecards Work Area : Local Area:Common Calendar Display\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1201\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 122\ndescription: \"\\n       Display of the worker\'s current common calendar display of holidays, absences, availability and hours worked (Common \\tCalendar design to be determined )\\n       \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3398,'Feature',1202,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worker Timecards Work Area : Local Area:Time Balance Monitor\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1202\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 122\ndescription: \"\\n       Listing of the Balances made available along with measuring against defined thresholds\\n       \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3399,'FunctionalWorkUnit',122,'destroy','1','--- \nname: Time and Labor Analytics\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:07 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 122\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3400,'Feature',1203,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Calculation Rules\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1203\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 123\ndescription: If the Rules Processing Engine is the heart of the TCR module, the Time Calculation Rules are the soul.  Without Time Calculation rules, the engine will have nothing to process and the TCR module is just an empty box.  The Time Calculation rules will contain the actual business logic that the customer wants to apply to the time.  Time Calculation Rules will be written as Fast Formulas, a business processing language already widely used throughout HCM for other types of business rules (e.g. Benefits, Payroll, etc.).\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3401,'Feature',1204,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: OTL Rules are consistent across the OTL Application\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1204\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 123\ndescription: OTL will deliver rules of different types (TER, TCR, TAR, and TIR) that are defined and assigned in a similar manner.  The Rule engine may or may not be the same (based on Development design) but should appear the same functionally.\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3402,'Feature',1205,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Enable Configurable Sort options for Timecard Entries prior to application of (TER, TCR, TAR, TIR (future)) Rules \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1205\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 123\ndescription: |-\n  The Rule set for each type of rule (TER, TCR, TAR, etc) must allow for a sort option, where OTL Development delivers the standard sort option used in EBS R12.  The Sort Option will reference a choice list where customer defined functions may be registered, and displayed for selection.  The sort options will then affect the execution of rules, since specific entries processed first may result in different end values.\n  \n  OTL Development will also deliver information on how to define new sort options and how to register them.\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3403,'Feature',1206,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Allow for overrides of Calculated Rule Results\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1206\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 123\ndescription: \"OTL Development will allow for Layouts defined with an editable rule result section to be assigned to timekeepers to manually adjust calculated results.  The Timecard containing adjusted results should be \\xE2\\x80\\x98identifiable\\xE2\\x80\\x99 so that a message may be shown explain how the results were arrived at.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3404,'Feature',1207,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Viewing the Calculation Results\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1207\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 123\ndescription: This is closely related to the previous feature in that customers want to be able to control not only when to perform the calculations, but also to determine when and how to show it to the users (if at all).  This is related because obviously you can only show the calculations results after you performed the calculation itself.  But customers can opt not to show the results at all (even though the calculation was done) or perform the calculation on submission, but only show the result after review or approval.\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3405,'Feature',1208,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Customer control over when to apply Time Calculation Rules\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1208\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 123\ndescription: We need to provide a feature that allows our customers to determine when the rules get applied to the entered timecard.  In other words, where (if at all) in the Timecard Entry flow the time calculation rules will get applied.  In addition, this feature needs to allow customers to postpone the calculation when they feel this is needed.  A typical example is an incomplete timecard, there might not be a point in performing any calculations on such a timecard (although I would assume that this would mean they save the timecard and they would select not to perform calculations on a Saved Timecard).\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3406,'Feature',1209,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Control over which Time Business Rule to apply and when\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1209\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 123\ndescription: \"One of our more critical requirements is the ability to be able to determine the \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cflavor\\xE2\\x80\\x9D of rule that gets applied depending on what the user enters on his timecard.  Probably the most frequent occurrence is that overtime isn\\xE2\\x80\\x99t being calculated the same in every state in the US.  How it gets calculated literally depends on where (in which state) the time was actually worked.  In other words, which flavor of Overtime Rule gets fired depends on what the user enters as location on his timecard (location being an attribute of the time).  We need to allow customers to use every attribute or combination of attribute (we\\xE2\\x80\\x99ll use Time Categories) as a \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cdecider\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.  Obviously, at setup, administrators do not know what the user is going to enter so they need to cater for all and we need to provide them with a feature that allows them to do this.  As a result a \\xE2\\x80\\x9Crule\\xE2\\x80\\x9D is going to be a combination of different Fast Formula that contain different business logic.  Which of these Fast Formulas will fire for that rule will then depend on the attributes on the timecards.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3407,'Feature',1210,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Total Control over Results of Rules\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1210\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 123\ndescription: \"Customers not only want control over the measure or IN OUT columns, they want to have total control over the attributes resulting from the TCR Rules as well.  In the TCR Rules Results, we will allow them to \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cset\\xE2\\x80\\x9D attribution based on a RETURN value from the Rule\\xE2\\x80\\x99s Fast Formula or specify the attribute value in the Rules Results themselves.  Either way, this will provide them with the flexibility to control any attribute on the resulting calculated time entries.\\n\\n\\\n  Also, because we are allowing calculations on all kinds of time, meaning for all kinds of attributes, it becomes very hard for us in development to know exactly what needs to be the result of a rule, in fact it is impossible to know and most likely it is different for different customers, so opening this up for our customers is necessary and unavoidable.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:35'),(3408,'Feature',1211,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Balances\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1211\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 123\ndescription: Some time business rules require time to be aggregated over a period of time.  Just like we do not know what kind of business rules customers want to apply to their time, we generally do not know how they want to aggregate time.  Not only do we not know the period but we also do not know what kind of time they want to group.  Depending on the attribution time might be in our out of the balance.  Therefore, we need to let our users setup their own Time Balances and we will leverage Payroll Balances to accomplish this.  This introduces a dependency on Core Payroll to ensure that Payroll Balances work with Time (instead of pay values).  Because we are able to use Payroll Balances, this feature requires no coding.  However, we need to seed the basic components of a balance (Balance Types and Balance Dimensions) so our users can create balances in the first place.\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:36'),(3409,'Feature',1212,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Rule Assignment\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1212\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 123\ndescription: \"Once the rules have been created, they need to somehow be \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cassigned\\xE2\\x80\\x9D to people so that those rules get applied to those employees\\xE2\\x80\\x99 timecards.  Therefore we will create a new preference or preference segment that allows customers to create a preference and pick a Time Calculation Rule Set, and then assign this preference per the preference module to individuals or groups using the available preference criteria.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:36'),(3410,'Feature',1213,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Work Day Definition\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1213\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 123\ndescription: \"Normally, a day is considered to start at 00:00:00 and end at 23:59:59 but for rules this definition is not always useable.  Sometimes it is necessary for a rule to interpret a day slightly different and a day would go from say 22:00 to 21:59:59 the next day, overlapping 2 real days.  As rules are sometimes dependant on a day, it is important that we let our customers decide when these \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cwork days\\xE2\\x80\\x9D start and end so their rules apply as they see fit.  A typical example is a premium that depends on a day, say Sunday.  If the shift starts on a that day \\xE2\\x80\\x93 Sunday 22:00 \\xE2\\x80\\x93 but runs into the next day \\xE2\\x80\\x93 Monday 06:00 \\xE2\\x80\\x93 then they employee might be entitled to the Sunday Premium the whole shift, even though he only really worked 2 hours on Sunday, and the rest on Monday.  Or he might not be.  This is entirely up to the customer and as a result we need to let them decide when a day starts or stops in relation to a Rule.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:36'),(3411,'Feature',1214,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Ability to use HR Holiday Calendar in TCR\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1214\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 123\ndescription: \"This feature will allow TCR to become \\xE2\\x80\\x9Choliday aware\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.  This awareness can then be used in rules or to determine which rules need to be used depending on the Holiday.  This feature will rely heavily on the HR Calendar module that stores the corporate Holiday Calendar.  In TCR, you will then be able to link Rules to this calendar and as a result get different rules on those Holiday Days.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:36'),(3412,'Feature',1215,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Calculation Templates\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1215\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 123\ndescription: \"TCR Templates are probably the feature that will make or break TCR.  Because the TCR module allows for so much flexibility, creating even the simplest of rules could become a pretty daunting task.  We need to try to avoid this at all costs and this is where templates will come in.  Therefore, for certain rules (and we still need to determine which ones) we will provide \\xE2\\x80\\x9Crule templates\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.  These rule templates will consists of a Fast Formula Template, and a form which can be used to answer a few questions that are needed to transform the template into a real Fast Formula.  Behind the scenes it will also create the Rule Results (again based on answers from the user), the processing rule (when the Fast Formula needs to fire), potentially a new balance and anything else that is necessary for it to become a rule that can be used in a Time Calculation Rule Set.\\n\\n\\\n  On the other side of the spectrum, we know that we cannot create formulas for all possible scenarios and so we also need to expose forms that our customers can use to create rules from scratch.  This would mean a form to create Fast Formulas (re-using the Payroll / HR Fast Formula Form), Rule Template (defining inputs and outputs then shown on the Rule Page)TCR Rules, TCR Rule Results and Balances.  T&L will make the Template page a mandatory step in defining new rules, placed over the formula, and making the actual rule creation a bit more functional.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:36'),(3413,'Feature',1216,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Tags\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1216\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 123\ndescription: \"Littered throughout the requirement document, there are references to a so called \\xE2\\x80\\x9CRule Type\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.  The purpose of this type was that we might be able to classify rules into these types and make it easier for our users to find a particular rule using the Rule Type.  This Rule Type however is probably too restrictive.  We will not be able to stripe our data by Business Group anymore, nor by Legislation (this is a functional decision; rules are to be global), so this type should also replace that functionality.  Finally, some rules cannot be easily classified and users can create their own rules for which we would have no type handy.  All this means that we need more flexible way to classify rules so that customers can find the rules they need.\\n\\n\\\n  We opted for a tagging (aka labeling) mechanism.  This allows our customers to add as many tags as the want to their rules that will make it easy for them to find them back later on.  E.g. a threshold rule could have the following tags: us overtime 8.  These 3 tags would indicate that the actual threshold rule is a rule that applies to the US, calculates Overtime, and has a threshold of 8.  Whenever the users need to search for a Rule, they can supply any combination of tags and a list of rules matching those tags will appear.  For example, they might want to see all rules that have \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cus\\xE2\\x80\\x9D as a tag (presumably these are rules applicable to the US legislation, but the point is that it could really mean anything the customer wants it to be).\\n\\n\\\n  The tagging infrastructure will also be made available for other entities in HXC, and we might use it as well for TCR fast Formulas.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:36'),(3414,'FunctionalWorkUnit',123,'destroy','1','--- \nname: Time and Labor Time Calculation Rules and Rule Sets\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 123\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:36'),(3415,'Feature',1217,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: No Name\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\npriority: \nid: 1217\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 124\ndescription: \"  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:36'),(3416,'FunctionalWorkUnit',124,'destroy','1','--- \nname: \"Time and Labor Public Timecard Template \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:08 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 196\nid: 124\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:36'),(3417,'BusinessArea',196,'destroy','1','--- \nname: FDDs\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:37:04 Z\nid: 196\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:36'),(3418,'BusinessArea',197,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3419,'FunctionalWorkUnit',125,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3420,'Feature',1218,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3421,'FunctionalWorkUnit',126,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3422,'Feature',1219,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3423,'Feature',1220,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3424,'FunctionalWorkUnit',127,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3425,'Feature',1221,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3426,'Feature',1222,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3427,'Feature',1223,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3428,'Feature',1224,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3429,'Feature',1225,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3430,'Feature',1226,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3431,'Feature',1227,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3432,'Feature',1228,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3433,'Feature',1229,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3434,'Feature',1230,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3435,'Feature',1231,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:21'),(3436,'Feature',1232,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:22'),(3437,'Feature',1233,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:22'),(3438,'Feature',1234,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:22'),(3439,'Feature',1235,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:22'),(3440,'Feature',1236,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:38:22'),(3441,'Feature',1237,'create',NULL,NUL