ve\nid: 1362\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Support Existing EBS OTL R12 rule functionality\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Provide ability to incorporate the triggering of Time Entry Rules upon save or submission of the timecard.  These rules will trigger validations, which errors need to be corrected before the timecard can be submitted for approval. \\r\\n\\\n  Seeded Time Entry Rules to include such rules as : Overlapping Time Entries Rule. This rule checks for clock times which overlap each other.   All Seeded Rules will be noted in Rules FDD.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:13:22'),(6849,'Feature',1362,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Time Entry Rules - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:23 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 22:13:22 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1362\nfeature_type: Business Rule\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Support Existing EBS OTL R12 rule functionality\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Provide ability to incorporate the triggering of Time Entry Rules upon save or submission of the timecard.  These rules will trigger validations, which errors need to be corrected before the timecard can be submitted for approval. \\r\\n\\\n  Seeded Time Entry Rules to include such rules as : Overlapping Time Entries Rule. This rule checks for clock times which overlap each other.   All Seeded Rules will be noted in Rules FDD.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:13:41'),(6850,'Feature',1363,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Time Interaction Rules - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:23 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-03 22:34:22 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1363\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Enhance Existing EBS OTL R12 rule functionality\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Provide ability to incorporate the triggering of Time Interaction Rules upon opening timecard.  These rules will allow for different page displays, different messages, graying of columns, etc.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:14:29'),(6851,'Feature',1363,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Time Interaction Rules - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:23 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 22:14:29 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1363\nfeature_type: Business Rule\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Enhance Existing EBS OTL R12 rule functionality\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Provide ability to incorporate the triggering of Time Interaction Rules upon opening timecard.  These rules will allow for different page displays, different messages, graying of columns, etc.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:14:40'),(6852,'Feature',1364,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Time Calculation Rules - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:23 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-03 22:34:57 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1364\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Support Existing EBS OTL R12 rule functionality\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Provide ability to incorporate the triggering of Time Calculation Rules upon save or submission of the timecard, which will produce rule results.  These results are the conversion of raw time into processed time which will be sent for approval and ultimately transferred to a receiving application such as Payroll or Project Portfolio Management. \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  All Seeded Rules will be noted in Rules FDD.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:15:11'),(6853,'Feature',1364,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Time Calculation Rules - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:23 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 22:15:11 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1364\nfeature_type: Business Rule\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Support Existing EBS OTL R12 rule functionality\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Provide ability to incorporate the triggering of Time Calculation Rules upon save or submission of the timecard, which will produce rule results.  These results are the conversion of raw time into processed time which will be sent for approval and ultimately transferred to a receiving application such as Payroll or Project Portfolio Management. \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  All Seeded Rules will be noted in Rules FDD.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:15:24'),(6854,'Feature',1365,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Time Audit Rules - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:23 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-03 22:36:58 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1365\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Support Existing EBS OTL R12 rule functionality\\r\\n\\\n  \\t        \\r\\n\\\n  Provide ability to incorporate the triggering of Time Audit Rules upon save or submission of the timecard, if Time and Labor Setup Profile Options defined the association of a Change and Late Audit Layout Set to the worker.  This     will trigger the user to enter reason codes and comments for changed time or late time entries.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  \\xE2\\x80\\xA2\\tLate Rule - will trigger display of Time Audit Entry page, if there are any time entries identified as being late\\r\\n\\\n  \\xE2\\x80\\xA2\\tChange Rule \\xE2\\x80\\x93 will trigger display of Time Audit Entry page, if there are any time entries identified as being changed\\r\\n\"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:17:06'),(6855,'Feature',1366,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Rule Results - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:23 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-03 22:37:31 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1366\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Support Existing EBS OTL R12 Rule Results functionality\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Provide ability to summarize time by Hours Type when applying Time Calculation Rules on the Timecard Review page.   There should be flexibility to place this section in different pages, as long as there is a call to the Time Calculation rules.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:17:53'),(6856,'Feature',1366,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Rule Results - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:23 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 22:17:53 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1366\nfeature_type: UI\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Support Existing EBS OTL R12 Rule Results functionality\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Provide ability to summarize time by Hours Type when applying Time Calculation Rules on the Timecard Review page.   There should be flexibility to place this section in different pages, as long as there is a call to the Time Calculation rules.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:18:09'),(6857,'Feature',1367,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Import Time - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:23 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-03 22:38:32 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1367\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Support Existing EBS OTL R12 import timecard functionality\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Provide services to import time into the timecard from clocks or other external time collection integrations.  This includes the ability to import time from an excel spreadsheet, with ability to use templates and downloaded choicelist values on the excel spreadsheet for detached time entry.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  See sections 2.3.6 and 2.3.7 for further details on import of time using ADFdi.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:19:11'),(6858,'Feature',1371,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Payroll and Project Adjustments to Reported Time (raw time) - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-03 23:05:11 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1371\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Retain Source of Change in Time and Labor, enhance ability to reconcile time between Time and Labor, Payroll and Projects (PPM) \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  There is a need to adjust time in timecards after they have been submitted for approval and routed to Payroll or Projects for processing.  There are many reasons why adjustments to the timecard are needed.  It can be that the original time was entered incorrectly, either because time was entered in advance and the actual hours changed or because the hours were booked to the wrong project/tasks or wrong departments.  Additionally, time may have been entered as paid leave to which the employee was not entitled, and the time has to be rebooked as unpaid leave.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Payroll Managers may need to go back and ensure adjustments are made to time, in order for time to be paid correctly in payroll.  Project Managers or Project Accountants may need to go back and make changes to time, to rebook hours to different combinations of Projects and Tasks or change work time to sick or vacation time, or visa versa.  These adjustments are required for proper billing to customers and correct updates to project plans.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  In order for Payroll Managers, Project Managers and Project Accountants to make the adjustments to time, the best approach is for them to have access to change time at the source, reported time in the Timecard Entry page.  For that reason, based on role assignment of \\xE2\\x80\\x9Ctimekeeper\\xE2\\x80\\x9D, they can be given access to our Group Time Entry feature to make these adjustments.  The access to the workers who require adjustments can be derived from defined group criteria.  The display of the needed fields will be determined via delivered Layout sets with Payroll and Projects.    See Group Time Entry FDD for more details on access to employees via Groups and time entry functionality by worker or batch views, as well as mass time entry updates.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  As the flow of these time adjustments may have a hard deadline because of a payroll to be processed or a billing cycle which needs to be closed in Projects, expedited processing is needed.  An attribute could be stored within the timecard to be populated when an adjustment is occurring (upon submit of the adjusted timecard).  If this attribute is populated, then as the timecard enters the AMX Approval flow, this attribute can trigger an auto-approval rule which automatically approves the timecard.  At that point, the timecard will be immediately available for the transfer services to deposit it into the interface tables for immediate retrieval by Payroll and Projects.\\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:21:44'),(6859,'Feature',1372,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Adjustments to Processed Time - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-03 23:05:57 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1372\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Allow for Exception Measures to Correct Time for Immediate Transfer of Time  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Processed Time is the net result of time calculation rules being applied to raw time in a timecard.  Normally, processed time should only be updated by the running of these rules in an online or batch process.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  There is the situation in which the rule results in processed time were not what was expected.  If the user (timekeeper or administrator) does not have adequate time to change the rules setup , or using override rules on the timecard would not resolve the time correctly, then the user should be able to make adjustments to the actual processed time.  The security for the duty of updating processed time should be very controlled as this is not a normal method of processing time.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  The timekeeper or administrator who is granted access to adjust calculated time, would  be given access to our Group Time Entry feature to make these adjustments.  The access to the workers who require adjustments can be derived from defined group criteria.  The individual timecard view will display a section for Processed Time results.  Based on security and layout set, the administrator will be able to have edit access to this section.  Once the administrator makes his changes and saves or submits the timecard, there will be a message associated with the Process Time Section that \\xE2\\x80\\x9CProcessed Time has been adjusted\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.  See Group Time Entry FDD for more details on access to employees via Groups and time entry functionality by worker or batch views, as well as mass time entry updates.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  As with adjustments to raw time, there may be a hard deadline because of a payroll to be processed or a billing cycle which needs to be closed in Projects.  This should invoke the  expedited processing  for the adjusted timecard.  If this is necessary, the administrator can select timecards which are required to be \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cforced transfer\\xE2\\x80\\x9D to time consumers by a separate \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cforced transfer\\xE2\\x80\\x9D action.   The timecards will still be routed through the normal approval flow in AMX, but will be immediately available to be retrieved by time consumers once they are marked as \\xE2\\x80\\x9CForced Transfer\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  In the future, if there need to be any updates to the raw time of the timecard, we should allow the updates to occur.  After the timecard is submitted, a workflow notification \\xE2\\x80\\x9CReview changes to adjusted timecard\\xE2\\x80\\x9D should be triggered and sent to the administrator.  This notification will contain the adjustments made to the processed time on the last version of the timecard.  The administrator will need to determine if he needs to reapply adjustments to processed time to the timecard.  Once he is complete, he will submit the timecard, and the timecard will be routed via the AMX approval flow.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  The adjustments to processed time need to be tracked from an audit perspective, just as changed to raw time would.  We need to know the person, role, date/time and updates made to the timecard.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  The complete flow of dealing with adjustments to raw or processed time will be covered in a new FDD, Time and Labor Validations and Adjustments FDD.\\r\\n\"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:23:26'),(6860,'Feature',1372,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: General Adjustments to Processed Time\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 22:23:41 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1372\nfeature_type: Miscellaneous\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Allow for Exception Measures to Correct Time for Immediate Transfer of Time  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Processed Time is the net result of time calculation rules being applied to raw time in a timecard.  Normally, processed time should only be updated by the running of these rules in an online or batch process.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  There is the situation in which the rule results in processed time were not what was expected.  If the user (timekeeper or administrator) does not have adequate time to change the rules setup , or using override rules on the timecard would not resolve the time correctly, then the user should be able to make adjustments to the actual processed time.  The security for the duty of updating processed time should be very controlled as this is not a normal method of processing time.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  The timekeeper or administrator who is granted access to adjust calculated time, would  be given access to our Group Time Entry feature to make these adjustments.  The access to the workers who require adjustments can be derived from defined group criteria.  The individual timecard view will display a section for Processed Time results.  Based on security and layout set, the administrator will be able to have edit access to this section.  Once the administrator makes his changes and saves or submits the timecard, there will be a message associated with the Process Time Section that \\xE2\\x80\\x9CProcessed Time has been adjusted\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.  See Group Time Entry FDD for more details on access to employees via Groups and time entry functionality by worker or batch views, as well as mass time entry updates.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  As with adjustments to raw time, there may be a hard deadline because of a payroll to be processed or a billing cycle which needs to be closed in Projects.  This should invoke the  expedited processing  for the adjusted timecard.  If this is necessary, the administrator can select timecards which are required to be \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cforced transfer\\xE2\\x80\\x9D to time consumers by a separate \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cforced transfer\\xE2\\x80\\x9D action.   The timecards will still be routed through the normal approval flow in AMX, but will be immediately available to be retrieved by time consumers once they are marked as \\xE2\\x80\\x9CForced Transfer\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  In the future, if there need to be any updates to the raw time of the timecard, we should allow the updates to occur.  After the timecard is submitted, a workflow notification \\xE2\\x80\\x9CReview changes to adjusted timecard\\xE2\\x80\\x9D should be triggered and sent to the administrator.  This notification will contain the adjustments made to the processed time on the last version of the timecard.  The administrator will need to determine if he needs to reapply adjustments to processed time to the timecard.  Once he is complete, he will submit the timecard, and the timecard will be routed via the AMX approval flow.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  The adjustments to processed time need to be tracked from an audit perspective, just as changed to raw time would.  We need to know the person, role, date/time and updates made to the timecard.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  The complete flow of dealing with adjustments to raw or processed time will be covered in a new FDD, Time and Labor Validations and Adjustments FDD.\\r\\n\"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:23:48'),(6861,'Feature',1371,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: \"General Adjustments to Raw Time \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 22:22:59 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1371\nfeature_type: Miscellaneous\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Retain Source of Change in Time and Labor, enhance ability to reconcile time between Time and Labor, Payroll and Projects (PPM) \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  There is a need to adjust time in timecards after they have been submitted for approval and routed to Payroll or Projects for processing.  There are many reasons why adjustments to the timecard are needed.  It can be that the original time was entered incorrectly, either because time was entered in advance and the actual hours changed or because the hours were booked to the wrong project/tasks or wrong departments.  Additionally, time may have been entered as paid leave to which the employee was not entitled, and the time has to be rebooked as unpaid leave.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Payroll Managers may need to go back and ensure adjustments are made to time, in order for time to be paid correctly in payroll.  Project Managers or Project Accountants may need to go back and make changes to time, to rebook hours to different combinations of Projects and Tasks or change work time to sick or vacation time, or visa versa.  These adjustments are required for proper billing to customers and correct updates to project plans.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  In order for Payroll Managers, Project Managers and Project Accountants to make the adjustments to time, the best approach is for them to have access to change time at the source, reported time in the Timecard Entry page.  For that reason, based on role assignment of \\xE2\\x80\\x9Ctimekeeper\\xE2\\x80\\x9D, they can be given access to our Group Time Entry feature to make these adjustments.  The access to the workers who require adjustments can be derived from defined group criteria.  The display of the needed fields will be determined via delivered Layout sets with Payroll and Projects.    See Group Time Entry FDD for more details on access to employees via Groups and time entry functionality by worker or batch views, as well as mass time entry updates.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  As the flow of these time adjustments may have a hard deadline because of a payroll to be processed or a billing cycle which needs to be closed in Projects, expedited processing is needed.  An attribute could be stored within the timecard to be populated when an adjustment is occurring (upon submit of the adjusted timecard).  If this attribute is populated, then as the timecard enters the AMX Approval flow, this attribute can trigger an auto-approval rule which automatically approves the timecard.  At that point, the timecard will be immediately available for the transfer services to deposit it into the interface tables for immediate retrieval by Payroll and Projects.\\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:23:54'),(6862,'Feature',1373,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: \" Validating Time by Consuming Applications and T&L\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 22:24:56 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1373\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Support Existing Validation Process of EBS Time and Labor R12 with enhancements for Fusion    \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Validations of time will be applied as the user moves through the timecard process, specific to validations delivered by Payroll or Project sections.  The set of validations and related error messages will be delivered by Payroll and Project Development teams and will be called as services upon either action of the timecard.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  We need the ability to validate raw time (originally entered time) or processed time (time processed as a result of time calculation rules).  Validations on raw time is validating what the user actually enters on their timecard entry page.  The validations on processed time is validating the results of applying time calculation rules. The validations on processed time is new for Fusion.   The reason for validating processed time is that is what the time consumers, Payroll and Projects (PPM) will receive and validate as they receive it. Validating the time at the point of entry will save time later from having transfer errors because the timecard could not be accepted by the time consumer.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Errors which are generated from validations will be displayed to the user in an error message listing pop-up on the Timecard Entry page.  If the worker or timecard user cannot resolve the errors from processed time validations , due to the fact that setup objects need to be adjusted in some way, the timecard flow needs to continue.  The proper processing of the timecards when validations fail will be covered in depth in a new Time and Labor Validations and Adjustments FDD .\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:25:01'),(6863,'Feature',1373,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: \" Validating Time by Consuming Applications and T&L\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 22:25:01 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1373\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 167\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Support Existing Validation Process of EBS Time and Labor R12 with enhancements for Fusion    \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Validations of time will be applied as the user moves through the timecard process, specific to validations delivered by Payroll or Project sections.  The set of validations and related error messages will be delivered by Payroll and Project Development teams and will be called as services upon either action of the timecard.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  We need the ability to validate raw time (originally entered time) or processed time (time processed as a result of time calculation rules).  Validations on raw time is validating what the user actually enters on their timecard entry page.  The validations on processed time is validating the results of applying time calculation rules. The validations on processed time is new for Fusion.   The reason for validating processed time is that is what the time consumers, Payroll and Projects (PPM) will receive and validate as they receive it. Validating the time at the point of entry will save time later from having transfer errors because the timecard could not be accepted by the time consumer.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Errors which are generated from validations will be displayed to the user in an error message listing pop-up on the Timecard Entry page.  If the worker or timecard user cannot resolve the errors from processed time validations , due to the fact that setup objects need to be adjusted in some way, the timecard flow needs to continue.  The proper processing of the timecards when validations fail will be covered in depth in a new Time and Labor Validations and Adjustments FDD .\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:25:14'),(6864,'Feature',1374,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Timecard Period Navigation Options - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-03 23:09:36 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1374\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Support Tier 1 Timecard UI Display shown to customers\\r\\n\\\n  \\t\\r\\n\\\n  As discussed in the Time Entry Page Composer FDD, there will be different options to choose for the user to \\tchange time periods on the timecard.  The following are the two preferred options from customer validation \\tsessions and competitive research.\\r\\n\\\n  a.   Local Area Option\\t\\r\\n\\\n  Calendar pop up widget\\r\\n \\r\\n               \\r\\n\\\n  To select a different time period from the local area calendar widget: \\r\\n\\\n  o\\tClick on Calendar widget displayed after the timecard period, select a date  and time period is refreshed on page to the period which intersects with that date.  To be determined in technical design if the period exceeds a week, whether the user will be taken to the beginning of the timecard period or to the week which intersects the date.   \\r\\n\\\n  o\\tOpen design issue:   need to determine if a new tab is opened when a new timecard period is selected, or refresh the existing timecard with the new time  period, warning the user that their changes need to be saved before navigating away from the timecard period.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  b.    Contextual Area Option\\r\\n\\\n  Open Calendar Navigation\\r\\n \\r\\n\\\n  The idea is to always have an opened calendar display for the user, to highlight the current timecard period which is currently displayed, and be allowed to select the next or previous timecard period by clicking on any date in the calendar month displayed.  \\r\\n\\\n  Once the new date is clicked on, the related timecard period will be highlighted and the local display of that timecard period would either be refreshed to reflect those dates, or a new tab would open for that new timecard period.  This is helpful if the user wants to compare entries from one timecard to another. \\xE2\\x80\\x93 Open Design Issue\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Ideally, this display would appear in the Regional section of the timecard, as other navigational tools appear.  Currently, there are constraints on needing it to appear in the Contextual section of the page due to navigational flows and ability to control the calendar display by application specific code.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Design Note:  This use of the Calendar widget requires enhancements from ADF on this component to support the highlighting of a time period based on a selected date.  Also noted that it would be nice to see the timecard period date range displayed in the calendar widget header based on the period highlighted.\"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:28:11'),(6865,'Feature',1375,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Timecard IntraPeriod Navigation Options - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-03 23:10:33 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1375\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification:   Support Tier 1 Timecard UI Display shown to customers\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Allowing for intraperiod navigation provides for timecards whose length in days might be longer than a week,   to \\tprovide the user an easy way to navigate from week to week.  At this point we are not offering a switcher for less than a \\tweek.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\tPrior to Fusion, the timecard user would have a horizontal scroll to navigate through the timecard \\tdays.  The \\tfollowing are two options the user can choose from in the Time Entry Page Composer.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\tThe display of a timecard period will always start with the start date of the timecard instance.\\r\\n\\\n  \\tA.  Weekly Selector\\r\\n\\\n  \\tAllows for a user to easily navigate from one week to another for timecard periods which exceed one week.  This option \\twould allow the user to not have to scroll horizontally through weeks, but be able to click an arrow to the next week or \\tprior week within the timecard.  This would be most beneficial for bi-weekly timecard users.  \\r\\n\\\n  For semi-monthly or monthly timecard periods, there may be  days not applicable at the end of the week which are not part of the current period, which would be grayed out.  There would be a week selector above the timecard matrix for the user to navigate back and forth between the weeks within the timecard period.  The day/date columns would just change in the user\\xE2\\x80\\x99s view.  The other attributes would remain in display, as if the columns were frozen before the day/date fields.  The column and row totals would need to reflect only the totals of the days displayed to the user.  As a result, the attributes from one week would display on the other weeks, since only the days are being scrolled to the right.\\r\\n\\\n  \\tWeekly Selector prototype:\\r\\n \\r\\n\\\n  Open Design Issue:  An issue with this design is the error messaging reference to the correct location of the error.  If the user is accessing the error message listing pop-up (listed above in Must Have Section 2.3.1), and clicks on the error message, the cursor should take the user to where the error exists in the timecard matrix.  With the intra-period navigation, not all entries are visible at once, so this functionality would not work.  A recommendation from UX is that when the user is accessing errors from the error message listing pop-up the intra-period navigation is hidden and the user will get the normal horizontal scroll through the days.\\r\\n\\\n  B.  Horizontal Scroll with Column Grouping by Week\\r\\n\\\n  This design is an alternate design option to allow for horizontal scroll through the timecard period.  Both options will be available in the timecard layout set creation. The attributes would not scroll, only the days of the week.  As the user clicked on a hyperlink for Week 1, Week 2, etc, the matrix would advance to that week, by displaying the first day of the week within the view of days.  There would not need to be an \\xE2\\x80\\x9Coverflow\\xE2\\x80\\x9D icon, as we would not exceed the display of 4 weeks in a timecard.\\r\\n\"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:31:55'),(6866,'Feature',1380,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Audit Log - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-05 19:41:30 Z\npriority: Should Have\nid: 1380\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Should Have Justification:  Support EBS R12.1 Enhancement\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Allow for an ongoing audit display at the footer of the timecard in a collapsible section, to record each time the timecard has been modified.  This would record all possible timecard actions, except deletion which will need to be recorded via an audit report.  The other attributes to be recorded would include:\\r\\n\\\n  o\\tUser \\xE2\\x80\\x93 the ID or name of the person making the change\\r\\n\\\n  o\\tAction \\xE2\\x80\\x93 actions which have occurred on the timecard such as: timecard modified, timecard created, timecard approved\\r\\n\\\n  o\\tDate Timestamp \\xE2\\x80\\x93 actual date and time of the timecard action as it was saved or submitted\\r\\n\\\n  o\\tRole \\xE2\\x80\\x93 job role of the user who took action on  the timecard \\r\\n\\\n  \\tThis Audit log feature expands on the enhancement made in EBS OTL R12.1 - Display last person who updated timesheet (HRMS-OTL-31)   This enhancement enabled the user to view the person who last updated the time details on the timecard. As a timecard can undergo many changes after an employee creates it, providing this information on the timecard enables you to identify the person who last made changes to the timecard.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:32:56'),(6867,'Feature',1380,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Audit Log - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 22:32:56 Z\npriority: Should Have\nid: 1380\nfeature_type: \"\"\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Should Have Justification:  Support EBS R12.1 Enhancement\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Allow for an ongoing audit display at the footer of the timecard in a collapsible section, to record each time the timecard has been modified.  This would record all possible timecard actions, except deletion which will need to be recorded via an audit report.  The other attributes to be recorded would include:\\r\\n\\\n  o\\tUser \\xE2\\x80\\x93 the ID or name of the person making the change\\r\\n\\\n  o\\tAction \\xE2\\x80\\x93 actions which have occurred on the timecard such as: timecard modified, timecard created, timecard approved\\r\\n\\\n  o\\tDate Timestamp \\xE2\\x80\\x93 actual date and time of the timecard action as it was saved or submitted\\r\\n\\\n  o\\tRole \\xE2\\x80\\x93 job role of the user who took action on  the timecard \\r\\n\\\n  \\tThis Audit log feature expands on the enhancement made in EBS OTL R12.1 - Display last person who updated timesheet (HRMS-OTL-31)   This enhancement enabled the user to view the person who last updated the time details on the timecard. As a timecard can undergo many changes after an employee creates it, providing this information on the timecard enables you to identify the person who last made changes to the timecard.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:33:51'),(6868,'Feature',1380,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Time Entry - Audit values of all updates\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 22:34:33 Z\npriority: Should Have\nid: 1380\nfeature_type: Miscellaneous\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Allow for an ongoing audit display at the footer of the timecard in a collapsible section, to record each time the timecard has been modified.  This would record all possible timecard actions, except deletion which will need to be recorded via an audit report.  The other attributes to be recorded would include:\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  >>\\tUser \\xE2\\x80\\x93 the ID or name of the person making the change\\r\\n\\\n  >>\\tAction \\xE2\\x80\\x93 actions which have occurred on the timecard such as: timecard modified, timecard created, timecard approved\\r\\n\\\n  >>\\tDate Timestamp \\xE2\\x80\\x93 actual date and time of the timecard action as it was saved or submitted\\r\\n\\\n  >>\\tRole \\xE2\\x80\\x93 job role of the user who took action on  the timecard \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  This Audit log feature expands on the enhancement made in EBS OTL R12.1 - Display last person who updated timesheet (HRMS-OTL-31)   This enhancement enabled the user to view the person who last updated the time details on the timecard. As a timecard can undergo many changes after an employee creates it, providing this information on the timecard enables you to identify the person who last made changes to the timecard.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:34:36'),(6869,'Feature',1461,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"\"\nname: Timecard Level Actions - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-05-02 12:30:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-05 21:25:22 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1461\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Uptake of Fusion Page Action Guidelines\\r\\n\\\n  \\tFor the normal timecard flow, the buttons which will be enabled are as follows:\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  \\t\\tTimecard Entry page:\\t\\t  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  \\t\\tTimecard Review page:\\t\\t   \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  a.  Next button - takes user to the Timecard Review page, from the Timecard Entry page. Upon clicking on the Next button, application validations and time entry, audit and calculation errors will be triggered.   If there are any resulting errors, the user will be kept on the Timecard Entry page, will have highlighted errors and will need to resolve the errors before successfully submitting the timecard.   If the timecard has errors as a result of validations on processed results but not raw time, the user will be forwarded to the Timecard Review page.  Processed results section will not be populated on the Timecard Review page in this scenario.  The user will get an informational message that processed results could not be displayed due to validation errors.  They will be told to submit the timecard for resolution of these errors by their timecard administrator.  The status of the timecard will be in Pending Resolution until these errors are resolved.  Further discussion of the resolution of errors for processed results will be noted in the Time and Labor Validations and Adjustments FDD.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  b.  Save button \\xE2\\x80\\x93 offers Save and Save and Close options\\r\\n\\\n  c.  Cancel \\xE2\\x80\\x93 cancels user out of timecard and returns them to prior navigation\\r\\n\\\n  d.  Submit button \\xE2\\x80\\x93 enabled on the Timecard Review page, it  will allow the user to submit the timecard.  Once the timecard is successfully submitted, the user will get a confirmation pop-up that the timecard has been successfully submitted and will have an option to print (a read-only review page of the timecard) or click OK.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\t\\r\\n\\\n  Open Design Issue:  Save button, whether the label can be \\xE2\\x80\\x9CSave as Draft\\xE2\\x80\\x9D. UX noted it should be Save to be consistent with other HCM applications.\\r\\n\"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 22:35:32'),(6870,'Feature',1463,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"\"\nname: Additional Information Sections - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-05-02 12:52:18 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-05 21:25:29 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1463\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Additional Reference information on the timecard include the following fields, with these display options discussed with UX:\\r\\n\\\n  a.\\tTimecard Comments \\xE2\\x80\\x93 comments for the overall timecard.  This section is currently displayed in the prototype as an open text field above the timecard matrix, so it is always open.\\r\\n\\\n  b.\\tAccrual Balances \\xE2\\x80\\x93 listing balances for all leave plans the worker is associated to.  The two options agreed upon were either show:\\r\\n\\\n  \\xEF\\x81\\xB6\\tAccrual Balance display open in the contextual section of the timecard, balance display provided by Absence Management\\r\\n\\\n  \\xEF\\x81\\xB6\\tOpen section in local area of the timecard, showing just 2 accrual balances, with a MORE link, to view all accrual balances in a pop-up page.\\r\\n\\\n  c.\\tApproval Comments \\xE2\\x80\\x93 comments from each timecard approver. This section should only be displayed if data exists.  If the timecard has not been routed for approval as of yet, the Approval Comments section or dialog box should not be displayed.  If there are Approval Comments, as the user enters the page, the Approval Comments message listing should pop-up like the Error Message listing does.  It should always be available to the user to re-access if they close the approval comments.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Configuration Options:   These configuration options were previously discussed for Time Entry Page Composer, please see above options for latest recommendations from UX.\\r\\n\\\n  \\xEF\\x81\\xB6\\tPop Up Information sections \\xE2\\x80\\x93 These sections of data can be presented via pop up pages from hyperlinks above the timecard matrix.  When the user clicks on the hyperlink, the related section will be in a pop-up page, which should be modeless, so the user can move the pop-up to another part of the timecard page, while being able to edit the timecard matrix.  This is especially important for the Approval Comment section, as the details of this pop-up will guide the user on what to address in the timecard matrix\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Example of  Additional Information Data links with pop-up page for Approval Comments:\\r\\n \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  \\xEF\\x81\\xB6\\tExpandable sections \\xE2\\x80\\x93  Another option for display of these sections is to show the data in expandable sections above the timecard matrix.  This is similar to current functionality in EBS OTL R12.  This design is for users who want the data displayed all the time.\\r\\n\"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 23:11:46'),(6871,'Feature',1463,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"\"\nname: Additional Information Sections - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-05-02 12:52:18 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 23:11:46 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1463\nfeature_type: \"\"\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Additional Reference information on the timecard include the following fields, with these display options discussed with UX:\\r\\n\\\n  a.\\tTimecard Comments \\xE2\\x80\\x93 comments for the overall timecard.  This section is currently displayed in the prototype as an open text field above the timecard matrix, so it is always open.\\r\\n\\\n  b.\\tAccrual Balances \\xE2\\x80\\x93 listing balances for all leave plans the worker is associated to.  The two options agreed upon were either show:\\r\\n\\\n  \\tAccrual Balance display open in the contextual section of the timecard, balance display provided by Absence Management\\r\\n\\\n  \\tOpen section in local area of the timecard, showing just 2 accrual balances, with a MORE link, to view all accrual balances in a pop-up page.\\r\\n\\\n  c.\\tApproval Comments \\xE2\\x80\\x93 comments from each timecard approver. This section should only be displayed if data exists.  If the timecard has not been routed for approval as of yet, the Approval Comments section or dialog box should not be displayed.  If there are Approval Comments, as the user enters the page, the Approval Comments message listing should pop-up like the Error Message listing does.  It should always be available to the user to re-access if they close the approval comments.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Configuration Options:   These configuration options were previously discussed for Time Entry Page Composer, please see above options for latest recommendations from UX.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Pop Up Information sections \\xE2\\x80\\x93 These sections of data can be presented via pop up pages from hyperlinks above the timecard matrix.  When the user clicks on the hyperlink, the related section will be in a pop-up page, which should be modeless, so the user can move the pop-up to another part of the timecard page, while being able to edit the timecard matrix.  This is especially important for the Approval Comment section, as the details of this pop-up will guide the user on what to address in the timecard matrix\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Example of  Additional Information Data links with pop-up page for Approval Comments:\\r\\n \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Expandable sections \\xE2\\x80\\x93  Another option for display of these sections is to show the data in expandable sections above the timecard matrix.  This is similar to current functionality in EBS OTL R12.  This design is for users who want the data displayed all the time.\\r\\n\"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 23:12:15'),(6872,'Feature',1463,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"\"\nname: Additional Information Sections - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-05-02 12:52:18 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 23:12:15 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1463\nfeature_type: \"\"\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Additional Reference information on the timecard include the following fields, with these display options discussed with UX:\\r\\n\\\n  a.\\tTimecard Comments \\xE2\\x80\\x93 comments for the overall timecard.  This section is currently displayed in the prototype as an open text field above the timecard matrix, so it is always open.\\r\\n\\\n  b.\\tAccrual Balances \\xE2\\x80\\x93 listing balances for all leave plans the worker is associated to.  The two options agreed upon were either show:\\r\\n\\\n  \\tAccrual Balance display open in the contextual section of the timecard, balance display provided by Absence Management\\r\\n\\\n  \\tOpen section in local area of the timecard, showing just 2 accrual balances, with a MORE link, to view all accrual balances in a pop-up page.\\r\\n\\\n  c.\\tApproval Comments \\xE2\\x80\\x93 comments from each timecard approver. This section should only be displayed if data exists.  If the timecard has not been routed for approval as of yet, the Approval Comments section or dialog box should not be displayed.  If there are Approval Comments, as the user enters the page, the Approval Comments message listing should pop-up like the Error Message listing does.  It should always be available to the user to re-access if they close the approval comments.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 23:13:24'),(6873,'Feature',1310,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Timecard Additional Information Sections - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:23 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 17:08:56 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1310\nfeature_type: \"\"\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 143\ndescription: \"Provide more real estate in the timecard page so the user can focus on the timecard matrix for time entry.  As a result, there\\r\\n\\\n  will be additional pieces of information that a user may want to\\r\\n\\\n  reference, but not view at all times. These sections should be \\\"information\\r\\n\\\n  on demand\\\", available to the user when needed.  Such sections include:\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  a.\\tTimecard Comments \\xE2\\x80\\x93 comments for the overall timecard.  This section is currently displayed in the prototype as an open text field above the timecard matrix, so it is always open.\\r\\n\\\n  b.\\tAccrual Balances \\xE2\\x80\\x93 listing balances for all leave plans the worker is associated to.  The two options agreed upon were either show:\\r\\n\\\n  >>\\tAccrual Balance display open in the contextual section of the timecard, balance display provided by Absence Management\\r\\n\\\n  >>\\tOpen section in local area of the timecard, showing just 2 accrual balances, with a MORE link, to view all accrual balances in a pop-up page.\\r\\n\\\n  d.\\tApproval Comments \\xE2\\x80\\x93 comments from each timecard approver. This section should only be displayed if data exists.  If the timecard has not been routed for approval as of yet, the Approval Comments section or dialog box should not be displayed.  If there are Approval Comments, as the user enters the page, the Approval Comments message listing should pop-up like the Error Message listing does.  It should always be available to the user to re-access if they close the approval comments.\\r\\n\"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 23:14:50'),(6874,'Feature',1533,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"\"\nname: Timecard Add\'l Info Sections Design - Pop up Sections\ncreated_at: 2011-05-30 21:34:41 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 21:36:02 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1533\nfeature_type: UI\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 174\ndescription: \"Configuration Options:   These configuration options were previously discussed for Time Entry Page Composer, please see above options for latest recommendations from UX.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  >>\\tPop Up Information sections \\xE2\\x80\\x93 These sections of data can be presented via pop up pages from hyperlinks above the timecard matrix.  When the user clicks on the hyperlink, the related section will be in a pop-up page, which should be modeless, so the user can move the pop-up to another part of the timecard page, while being able to edit the timecard matrix.  This is especially important for the Approval Comment section, as the details of this pop-up will guide the user on what to address in the timecard matrix\"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 23:15:34'),(6875,'Feature',1466,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"\"\nname: Timecard Add\'l Info Sections Design - Expandable Sections\ncreated_at: 2011-05-02 22:26:38 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 21:35:56 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1466\nfeature_type: UI\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 174\ndescription: \"Configuration Options:   These configuration options were previously discussed for Time Entry Page Composer, please see above options for latest recommendations from UX.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  >>\\tExpandable sections \\xE2\\x80\\x93  Another option for display of these sections is to show the data in expandable sections above the timecard matrix.  This is similar to current functionality in EBS OTL R12.  This design is for users who want the data displayed all the time.\"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 23:15:49'),(6876,'Feature',1359,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Timecard Access for Terminated Workers - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:23 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-25 19:58:14 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1359\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 167\ndescription: \"Must Have Justification :  Support time consumer needs to stop processing on terminated worker timecards\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  There will be different processing rules which users have with regards to viewing and updating timecards for terminated employees.  In most cases, workers cannot view, update, create or delete any timecards as of their last day of employment. \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  For timekeepers, managers or administrators who need to do further processing of timecards for terminated employees, they may have different dates up to which they can do any processing on terminated worker\\xE2\\x80\\x99s timecards. \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Feedback from payroll localization teams note that administrators (and sometimes his/her managers) should have timecard access up to Final Closing Date. Administrator access should be cut off once the final payment to the employee has been done but it should be dependent on internal regulations of employer, the final payment may be done even during 1 year after termination.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Core Pay will support the following three dates for the termination of a Payroll Relationship, Work Term or Assignment: \\r\\n\\\n  \\xE2\\x80\\xA2\\tLast Standard Earning Date (LSED) \\xE2\\x80\\x93 the date on which standard earnings are no longer accumulated. Typically in terminations the Actual Termination Date entered by HR. After the LSED, users can still pay someone a recurring element up to LSPD. \\r\\n\\\n  \\xE2\\x80\\xA2\\tLast Standard Process Date (LSPD) \\xE2\\x80\\x93 The last date on which the object (Payroll Relationship, Term, Assignment) is consider for normal processing in the Payroll Run. This date is defaulted from the LSED mentioned above but it can be overridden.  After the LSPD, users can only pay someone that has a non-recurring element. \\r\\n\\\n  \\xE2\\x80\\xA2\\tFinal Close Date (FCD) \\xE2\\x80\\x93 The date from which the object is no longer considered for processing, thus is datetrack ended. \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Currently in Projects (PPM) setup, there is a profile option which is \\xE2\\x80\\x9CSpecify Number of Days to Display People with Terminated Assignments\\xE2\\x80\\x9D which controls the display of people in various  PPM pages. \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  However, there is open discussion if Projects would want to use a final processing date which is available in Core HR.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  The ability to offer flexible setup options for different access needs is an open design issue being discussed with the Payroll and Projects (PPM) team.    This is an open design issue for setup in the Worker Core Processing Setup Profile\\r\\n\"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 23:17:03'),(6877,'Feature',1379,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Audit Trail on Time Cards Report - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-25 19:58:18 Z\npriority: Should Have\nid: 1379\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 167\ndescription: \"Should Have Justification: Support EBS R12.1 Enhancement \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  This report provides the complete history of timecards from its timecard submission to approval stages.  The report displays details such as the number of times a particular timecard is submitted, modified, or deleted, and various actions done by various employees, approvers on a particular timecard.  \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Reference:  (OTL_TC_Changes_Audit_Report_FDD_6675298_12.1.doc) design document for the design.\\r\\n\\\n  An alternate design option is to display an audit trail at the bottom of each timecard, listing the user, role, action taken and action date .  However, this type of audit cannot account for the deletion of timecards.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 23:18:34'),(6878,'Feature',1381,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Transfer of partial timecard to other applications - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-25 19:58:22 Z\npriority: Nice to Have\nid: 1381\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 167\ndescription: \"Nice to Have Justification:  Customer Request during Customer Feedback Sessions; Current Enterprise TL functionality of being able to pay what is valid\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Allow for option to transfer timecards differently for different worker groups.   For example, if one day is in error for a whole timecard period, user would want days which are correct to be transferred for exempt employees, but for biweekly staff they might want to hold all time in an errored timecard, since there are dependent rules that would execute.  This would be a change in the approval rules, in which only a portion of the timecard would be approved related to the non-errored time, whereas the errored time would not yet be approved.  Therefore a partially approved timecard would be transferred to one or more applications.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 23:20:04'),(6879,'Feature',1386,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Embedded Timecard in other Applications - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-25 19:58:26 Z\npriority: Nice to Have\nid: 1386\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 167\ndescription: |\n  Nice to Have Justification:  Requested Feature from Projects (PPM)\r\n  \r\n  Allow for the timecard to be embedded as a portlet in other applications such as the Project Team Member page in Project \r\n  \r\n  Portfolio Management, or other application dashboards which require time entry.  The related application validations will need to be associated to the portlet, as well as services to store the timecard updates and run relevant time-related rules. \r\n\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 23:21:20'),(6880,'Feature',1392,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: \"Worker Timecards Display: Timecards Portlet - Calendar - 3 months view\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-25 19:58:29 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1392\nfeature_type: \"\"\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 167\ndescription: \"Calendar View\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  There will be a view of timecards for the user to view and access\\r\\n his timecards from a calendar display.  There will be three months\\r\\n displayed at a time, with the ability to scroll to the next three\\r\\n or prior three months. Each timecard period will be highlighted on\\r\\n the calendar, and the user just needs to click on any date in that\\r\\n timecard period, and will be transferred to that timecard.\\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 23:22:14'),(6881,'Feature',1392,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: \"Worker Timecards Display: Timecards Portlet - Calendar - 3 months view\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 23:22:14 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1392\nfeature_type: UI\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 167\ndescription: \"Calendar View\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  There will be a view of timecards for the user to view and access his timecards from a calendar display.  There will be three months displayed at a time, with the ability to scroll to the next three or prior three months. Each timecard period will be highlighted on the calendar, and the user just needs to click on any date in that timecard period, and will be transferred to that timecard.\\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 23:23:01'),(6882,'Feature',1394,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Adoption of 3 Tier Levels of Fusion Employment Model - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-25 19:58:33 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1394\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 167\ndescription: \"<pre>To provide the ability to report time at any of the 3 levels\\n of employment: Work Relationship, Employment terms or Assignments,\\n we need to provide these as components for the users to choose to\\n select for display on their timecard layouts.  Even if the user decides\\n to not to report to the assignment level, it is critical to know\\n that we will always store the reported time in the primary assignment\\n level.\\n\\n\\\n  In our retrieval processes with existing applications such as Project\\n Portfolio Management and Payroll, we need to provide the levels of\\n time reporting that the customer needs, so we need to derive the\\n highest to lowest level of detail when transferring the time data.\\n\\n\\\n  In our timecard validation processes, we also need to validate to\\n the correct employment levels as well, depending on what has been\\n allowed for in the application validation rules.</pre>\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-30 23:25:01'),(6883,'Feature',1333,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Inline Error Messages - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:23 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-30 06:53:07 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1333\nfeature_type: \"\"\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 144\ndescription: |\n  Allow for easy inline error messages for invalid time, with indications on the reported cells.  The inline error messaging should allow for the highlighting of any field in the timecard matrix, including a particular entry of hours or Start/Stop times.  \r\n  \r\n  Offer a \"Show Messages\" button as a way to get the \"error message list\" dialog . Also, the user will have the dialog box open when they access the timecard entry page if there are existing errors.   We may not need the Show Messages button, if user clicks on each highlighted field the message display will pop-up again.   Will also have the dialog expanded when selecting the  Next button, if error messages still exist.\r\n  \r\n  If the user clicks on the message link and is taken to the line in error, he should always be able to access the error message listing dialog, to view all messages again.\r\n\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-31 16:43:49'),(6884,'Feature',1304,'destroy','3','--- \nscope: \"1.0\"\nname: Employment Header - Primary Assignment - jf\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:23 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-03 21:24:28 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1304\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 31\ndescription: \"Primary Assignment \\xE2\\x80\\x93 The display of the timecard page will be derived from the layout set and timecard period associated to a worker on his Worker Web Time Entry Setup Profile.  This Profile will be assigned to a worker via Group, based on the common component Group functionality.  The connection between the Worker Web Time Entry Setup Profile and group eligibility will be based on the worker\\xE2\\x80\\x99s primary assignment.  Since the eligibility is based on primary assignment only, the Assignment label should denote in the header that this is the \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cprimary assignment\\xE2\\x80\\x9D header information.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  In this way, the person accessing the timecard will understand from which assignment the employment  header is based, and also not to expect display of additional employment header information from other assignments.  The entry of time (entries in the timecard matrix) does support multiple assignments and allows the user to report time against any assignment\\r\\n      \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-31 16:44:45'),(6885,'FunctionalWorkUnit',178,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:03:52'),(6886,'Feature',1534,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:04:05'),(6887,'Feature',1535,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:04:16'),(6888,'Feature',1536,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:08:42'),(6889,'Feature',1536,'update','3','--- \nscope: \nname: Start Page\ncreated_at: 2011-05-31 19:08:42 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-31 19:08:42 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1536\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 178\ndescription: \niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-31 19:12:13'),(6890,'Feature',1534,'update','3','--- \nscope: \nname: Basic Search\ncreated_at: 2011-05-31 19:04:05 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-31 19:04:05 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1534\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 178\ndescription: \niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-31 19:17:48'),(6891,'Feature',1535,'update','3','--- \nscope: \nname: Advanced Search\ncreated_at: 2011-05-31 19:04:16 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-31 19:04:16 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1535\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 178\ndescription: \niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-31 19:19:48'),(6892,'Feature',1537,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:21:08'),(6893,'BusinessArea',224,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:22:01'),(6894,'FunctionalWorkUnit',178,'update','3','--- \nname: Layout Set Composer - Search / Results\ncreated_at: 2011-05-31 19:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-31 19:03:52 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 222\nid: 178\nparent_id: \niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-31 19:22:14'),(6895,'FunctionalWorkUnit',179,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:23:08'),(6896,'Feature',1536,'update','3','--- \nscope: \"\"\nname: Start Page - General Look\ncreated_at: 2011-05-31 19:08:42 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-31 19:20:57 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1536\nfeature_type: UI\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 178\ndescription: \"Initial Page layout:\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Search / Results with table displaying results.\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Search is in local panel - with Basic / Advanced search options\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Table has columns for Layout Set Name, Description, etc,\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Table has toolbar for Table actions : Create, Delete, Edit, Duplicate.  \"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-31 19:23:19'),(6897,'FunctionalWorkUnit',180,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:23:50'),(6898,'Feature',1537,'update','3','--- \nscope: \nname: Results Table\ncreated_at: 2011-05-31 19:21:08 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-31 19:21:08 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1537\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 178\ndescription: \niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-31 19:23:53'),(6899,'BusinessArea',225,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:28:55'),(6900,'FunctionalWorkUnit',181,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:29:21'),(6901,'FunctionalWorkUnit',182,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:29:31'),(6902,'FunctionalWorkUnit',183,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:29:47'),(6903,'BusinessArea',226,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:31:13'),(6904,'BusinessArea',227,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:31:49'),(6905,'BusinessArea',228,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:34:11'),(6906,'BusinessArea',229,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:37:18'),(6907,'BusinessArea',230,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:38:07'),(6908,'BusinessArea',231,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:38:37'),(6909,'BusinessArea',232,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:38:59'),(6910,'BusinessArea',233,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:39:22'),(6911,'BusinessArea',234,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:39:40'),(6912,'BusinessArea',235,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:39:58'),(6913,'BusinessArea',236,'create','3',NULL,'2011-05-31 19:40:23'),(6914,'Feature',1272,'destroy','8','--- \nscope: Post 2.0\nname: \"Lunar Month Option \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\npriority: Nice to Have\nid: 1272\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \"\\n                  To support Lunar month option as payroll, we are giving an option to create 4 weeks period but not real Lunar month(29 day, 12 hours and 44 minutes) \\n                  Real Lunar Month capability -- Feature Release.\\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-05-31 20:09:58'),(6915,'Feature',1273,'destroy','8','--- \nscope: Post 2.0\nname: \"Cutoff Date \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\npriority: Nice to Have\nid: 1273\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \"\\n                  <dt>Description:</dt>\\n                  <dd>John raised the possibility of allowing the customer to define a cutoff date for each recurring period. Whilst we do not know the eventual use of a \\n                  repeating period when its defined a cutoff date that was simply used for reporting purposes might not be an issue.<dd> \\n                  <dd>02-DEC-2009 MarkV: Please remind John/Sue about this and ask them if they have come to a conclusion. Also, I would like to know what this cutoff date would be used \\n                  for in OTL. BTW, this functionality is also present in the Payroll Period, again bringing our Period LBA closer to the Payroll Period module, making the need to \\n                  merge them into one HCM application even more useful.</dd> \\n                 <dt> 12/7/09 Sue - Timecard Submission Date/Time Purposes</dt>    \\n                  <dd>   List Date Time the timecard is due on the timecard  </dd>                          \\n                  <dd>   Monitor late timecards which have not yet been submitted compared to due date  </dd>                           \\n                  <dd>   Send notification reminders before due date/time to the employee            </dd>                \\n                  <dd>  Time should be an optional field, some just have submission dates, some use date and time   </dd> \\n                                  \\n                  <dt>5.  A competitive feature UI Suggestions:</dt>          \\n                  <dd>Borrow from Payroll\'s payroll definition with offsets to define cutoff date (# of days on/before/after time period start or end date), \\n                  with ability to override the date.</dd>\\n                  <dd>Determine if we can import payroll definition with regards to period duration, period instances and period cut off date.</dd>                             \\n                  <p>Reference:Payroll Definition FDD from Payroll Next Step to Resolve: John to talk to Sue and propose the details of how a cutoff \\n                  date would be defined for all the period types and propose UI.</p>\\n                  <p>2/11/10 - Action to Sue to write up the reasons for cutoff date and where it would be placed and how the customers would use it and then followup with meeting to discuss with all.</p>                        \\n                  Timecard Submission Due Date.doc   - sent to all interested parties on 2/27/2010 - Sue \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-05-31 20:10:01'),(6916,'Feature',1274,'destroy','8','--- \nscope: Post 2.0\nname: \"Offset \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\npriority: Nice to Have\nid: 1274\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \"\\n                     <dt>Description:</dt>\\n                     <dd>Enterprise had the concept of  off set in their repeating period definition, do we need this concept in fusion?  (Sue)\\n                        Offset in Daily Time Period in Enterprise: used for Rolling Periods.  Rolling periods can have overlapping period instances if the offset is negative or there can be \\n                        jumps in period instances if the offset is positive. \\\"Enter the number of offset days. Offset days are used to derive the start date of the next period instance with \\n                        respect to the end date of previous instance. Offsets can be positive or negative. The default for offset days is 1. </dd>\\n                        <dd>If the offset is a negative number, the system counts backwards from the end of the earlier period instance by the number of offset days to determine the start of the next period instance. Any two \\n                        consecutive period instances will overlap if the offset is negative. The absolute value of offset days cannot be equal to or greater than the period length. \\n                        In other words, when the offset days number is negative, the next period cannot start on or before the current period. \\\"\\n                        Rolling periods are for rules processing only, not for time reporting.</dd>\\n                     <dd>Suggestion:  we could offer different  period types: rule period (which allow for offsets) versus time reporting and approval periods whch do not allow offsets. \\n                        Or we can invoke business logic when assigning reporting periods or approval periods, that they cannot assign periods with offsets.</dd>\\n                     <dd>Mitul: 07 Dec, 2009 - Are we going to support only the definition of rolling period given in Issue 16 below? \\n                        How are we going to incorporate support for Rolling Period and Off Set in our UI? We need to remember Overlapping Period also when we talk about Off Set. \\n                        All these three goes hand in hand.</dd>\\n                     <dt>Next Step to Resolve:</dt>\\n                     <dd>Talk to John/Sue 02-DEC-2009 MarkV: Please remind John and Sue. Also, please find out what this does in E and note that on this LBA somewhere </dd>\\n                     <dd>2/11/10 - Do not think it is a priority for v2, will schedule a meeting to discuss this with team, along with item 16, and 17. - Sue)</dd>\\n                     <dd>2/26/2010 - Met on 2/25/2010 with Joel, Mark, Kavitha, Andy, John, Faz on rolling periods and offsets today - We cannot determine requirements for overlapping time periods or period instances which skip days.  I have emailed Anton Graaf today to ask him if there are localzation requirements in rules or elsewhere which require the concept of overlapping periods or periods with skips of days.  \\n                     Most likely this will be scoped out for Fusion v2 unless there are compelling use cases. - Sue</dd>\\n                     <dt>Resolution:</dt>\\n                     <dd>3/10/2010 - have not heard from Anton Graaf at all, as of now no requirement in hand to use offset for period definition for Fusion v2- Sue</dd>\\n                  \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-05-31 20:10:04'),(6917,'Feature',1275,'destroy','8','--- \nscope: Post 2.0\nname: \"9-80 \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\npriority: Nice to Have\nid: 1275\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \"\\n                  <p>9-80 implementation will have an impact on the repeating period adding \'time\' to time period definition, dependent on our 9/80 scheduling/time entry \\n                  requirements 02-DEC-2009.  MarkV: This will actually be handled differently now and does not require these \'time aware periods\' anymore so we can close this. </p>\\n                  <dt>Next Step to Resolve:</dt>  \\n                  <dd>Cover in the 9-80 FDD 2/11/10 - Joel checking with Mark on why we don\'t need time for 9/80 requirements on the time period? - Sue </dd>                      \\n                  <dt>Resolution: </dt>\\n                  <dd>We do not need time aware periods anymore. Faz: At this point 9/80 is not in the V2 scope. but development should have design consideration for that                          \\n                    Sue - are we doing anything for this right now?</dd>\\n                               \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-05-31 20:10:09'),(6918,'Feature',1276,'destroy','8','--- \nscope: Post 2.0\nname: \"Overlapping Period \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\npriority: Nice to Have\nid: 1276\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \"\\n                    <dt>Description:</dt>\\n                    <dd> From your previous e-mail, I understand that we will have overlapping period if the offset is negative (and The maximum number of negative offset days \\n                    cannot exceed the period length minus two) and gap into the period when the offset is positive. It becomes interesting when an rolling period is defined \\n                    with an offset First you have to confirm if we will be using offset in Fusion V1.1</dd>                          \\n                    <dd>After the use of the repeating periods with offset, I would like to understand if a timecard or approval period could be set on a period with offset, \\n                    or it is exclusively for rules. Are we generating such period? </dd>                            \\n                    <dd>16-OCT-2008: Andy: I am curious about this offset idea. You are basically trying to set up some kind of structure to the repeating periods. \\n                    I am wondering why, if this is needed, why other things arent, say a 5 day period followed by a 4 day period etc. If we are going to get into this \\n                    kind of complex period definition I think we should just come up with something that allows for any kind of repetition .. . \\n                    danger is that it starts to be a calendar.  </dd>                        \\n                  <dt>Next Step to Resolve: </dt>                           \\n                    <dd>Sue/John/Andy/Mark - Sue:  This issue is linked to Issue 9, once we resolve issue 9, this is resolved as well.  \\n                    An overlapping period does not exist without an offset principle. Overlapping periods would only be for rules and not for time entry or approvals. -                              \\n                    Rolling periods and complex periods are period types supported in Enterprise TL currently.  - 2/26/2010 </dd>                                                \\n                  <dt>Resolution:</dt> \\n                  <dd>3/10/2010 - have not heard from Anton Graaf at all, as of now no requirement in hand to use offset for period definition for Fusion v2- Sue\\\" </dd>\\n                  \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-05-31 20:10:12'),(6919,'Feature',1279,'destroy','8','--- \nscope: Post 2.0\nname: \"Do we need repeating periods at all  \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\npriority: Nice to Have\nid: 1279\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \"\\n                  <dt>Description:</dt>                  \\n                      <dd>Can we use something like the ZMM schedule instead of owning our own periods or try to get the payroll / OTL models merged.</dd>                       \\n                      <dd>16-OCT-08: Feedback from Sue ... you could think of periods as calendars / schedules. Problem is that you could NOT use ZMM as it stands </dd>                            \\n                      <dd>01-DEC-2009 (MarkV): I think we can definitely dismiss the idea of using ZMM, however, I would like us to expand on the idea of using other \\n                      Application\'s periods implementations.</dd>\\n                     <dd> What would be really cool is if in our Period LBA we can point to other applications\' periods. For example, we should be able to define a period as a \\n                     \'Payroll Period\'. </dd>                             \\n                      <dd>All the information of this period is held in payroll, we just reference it in our Period LBA and provide services/APIs to retrieve the periods as needed.</dd>                              \\n                      <dd>Even nicer would be if we can define an \'(Primary) Assignment Payroll Period\' which in essence would link to the Assignment\'s Payroll Period rather than a \\n                      fixed Payroll Period.  </dd>                            \\n                      <dd>We could then use this throughout the product and base e.g. a Timecard Period on the \'Assignment Payroll Period\' which would mean that the Timecard Period \\n                      differs per person because different assignments have different Payroll Periods assigned to them. This way we can define our own periods \\n                      (if we would still need to do this because most of the periods we define exist in Payroll already) and reference any other period in HCM (or even outside). \\n                      Can you please investigate this? </dd>                        \\n                      <dd>Mitul: 03 Dec, 2009 - Payroll Period- Prototype , Live , FDD AdfHcmPayPublicModel.jar contains the related public objects. Finding more information on \\n                      \'Assignment Payroll Period\'. </dd>                        \\n                      <dd>Mitul: 07 Dec, 2009 - Time Defintion - Prototype , Live </dd>                            \\n                      <dd>Mitul: 09 Dec, 2009 - Additional features Payroll Time Definitions provides: Defintion Type : Time Span Takes user input to know whether the periods \\n                      should be generated for past or future and the amount of units to generate ( 7 Days, 2 Weeks, 1 Month, 10 Years ). Allows negative and positive \\n                      adjustments in days to the periods.  </dd>                           \\n                      <dd>Defintion Type : Static Period Takes user input for number of years to be generated. Features Payroll Time Definitions doesn\'t provide: I could not \\n                      see any support for Lunar Calendar.  For us, we always ask for a Reference date, while for them it is always centered to the current date \\n                      (except when the definition type is User Defined Date) We provide more flexibility to allow more user control on how periods get generated. \\n                      For e.g. when type is Multiple Months we allow them to select Start Month and Day. While we can fetch Payroll Time Definition to generate our periods, \\n                      we may not want it to be completely replaced by Payroll Time Definition. Additionally, we can fetch cut-off date/offsets from Payroll Period Definition.</dd>\\n                  <dt>Next step to Resolve: </dt>\\n                     <dd>\\n                      Ask Joel to investigate - though probably difficult to get interest in this from v1  teams at the moment 16-OCT-08: Plan is to bring this up in the Leadership Circle.\\n                      Definitely suggest central entity for HCM. For apps? May talk about periods as schedules / calendars. </dd>                      \\n                  <dt>Resolution: </dt>\\n                  <dd> For V2 we will go with our solution. </dd>\\n                                     \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-05-31 20:11:02'),(6920,'Feature',1278,'destroy','8','--- \nscope: Post 2.0\nname: \"Persistence of Time Periods \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\npriority: Nice to Have\nid: 1278\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \"\\n                  <dt>Description:</dt>\\n                  <dd>Do we need to move to a payroll-style period model where we store time periods instead of generating them as needed </dd>                                          \\n                  <dt>Next step to Resolve: </dt>\\n                     <dd>Andy: Need to collect period requirements. Where are periods needed and is storage of periods essential? </dd>                      \\n                  <dt>Resolution: </dt>\\n                  <dd>16-OCT-08:We will generate periods and store them. This makes it easier when using payroll balances. It will probably also be helpful as periods become more \\n                  complex</dd>\\n                  <dd>post 1.1 .. offsets .. time component and custom periods where the dates are simply listed out by the customer. </dd>\\n                    \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-05-31 20:12:19'),(6921,'Feature',1277,'destroy','8','--- \nscope: Post 2.0\nname: \"Dependency on PER_TIME_PERIOD_TYPES  \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\npriority: Nice to Have\nid: 1277\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \"\\n                  <dt>Description:</dt> \\n                  <dd>We need to think about the solution we are providing. In the long run it would seem to make sense to centralize time period definitions and generation in HCM or apps and not \\n                    in specific products (payroll / OTL).</dd>\\n                    <dd>Since payroll is in the same pillar we could continue to have this dependency on period type or simply hard code the period types into the evaluation \\n                    code for performance reasons (we have NEVER had a request for a new period and since these come from payroll I imagine they have never seen such a request either) 02-DEC-2009 \\n                    MarkV: More indications of the similarities between this and Payroll Periods ...  </dd>                         \\n                  <dt>Next Step to Resolve:</dt>\\n                  <dd>Talk to Joel about it </dd>                                            \\n                  <dt>Resolution:  </dt>\\n                  <dd>We will not have any dependencies on per_time_period_types. </dd>\\n                  \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-05-31 20:12:22'),(6922,'FunctionalWorkUnit',184,'create','8',NULL,'2011-05-31 20:16:02'),(6923,'FunctionalWorkUnit',185,'create','8',NULL,'2011-05-31 20:16:47'),(6924,'Feature',1268,'destroy','8','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: \"Create Repeating Time Period \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1268\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \"\\n                  \'Create\' action or \'Create\' button from the Search Results grid are used to create new repeating periods. \\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-05-31 20:16:57'),(6925,'Feature',1269,'destroy','8','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: \"Edit Repeating Time Period \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1269\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \"\\n                  Only the name of the repeating period can be edited, other fields are read only fields.\\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-05-31 20:17:04'),(6926,'Feature',1270,'destroy','8','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: \"Key logic for Repeating Period \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1270\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \"\\n                   User cannot delete existing Repeating Period.\\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-05-31 20:18:59'),(6927,'Feature',1271,'destroy','8','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: \"Translation \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1271\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \"\\n                   Period Name and Period Description fields are translatable.\\n                  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-05-31 20:19:02'),(6928,'Feature',1538,'create','8',NULL,'2011-05-31 20:19:20'),(6929,'Feature',1538,'update','8','--- \nscope: \nname: Translation\ncreated_at: 2011-05-31 20:19:20 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-31 20:19:20 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1538\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 184\ndescription: \niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-31 20:19:53'),(6930,'Feature',1539,'create','8',NULL,'2011-05-31 20:20:40'),(6931,'Feature',1539,'update','8','--- \nscope: \nname: Page Actions\ncreated_at: 2011-05-31 20:20:40 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-31 20:20:40 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1539\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-31 20:23:19'),(6932,'Feature',1539,'update','8','--- \nscope: \"Create and Edit -  Toolbar Actions\\t\\t\\t\"\nname: Page Actions\ncreated_at: 2011-05-31 20:20:40 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-31 20:23:19 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1539\nfeature_type: UI\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \"Create - When using the \\xE2\\x80\\x9Ccreate\\xE2\\x80\\x9D action or \\xE2\\x80\\x9Ccreate\\xE2\\x80\\x9D button from the Search Results grid, a user will be able to add a new repeating period\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Edit - Only the name of a repeating period can be edited, the other fields will be grayed out in read only mode, to protect the period.  This is because the period is \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  NO DELETE ACTION - repeating periods cannot be deleted.\"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-31 20:26:38'),(6933,'Feature',1539,'update','8','--- \nscope: \"1\"\nname: Page Actions\ncreated_at: 2011-05-31 20:20:40 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-31 20:26:38 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1539\nfeature_type: UI\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \"Create and Edit -  Toolbar Actions\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Create - When using the \\xE2\\x80\\x9Ccreate\\xE2\\x80\\x9D action or \\xE2\\x80\\x9Ccreate\\xE2\\x80\\x9D button from the Search Results grid, a user will be able to add a new repeating period\\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  Edit - Only the name of a repeating period can be edited, the other fields will be grayed out in read only mode, to protect the period.  This is because the period is \\r\\n\\\n  \\r\\n\\\n  NO DELETE ACTION - repeating periods cannot be deleted.\"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-31 20:27:17'),(6934,'Feature',1265,'destroy','8','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Basic Search page for Repeating Time Periods\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1265\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \"\\n        <p>User can search Repeating Periods using this feature </p>\\n        <p>Basic search is performed using \'Name\' or \'Period Type\' search fields of the period.  Based on the user input system will run a query to the tables and display the period \\n        information in search restuls grid.</p> \\n        \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-05-31 20:36:34'),(6935,'Feature',1266,'destroy','8','--- \nscope: \"2.0\"\nname: Advanced Search page for Repeating Time Periods\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:38:22 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1266\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 132\ndescription: \"\\n                    <p>Lets the user execute advanced queries based on logical operators and wildcards.</p>                     \\n                    <dt>Search can be executed using the following parameters</dt>\\n                    <dd>Name : Name of the Period, it is a text box</dd>\\n                    <dd>Period Type : Type of the period, It is List of Values field with Daily, Weekly, Monthly, Semi-Monthly types.</dd>\\n                    <dd>Description : Description of the period is text box</dd>\\n                    <dd>Start Date : Start date of the period it is a date column</dd>\\n                    <dd>Duration in Days : Period length in days is number field.</dd>                    \\n                    Also allows wildcards in Name and Description based search</ol>\\n                   \\n        \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-05-31 20:36:44'),(6936,'Feature',1540,'create','8',NULL,'2011-05-31 20:37:01'),(6937,'Feature',1541,'create','8',NULL,'2011-05-31 20:38:12'),(6938,'Feature',1542,'create','8',NULL,'2011-05-31 20:38:23'),(6939,'Feature',1543,'create','8',NULL,'2011-05-31 20:38:59'),(6940,'Feature',1541,'update','8','--- \nscope: \nname: Define Time Period\ncreated_at: 2011-05-31 20:38:12 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-31 20:38:31 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1541\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 184\ndescription: \niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-31 20:41:01'),(6941,'Feature',1544,'create','8',NULL,'2011-05-31 20:41:24'),(6942,'Feature',1544,'update','8','--- \nscope: \nname: Define Time Period - Type Additional Questions\ncreated_at: 2011-05-31 20:41:24 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-31 20:41:24 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1544\nfeature_type: \nfunctional_work_unit_id: 184\ndescription: \niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-31 20:48:56'),(6943,'Feature',1538,'update','8','--- \nscope: Name and Description are Translatable, may display in timecard header.\nname: Translation\ncreated_at: 2011-05-31 20:19:20 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-05-31 20:19:53 Z\npriority: Must Have\nid: 1538\nfeature_type: Miscellaneous\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 184\ndescription: \"\"\niteration_id: 1\n','2011-05-31 20:49:24'),(6944,'Feature',1542,'upda